|first=John J|title=Manchester: an Architectural History|year=2000|publisher=Manchester University Press|ref=harv|isbn=0-7190-5606-3}}\n*{{cite book | title= Farewell Manchester: history of Manchester Racecourse |last=Ramsden|first=Caroline | year= 1966 | publisher=J A Allen & Co|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Joe|last=Ravetz|year=2000|title=City-Region 2020|publisher=Earthscan|isbn=978-1-85383-606-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book | title= English local government reformed | last1=Redcliffe-Maud|first1=John | first2= Bruce|last2=Wood |authorlink= John Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud | year= 1975 | publisher=OUP|ref=harv| isbn= 0-19-885091-3 }}\n*{{cite book | last=Redcliffe-Maud|first=John| authorlink= John Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud|title= Royal Commission on Local Government in England 1966\u20131969, Volume I: Report (Cmnd.&nbsp;4040) |date=June 1969 | publisher=HMSO|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book | last = Redhead | first = Brian | title = Manchester: a Celebration | authorlink = Brian Redhead | publisher=Andre Deutsch Ltd|ref=harv| year = 1993 | isbn = 0-233-98816-5}}\n*{{cite book |last=Rochdale Metropolitan Borough Council|title=Metropolitan Rochdale Official Guide|publisher=Ed. J. Burrow & Co. Limited|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=City Life: Manchester the Complete Guide |last=Schofield|first=Jonathan|year=2003|publisher=City Life |isbn=978-0-9544460-0-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Manchester: the complete guide 2007 |last=Schofield|first=Jonathan |year=2007 |publisher=City Life|ref=harv|isbn=<!--ain't one-->}}\n*{{cite book|title=A Tale of Two Cities: Global Change, Local Feeling, and Everyday Life in the North of England: a Study in Manchester and Sheffield|last1=Taylor|first1=Ian|last2=Evans|first2=Karen|last3=Fraser|first3=Penny|publisher=Routledge|year=1996|isbn=978-0-415-13828-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Regional Imperative: Regional Planning and Governance in Britain, Europe and the United States|last= Wannop|first=Urlan |year=2002|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-11-702368-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Local Government in the United Kingdom|last1= Wilson|first1=David|last2=Game|first2=Chris|year=2002|edition=3rd|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-333-94859-0}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Greater Manchester}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Greater Manchester}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051026152244/http://www.agma.gov.uk/ www.agma.gov.uk], the [[Association of Greater Manchester Authorities]]\n*[http://www.gmcro.co.uk/ www.gmcro.co.uk], the [[Greater Manchester County Record Office]], for historical records relating to Greater Manchester\n*[https://www.visitmanchester.com/ www.visitmanchester.com], the official tourism website for Greater Manchester\n*{{curlie|Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom/England/Manchester}}\n{{Greater Manchester}}\n\n{{England_counties}}\n{{NW_England}}\n{{Metropolitan counties}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Greater Manchester| ]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan counties]]\n[[Category:NUTS 2 statistical regions of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Counties of England established in 1974]]\n", "name_user": "Schiavo59", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting the assertion that the conurbation is landlocked which overlooks that the opening of the Manchester Ship Canal 1n 1894 made Manchester an important seaport the third busiest port in the uk by tonnage in the 1950s.The 26 mile seaway still operates as a seaport with regular calls from international shipping up to 12k tonnes to ignore this in any description of Greater Manchester is a major oversight", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greater_Manchester"}
{"title_page": "Heiner Goebbels", "text_new": "'''Heiner Goebbels''' (born 17 August 1952) is a [[Germany|German]] [[composer]], [[Artistic director|director]] and professor at [[University of Giessen|Justus-Liebig-University]] in [[Gie\u00dfen]] and artistic director of the International Festival of the Arts [[Ruhrtriennale]] 2012\u201314.\n\n== Biography ==\nGoebbels was born in [[Neustadt an der Weinstra\u00dfe]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=22 February 2001 |title=Heiner Goebbels |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/biogramm-heiner-goebbels-11267359.html |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |location=Frankfurt |language=de |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> Goebbels, who studied sociology and music in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]],<ref name=OTB>Program for Pacific Musicworks / Seattle Chamber Players performance of Heiner Goebbels ''Songs of Wars I Have Seen'', On the Boards, Seattle, March 4\u20136, 2010.</ref> is a composer of ensemble works and compositions for large orchestra. He has created several prize-winning radio plays, staged concerts, and, since the early 1990s, music theatre works, which have been invited to the most important theatre and music festivals worldwide.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nGoebbels and [[Alfred Harth]] were musical partners in the [[Duo Goebbels/Harth]] (1975-1988) who co-founded the wind band [[Sogenanntes Linksradikales Blasorchester]] (1976-1981) and the [[avant-rock]] [[Musical ensemble|group]] [[Cassiber]] (1982\u20131992) with [[Alfred Harth]], [[Chris Cutler]] and [[Christoph Anders]]. They toured extensively across [[Europe]], [[Asia]] and [[North America]], and made five albums. In October 1983 Cassiber (minus Anders) joined [[Duck and Cover (German band)|Duck and Cover]],  commissioned for the 1983 [[Moers Festival]] at the request of festival director Burkhard Hennen to Alfred Harth, followed by a performance at the [[Berlin Jazz Festival]] in [[West Berlin]],  and by another in February 1984 in [[East Berlin]].\n\nSome of his better-known work originated from his close collaboration with the [[East Germany|East German]] writer [[Heiner M\u00fcller]], resulting in stage compositions as well as shorter pieces (concerts as well as audio plays) based on M\u00fcller texts,<ref name=OTB /> such as ''Verkommenes Ufer'' (Waste Shore, 1984), ''Die Befreiung des Prometheus'' (The Liberation of Prometheus, 1985), or ''Wolokolamsker Chaussee'' (Volokolamsk Highway, 1989).{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} \nGoebbels' attempts to fill the space between theatre and opera left blank due to traditional genre borderline drawing{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} has led to projects such as \"''Ou bien le d\u00e9barquement d\u00e9sastreux''\" (Paris 1993), ''Schwarz auf Weiss'' (Black on White, 1996)<ref name=OTB /> and ''Die Wiederholung'' (The Repetition, 1995).{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} The political nature of his work is often referred to by critics.{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} His interest in Heiner M\u00fcller can partly be explained by the political character of M\u00fcller's texts, as may be the case with his interest in [[Bertolt Brecht]] and [[Hanns Eisler]], works by the latter he used in composing his staged concert ''Eislermaterial'' (1998).{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} \n1998 he also created the music theatre play \"Max Black\" with words by [[Paul Valery]] and others, in 2000 \"Hashirigaki\" after [[Gertrude Stein]], 2002 his first opera \"Landscape with distant relatives\", 2004 the price winning \"Eraritjaritjaka\" with words by [[Elias Canetti]], followed 2007 by the performative installation \"Stifters Dinge\" which has been performed more than 300 times in four continents. 2007 followed the staged concert \"Songs of Wars I have seen\" with words by [[Gertrude Stein]] - a commission by the [[London Sinfonietta]] and the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]], 2008 \"I went to the House but did not enter\" with the [[Hilliard Ensemble]] and words by [[Maurice Blanchot]], [[Samuel Beckett]] a.o. In 2012 he created \"When the Mountain changed its clothing\" with the Choir Carmina Slovenica, and staged [[John Cage]]'s \"Europeras 1&2\" 2012 and [[Harry Partch]]'s ''[[Delusion of the Fury]]'' 2013 and [[Louis Andriessen]]'s [[De Materie]] for the [[Ruhrtriennale]] International Festival of the Arts.\n\nGoebbels' work is being increasingly acknowledged as he is being played and staged around the world and as his recordings are being published. He collaborated with the finest ensembles and orchestras - [[Ensemble Modern]], [[Ensemble Intercontemporain]], Ensemble [[musikFabrik]], [[Asko/Sch\u00f6nberg]], [[Berg Orchestra]], [[Berlin Philharmonic]], [[Bochumer Symphoniker]], Junge Deutsche Philharmonie, [[Brooklyn Philharmonic]] and many others and worked with conductors like Sir [[Simon Rattle]], [[Peter Eotvos]], [[Lothar Zagrosek]], [[Peter Rundel]], [[Steven Sloane]] and many others.  In 2000 he collaborated with [[Piano Circus]] and composer [[Richard Harris (composer)|Richard Harris]] to produce ''Scutigeras'', which received a live BBC radio premiere in the UK. \nHis ''Surrogate Cities'', a work for big orchestra dating from 1994 and featuring texts from [[Paul Auster]], Heiner M\u00fcller, and [[Hugo Hamilton (writer)|Hugo Hamilton]], has been performed widely in Europe, the US and Australia and was nominated for a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] in the category [[Grammy Award for Best Classical Contemporary Composition|Best Classical Contemporary Composition]] at the [[Grammy Awards of 2001|43rd Grammy Awards in 2001]].<ref name=\"egs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.egs.edu/faculty/heiner-goebbels/biography/ | title=Heiner Goebbels Faculty Page at European Graduate School (Biography, bibliography and video lectures) | publisher=[[European Graduate School]] | author= | accessdate=2010-09-25}}</ref> His ''Eislermaterial'' won him another Grammy nomination at the [[Grammy Awards of 2004|46th Grammy Awards in 2004]], this time in the category [[Grammy Award for Best Small Ensemble Performance|Best Small Ensemble Performance (with or without conductor)]].<ref>[http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news_print.php?id=3058  ECM and its artists received eight nominations for the 46th Grammy Awards.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050226144201/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news_print.php?id=3058 |date=2005-02-26 }} ''All about jazz'', 2003-12-19.</ref>\n\nHis installative artwork \"Stifters Dinge - the Unguided Tour\" has been presented by [[Artangel]] in London (2012) and at the [[Ruhrtriennale]] in Duisburg (2013), \"Genko-An\" in Berlin (2008), [[Darmstadt Artists' Colony]]/Mathildenh\u00f6he (2012), [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Lyon]] (2014) and Moscow's NEW SPACE (2017). For the [[Centre Pompidou]] Paris he created the soundinstallations \"Fin de Soleil\" and \"Tim\u00e9e\"(2000) which was also exhibited at the [[ZKM]] Karlsruhe, the [[MACBA]] Barcelona, in Brugge and in Palazzo delle Esposizioni/Rome. He also closely collaborated on several videoinstallations with visual artist [[Michal Rovner]]. 1982, 1987 and 1997 he participated with concerts, installative works and performing arts at the [[documenta]] in Kassel\n\nGoebbels was a professor at Justus-Liebig-University in Gie\u00dfen, Institute for Applied Theater Studies from 1999 until 2018, and teaches the European Graduate School in Saas-Fee, Switzerland.<ref name=\"egs\" /> From 2006 until 2018 he was President of the Theater Academy of Hesse. In recent years Goebbels enjoyed the privilege of several guest professorships and nominations for composer-in-residence.,<ref name=OTB /> he is member of several academies of arts (Berlin, Bensheim, D\u00fcsseldorf, Mainz, Munich), Fellow of the Institute of Advanced Studies in Berlin, Honorable Fellow at the Dartington College of the Arts and the [[Central School of Speech and Drama]], London. In 2012 he was awarded an honorary doctorate by [[Birmingham City University]], in 2018 by the National Academy for Theatre and Film Arts in Sofia (Bulgaria).\n\nHe received numerous awards and honours, such as [[Prix Italia]], [[Europe Theatre Prize]], and 2012 the [[International Ibsen Award]], one of the world's most prestigious theatre awards, for bringing \"new artistic dimensions to the world of drama or theatre.\".\n\nIn September 2010, it was announced that Goebbels was the artistic director designate for the 2012-14 seasons of the [[Ruhrtriennale]].<ref>{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.ruhrtriennale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/pressemitteilung-24-09-10\n |title       = Heiner Goebbels is Artistic Director designate\n |publisher   = Ruhrtriennale\n |accessdate  = 2011-03-10\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101227073108/http://www.ruhrtriennale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/pressemitteilung-24-09-10/\n |archivedate = 2010-12-27\n}}</ref>\n{{clear}} As artistic director of this Festival Heiner Goebbels curated, produced and presented several new works by the artists [[Robert Wilson (director)|Robert Wilson]], [[Romeo Castellucci]], [[Michal Rovner]], [[Boris Charmatz]], [[Robert Lepage]], [[Jan Lauwers]], [[Ryoji Ikeda]], [[Douglas Gordon]], [[William Forsythe (choreographer)|William Forsythe]], [[Lemi Ponifasio]], [[Mathilde Monnier]], [[Saburo Teshigawara]], [[Anne Teresa de Keersmaeker]], [[Rimini Protokoll]], [[Tim Etchells]], [[Gregor Schneider]] and many others.\n\nHis latest work, ''Everything that happened and would happen'', was performed for the first time in October 2018 at [[Manchester Mayfield railway station|Mayfield Depot]] in [[Manchester]]. It explores the history of Europe since [[World War I]] and combines live music, performance and film <ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/09/from-bombsites-to-usain-bolt-manchester-relives-100-years-of-war-and-peace | title=From bombsites to Usain Bolt: Manchester relives 100 years of war and peace| newspaper=The Guardian| date=2018-10-09| last1=Connolly| first1=Kate}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/10/arts/heiner-goebels-everything-that-happened-manchester.html |title = 120 Years of European History, in 3 Disorienting Hours|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2018-10-10|last1 = G\u00fcner|first1 = Fisun}}</ref>\n\n== Works (Selection) ==\n\n=== Stage works ===\n* ''When the Mountain Changed Its Clothing'' (2012) Music theatre for a girl's choir. Text: Jean Jaques Rousseau, Gertrude Stein, Adalbert Stifter, Alain Robe-Grillet and others\n* ''I went to the house but did not enter'' (2008) Scenic concert in three pictures for four male voices. Text: T.S. Eliot, Maurice Blanchot, Samuel Beckett, Franz Kafka\n* ''Stifters Dinge'' (2007) Installative Performance \n* ''Eraritjaritjaka - mus\u00e9e de Phrases'' (2007) music theatre for actor and string quartett, words by Elias Canetti\n* ''Landschaft mit entfernten Verwandten'' (2002) Opera for ensemble, choir and soloists. Texts and motifs by Giordano Bruno, Arthur Chapman/Estelle Philleo, T.S. Eliot, Francois F\u00e9nelon, Michel Foucault and others\n* ''Hashirigaki'' (2000) music theatre with words by Getrude Stein \n* ''...meme soir'' (2000) music theatre \n* ''Eislermaterial'' (1998) staged concert for Ensemble with music by Hanns Eisler\n* ''Max Black'' (1998) music theatre with words by Georg Christooh Lichtenberg, Paul Valery, Ludwig Wittgenstein and Max Black\n* ''Schwarz auf Weiss'' (1996) Music theatre for eighteen musicians. Text: Edgar Allan Poe, John Webster,  T.S. Eliot, Maurice Blanchot\n* ''Die Wiederholung / La Reprise / The Repetition'' (1995) music theatre with words by S\u00f6ren Kierkegaard, Alain Robbe-Grillet and Prince \n* ''Ou bien le d\u00e9barquement d\u00e9sastreux'' (1993) music theatre with words by Joseph Conrad, Heiner M\u00fcller and Francis Ponge\n\n=== Orchestra works ===\n* ''Ou bien Sunyatta'' (2004) for kora, voice and orchestra\n* ''Notiz einer Fanfare'' (2003) for big orchestra \n* ''Aus einem Tagebuch'' (2002/03) Short diary entries for orchestra \n* ''Walden'' (1998) for extended orchestra and speaker. Text: H. D. Thoreau\n* ''Industry and Idleness'' (1998) for orchestra\n* ''Surrogate Cities'' (1993/94) for mezzo-soprano, voice, sampler and big orchestra. Text: Heiner M\u00fcller, Hugo Hamilton, Paul Auster\n\n=== Ensemble works ===\n* ''Songs of Wars I have seen'' (2007) staged concert for Ensemble with words by Gertrude Stein\n* ''Schlachtenbeschreibung'' (2002) for bariton and ensemble with words by Leonardo da Vinci\n* ''Samplersuite from Surrogate Cities'' (1994) for ensemble\n* ''Herakles 2'' (1991) for seven instruments\n* ''La Jalousie'' (1991) Noises from a novel for speaker and ensemble. Text: Alain Robbe-Grillet\n* ''Red Run'' (1998/91) Nine Songs for Eleven Instruments\n\n=== Chamber music ===\n* ''The Lovesong of J. Alfred Prufrock'' (T.S.Eliot), \"The Excursion into the Mountains\" (Franz Kafla), \"Worstward Ho\"(Samuel Beckett) (2008) for four voices\n* ''Bagatellen'' (1986-2006) for violin and sampler and clarinet ad lib.\n* ''And We Said Good Bye'' (2002) from ''Landschaft mit entfernten Verwandten'' for flute, clarinet and playback-CD \n* ''Harrypatari'' (1995/96) from ''Schwarz auf Wei\u00df'' for zither, marimba, cimbalom, clavichord and e-bass\n* ''In the Basement'' (1995/96) for oboe, clarinet, bassoon and electronic feed\n* ''Toccata for Tea pot and Piccolo'' (1995/96) from ''Schwarz auf Wei\u00df'' for Piccolo and tea pot\n\n=== Installative works ===\n* ''Maelstroms\u00fcdpol'' site specific installation with Heiner M\u00fcller, Erich Wonder 1987 (documenta Kassel), 1988 (ars electronica Linz and Berlin) \n* ''Tim\u00e9e'' 2000 soundinstallation with words by Plato\n* ''Fin du Soleil''2000 soundinstallation \n* ''Genko An'' 2008 (Berlin), 2012 (Darmstadt), 2014 (Lyon), 2017 (Moscow) site specific visual and sound-installation\n* ''Stifters Dinge - The Unguided Tour'' 2012\n \n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.heinergoebbels.com Heiner Goebbels site]\n*[http://www.egs.edu/faculty/heiner-goebbels/biography/ Heiner Goebbels Faculty Page] at [[European Graduate School]]. (Biography, bibliography and video lectures)\n*[http://www.paristransatlantic.com/magazine/interviews/goebbels.html Interview (1997)]\n*[http://www.ricordi.com/en-US/Composers/G/Goebbels-Heiner/ Publisher's website: Heiner Goebbels's biography and worklist at Ricordi]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120218205623/http://www.trovar.com/ECM/ECM.php?artist=Goebbels Heiner Goebbels on ECM Records]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goebbels, Heiner}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German classical composers]]\n[[Category:European Graduate School faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:ECM Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Neustadt an der Weinstra\u00dfe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:German male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "'''Heiner Goebbels''' (born 17 August 1952) is a [[Germany|German]] [[composer]], [[Artistic director|director]] and professor at [[University of Giessen|Justus-Liebig-University]] in [[Gie\u00dfen]] and artistic director of the International Festival of the Arts [[Ruhrtriennale]] 2012\u201314.\n\n== Biography ==\nGoebbels was born in [[Neustadt an der Weinstra\u00dfe]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=22 February 2001 |title=Heiner Goebbels |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/biogramm-heiner-goebbels-11267359.html |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |location=Frankfurt |language=de |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> Goebbels, who studied sociology and music in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]],<ref name=OTB>Program for Pacific Musicworks / Seattle Chamber Players performance of Heiner Goebbels ''Songs of Wars I Have Seen'', On the Boards, Seattle, March 4\u20136, 2010.</ref> is a composer of ensemble works and compositions for large orchestra. He has created several prize-winning radio plays, staged concerts, and, since the early 1990's, music theatre works, which have been invited to the most important theatre and music festivals worldwide.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nGoebbels and [[Alfred Harth]] were musical partners in the [[Duo Goebbels/Harth]] (1975-1988) who co-founded the wind band [[Sogenanntes Linksradikales Blasorchester]] (1976-1981) and the [[avant-rock]] [[Musical ensemble|group]] [[Cassiber]] (1982\u20131992) with [[Alfred Harth]], [[Chris Cutler]] and [[Christoph Anders]]. They toured extensively across [[Europe]], [[Asia]] and [[North America]], and made five albums. In October 1983 Cassiber (minus Anders) joined [[Duck and Cover (German band)|Duck and Cover]],  commissioned for the 1983 [[Moers Festival]] at the request of festival director Burkhard Hennen to Alfred Harth, followed by a performance at the [[Berlin Jazz Festival]] in [[West Berlin]],  and by another in February 1984 in [[East Berlin]].\n\nSome of his better-known work originated from his close collaboration with the [[East Germany|East German]] writer [[Heiner M\u00fcller]], resulting in stage compositions as well as shorter pieces (concerts as well as audio plays) based on M\u00fcller texts,<ref name=OTB /> such as ''Verkommenes Ufer'' (Waste Shore, 1984), ''Die Befreiung des Prometheus'' (The Liberation of Prometheus, 1985), or ''Wolokolamsker Chaussee'' (Volokolamsk Highway, 1989).{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} \nGoebbels' attempts to fill the space between theatre and opera left blank due to traditional genre borderline drawing{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} has led to projects such as \"''Ou bien le d\u00e9barquement d\u00e9sastreux''\" (Paris 1993), ''Schwarz auf Weiss'' (Black on White, 1996)<ref name=OTB /> and ''Die Wiederholung'' (The Repetition, 1995).{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} The political nature of his work is often referred to by critics.{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} His interest in Heiner M\u00fcller can partly be explained by the political character of M\u00fcller's texts, as may be the case with his interest in [[Bertolt Brecht]] and [[Hanns Eisler]], works by the latter he used in composing his staged concert ''Eislermaterial'' (1998).{{citation needed|date=March 2010}} \n1998 he also created the music theatre play \"Max Black\" with words by [[Paul Valery]] and others, in 2000 \"Hashirigaki\" after [[Gertrude Stein]], 2002 his first opera \"Landscape with distant relatives\", 2004 the price winning \"Eraritjaritjaka\" with words by [[Elias Canetti]], followed 2007 by the performative installation \"Stifters Dinge\" which has been performed more than 300 times in four continents. 2007 followed the staged concert \"Songs of Wars I have seen\" with words by [[Gertrude Stein]] - a commission by the [[London Sinfonietta]] and the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]], 2008 \"I went to the House but did not enter\" with the [[Hilliard Ensemble]] and words by [[Maurice Blanchot]], [[Samuel Beckett]] a.o. In 2012 he created \"When the Mountain changed its clothing\" with the Choir Carmina Slovenica, and staged [[John Cage]]'s \"Europeras 1&2\" 2012 and [[Harry Partch]]'s ''[[Delusion of the Fury]]'' 2013 and [[Louis Andriessen]]'s [[De Materie]] for the [[Ruhrtriennale]] International Festival of the Arts.\n\nGoebbels' work is being increasingly acknowledged as he is being played and staged around the world and as his recordings are being published. He collaborated with the finest ensembles and orchestras - [[Ensemble Modern]], [[Ensemble Intercontemporain]], Ensemble [[musikFabrik]], [[Asko/Sch\u00f6nberg]], [[Berg Orchestra]], [[Berlin Philharmonic]], [[Bochumer Symphoniker]], Junge Deutsche Philharmonie, [[Brooklyn Philharmonic]] and many others and worked with conductors like Sir [[Simon Rattle]], [[Peter Eotvos]], [[Lothar Zagrosek]], [[Peter Rundel]], [[Steven Sloane]] and many others.  In 2000 he collaborated with [[Piano Circus]] and composer [[Richard Harris (composer)|Richard Harris]] to produce ''Scutigeras'', which received a live BBC radio premiere in the UK. \nHis ''Surrogate Cities'', a work for big orchestra dating from 1994 and featuring texts from [[Paul Auster]], Heiner M\u00fcller, and [[Hugo Hamilton (writer)|Hugo Hamilton]], has been performed widely in Europe, the US and Australia and was nominated for a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] in the category [[Grammy Award for Best Classical Contemporary Composition|Best Classical Contemporary Composition]] at the [[Grammy Awards of 2001|43rd Grammy Awards in 2001]].<ref name=\"egs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.egs.edu/faculty/heiner-goebbels/biography/ | title=Heiner Goebbels Faculty Page at European Graduate School (Biography, bibliography and video lectures) | publisher=[[European Graduate School]] | author= | accessdate=2010-09-25}}</ref> His ''Eislermaterial'' won him another Grammy nomination at the [[Grammy Awards of 2004|46th Grammy Awards in 2004]], this time in the category [[Grammy Award for Best Small Ensemble Performance|Best Small Ensemble Performance (with or without conductor)]].<ref>[http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news_print.php?id=3058  ECM and its artists received eight nominations for the 46th Grammy Awards.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050226144201/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news_print.php?id=3058 |date=2005-02-26 }} ''All about jazz'', 2003-12-19.</ref>\n\nHis installative artwork \"Stifters Dinge - the Unguided Tour\" has been presented by [[Artangel]] in London (2012) and at the [[Ruhrtriennale]] in Duisburg (2013), \"Genko-An\" in Berlin (2008), [[Darmstadt Artists' Colony]]/Mathildenh\u00f6he (2012), [[Mus\u00e9e d'art contemporain de Lyon]] (2014) and Moscow's NEW SPACE (2017). For the [[Centre Pompidou]] Paris he created the soundinstallations \"Fin de Soleil\" and \"Tim\u00e9e\"(2000) which was also exhibited at the [[ZKM]] Karlsruhe, the [[MACBA]] Barcelona, in Brugge and in Palazzo delle Esposizioni/Rome. He also closely collaborated on several videoinstallations with visual artist [[Michal Rovner]]. 1982, 1987 and 1997 he participated with concerts, installative works and performing arts at the [[documenta]] in Kassel\n\nGoebbels was a professor at Justus-Liebig-University in Gie\u00dfen, Institute for Applied Theater Studies from 1999 until 2018, and teaches the European Graduate School in Saas-Fee, Switzerland.<ref name=\"egs\" /> From 2006 until 2018 he was President of the Theater Academy of Hesse. In recent years Goebbels enjoyed the privilege of several guest professorships and nominations for composer-in-residence.,<ref name=OTB /> he is member of several academies of arts (Berlin, Bensheim, D\u00fcsseldorf, Mainz, Munich), Fellow of the Institute of Advanced Studies in Berlin, Honorable Fellow at the Dartington College of the Arts and the [[Central School of Speech and Drama]], London. In 2012 he was awarded an honorary doctorate by [[Birmingham City University]], in 2018 by the National Academy for Theatre and Film Arts in Sofia (Bulgaria).\n\nHe received numerous awards and honours, such as [[Prix Italia]], [[Europe Theatre Prize]], and 2012 the [[International Ibsen Award]], one of the world's most prestigious theatre awards, for bringing \"new artistic dimensions to the world of drama or theatre.\".\n\nIn September 2010, it was announced that Goebbels was the artistic director designate for the 2012-14 seasons of the [[Ruhrtriennale]].<ref>{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.ruhrtriennale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/pressemitteilung-24-09-10\n |title       = Heiner Goebbels is Artistic Director designate\n |publisher   = Ruhrtriennale\n |accessdate  = 2011-03-10\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20101227073108/http://www.ruhrtriennale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/pressemitteilung-24-09-10/\n |archivedate = 2010-12-27\n}}</ref>\n{{clear}} As artistic director of this Festival Heiner Goebbels curated, produced and presented several new works by the artists [[Robert Wilson (director)|Robert Wilson]], [[Romeo Castellucci]], [[Michal Rovner]], [[Boris Charmatz]], [[Robert Lepage]], [[Jan Lauwers]], [[Ryoji Ikeda]], [[Douglas Gordon]], [[William Forsythe (choreographer)|William Forsythe]], [[Lemi Ponifasio]], [[Mathilde Monnier]], [[Saburo Teshigawara]], [[Anne Teresa de Keersmaeker]], [[Rimini Protokoll]], [[Tim Etchells]], [[Gregor Schneider]] and many others.\n\nHis latest work, ''Everything that happened and would happen'', was performed for the first time in October 2018 at [[Manchester Mayfield railway station|Mayfield Depot]] in [[Manchester]]. It explores the history of Europe since [[World War I]] and combines live music, performance and film <ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/09/from-bombsites-to-usain-bolt-manchester-relives-100-years-of-war-and-peace | title=From bombsites to Usain Bolt: Manchester relives 100 years of war and peace| newspaper=The Guardian| date=2018-10-09| last1=Connolly| first1=Kate}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/10/arts/heiner-goebels-everything-that-happened-manchester.html |title = 120 Years of European History, in 3 Disorienting Hours|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2018-10-10|last1 = G\u00fcner|first1 = Fisun}}</ref>\n\n== Works (Selection) ==\n\n=== Stage works ===\n* ''When the Mountain Changed Its Clothing'' (2012) Music theatre for a girl's choir. Text: Jean Jaques Rousseau, Gertrude Stein, Adalbert Stifter, Alain Robe-Grillet and others\n* ''I went to the house but did not enter'' (2008) Scenic concert in three pictures for four male voices. Text: T.S. Eliot, Maurice Blanchot, Samuel Beckett, Franz Kafka\n* ''Stifters Dinge'' (2007) Installative Performance \n* ''Eraritjaritjaka - mus\u00e9e de Phrases'' (2007) music theatre for actor and string quartett, words by Elias Canetti\n* ''Landschaft mit entfernten Verwandten'' (2002) Opera for ensemble, choir and soloists. Texts and motifs by Giordano Bruno, Arthur Chapman/Estelle Philleo, T.S. Eliot, Francois F\u00e9nelon, Michel Foucault and others\n* ''Hashirigaki'' (2000) music theatre with words by Getrude Stein \n* ''...meme soir'' (2000) music theatre \n* ''Eislermaterial'' (1998) staged concert for Ensemble with music by Hanns Eisler\n* ''Max Black'' (1998) music theatre with words by Georg Christooh Lichtenberg, Paul Valery, Ludwig Wittgenstein and Max Black\n* ''Schwarz auf Weiss'' (1996) Music theatre for eighteen musicians. Text: Edgar Allan Poe, John Webster,  T.S. Eliot, Maurice Blanchot\n* ''Die Wiederholung / La Reprise / The Repetition'' (1995) music theatre with words by S\u00f6ren Kierkegaard, Alain Robbe-Grillet and Prince \n* ''Ou bien le d\u00e9barquement d\u00e9sastreux'' (1993) music theatre with words by Joseph Conrad, Heiner M\u00fcller and Francis Ponge\n\n=== Orchestra works ===\n* ''Ou bien Sunyatta'' (2004) for kora, voice and orchestra\n* ''Notiz einer Fanfare'' (2003) for big orchestra \n* ''Aus einem Tagebuch'' (2002/03) Short diary entries for orchestra \n* ''Walden'' (1998) for extended orchestra and speaker. Text: H. D. Thoreau\n* ''Industry and Idleness'' (1998) for orchestra\n* ''Surrogate Cities'' (1993/94) for mezzo-soprano, voice, sampler and big orchestra. Text: Heiner M\u00fcller, Hugo Hamilton, Paul Auster\n\n=== Ensemble works ===\n* ''Songs of Wars I have seen'' (2007) staged concert for Ensemble with words by Gertrude Stein\n* ''Schlachtenbeschreibung'' (2002) for bariton and ensemble with words by Leonardo da Vinci\n* ''Samplersuite from Surrogate Cities'' (1994) for ensemble\n* ''Herakles 2'' (1991) for seven instruments\n* ''La Jalousie'' (1991) Noises from a novel for speaker and ensemble. Text: Alain Robbe-Grillet\n* ''Red Run'' (1998/91) Nine Songs for Eleven Instruments\n\n=== Chamber music ===\n* ''The Lovesong of J. Alfred Prufrock'' (T.S.Eliot), \"The Excursion into the Mountains\" (Franz Kafla), \"Worstward Ho\"(Samuel Beckett) (2008) for four voices\n* ''Bagatellen'' (1986-2006) for violin and sampler and clarinet ad lib.\n* ''And We Said Good Bye'' (2002) from ''Landschaft mit entfernten Verwandten'' for flute, clarinet and playback-CD \n* ''Harrypatari'' (1995/96) from ''Schwarz auf Wei\u00df'' for zither, marimba, cimbalom, clavichord and e-bass\n* ''In the Basement'' (1995/96) for oboe, clarinet, bassoon and electronic feed\n* ''Toccata for Tea pot and Piccolo'' (1995/96) from ''Schwarz auf Wei\u00df'' for Piccolo and tea pot\n\n=== Installative works ===\n* ''Maelstroms\u00fcdpol'' site specific installation with Heiner M\u00fcller, Erich Wonder 1987 (documenta Kassel), 1988 (ars electronica Linz and Berlin) \n* ''Tim\u00e9e'' 2000 soundinstallation with words by Plato\n* ''Fin du Soleil''2000 soundinstallation \n* ''Genko An'' 2008 (Berlin), 2012 (Darmstadt), 2014 (Lyon), 2017 (Moscow) site specific visual and sound-installation\n* ''Stifters Dinge - The Unguided Tour'' 2012\n \n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.heinergoebbels.com Heiner Goebbels site]\n*[http://www.egs.edu/faculty/heiner-goebbels/biography/ Heiner Goebbels Faculty Page] at [[European Graduate School]]. (Biography, bibliography and video lectures)\n*[http://www.paristransatlantic.com/magazine/interviews/goebbels.html Interview (1997)]\n*[http://www.ricordi.com/en-US/Composers/G/Goebbels-Heiner/ Publisher's website: Heiner Goebbels's biography and worklist at Ricordi]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120218205623/http://www.trovar.com/ECM/ECM.php?artist=Goebbels Heiner Goebbels on ECM Records]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goebbels, Heiner}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German classical composers]]\n[[Category:European Graduate School faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:ECM Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Neustadt an der Weinstra\u00dfe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:German male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heiner_Goebbels"}
{"title_page": "Devon Allman", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Devon Allman\n| image            = DevonAllman.2018-05-28.LasVegas-NV-BrooklynBowl.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Devon Allman performing at [[Brooklyn Bowl]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on May 28, 2018\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|08|10}}\n| birth_place      = [[Corpus Christi, Texas]]\n| origin           = [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Blues rock]], [[Rock music|rock]]\n| occupation       = Singer, guitarist, songwriter, producer, actor\n| instrument       = Guitar, Keyboard\n| years_active     = 1999\u2013present\n| label            = [[Ruf Records]]\n| associated_acts  = Devon Allman Project [[Honeytribe]], [[Royal Southern Brotherhood]]\n| website          = {{URL|devonallmanproject.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Devon Allman''' (born August 10, 1972) is an American guitarist, vocalist, keyboardist, songwriter, and record producer. He is the son of musician [[Gregg Allman]] and has appeared occasionally as a guest musician for [[Gregg Allman]] and [[The Allman Brothers Band]]. In addition, he is the now ex-stepson of musician [[Cher]]. Allman was the founder and bandleader of [[Honeytribe]], also known as Devon Allman's Honeytribe, with whom he released two albums and toured across North America and Europe. Prior to Honeytribe, Allman contributed to several other musical recordings, notably [[Javier Vargas (musician)|Vargas Blues Band]] and the ''[[A Song for My Father (album)|A Song for My Father]]'' compilation album. He was one of the original members of [[Royal Southern Brotherhood]] and contributed to their first two studio albums and toured with them. In 2013, Allman launched his solo career as the Devon Allman Band, and has since released three albums. His latest tour, branded as the Devon Allman Project, features special guest [[Duane Betts]].<ref name=\"rollingstone2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/gregg-allmans-son-devon-talks-carrying-on-the-family-legacy-w521508 |title=Gregg Allman's Son Devon Talks Carrying on the Family Legacy |publisher=rollingstone.com |date=2018-06-18 |accessdate=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAllman is the son of Gregg Allman (of [[The Allman Brothers Band]]) and Shelley Kay Jefts. His parents divorced when he was an infant, and he grew up in [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], as well as [[Tennessee]] and [[St. Louis, Missouri]], raised by his mother.<ref name=\"interview2010\">{{cite web |url=http://blues.about.com/od/bluesinterviews/a/Devon-Allman-Interview-2010.htm |title=Devon Allman of Devon Allman's Honeytribe - Interview with Devon Allman of Devon Allman's Honeytribe |publisher=Blues.about.com |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2014-03-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325011426/http://blues.about.com/od/bluesinterviews/a/Devon-Allman-Interview-2010.htm |archive-date=2014-03-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAllman began playing music as a teen, but was not influenced by his father.<ref name=\"interview2010\" /> He did not meet his father until he was in his teens, but they then bonded instantly.<ref name=\"interview20061206\">{{cite web |url=http://blogcritics.org/music/article/an-interview-with-devon-allman-like/ |title=An Interview with Devon Allman - Like Father, Like Son - Blogcritics Music |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725085811/http://blogcritics.org/music/article/an-interview-with-devon-allman-like/ |archivedate=2011-07-25 }}</ref> For several years in the 1990s he performed around the growing St. Louis blues and rock music scene, while also managing a suburban [[Guitar Center]] store where he met his future Royal Southern Brotherhood bandmate, Mike Zito.<ref name=\"boston.com\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://articles.boston.com/2012-03-08/arts/31138669_1_devon-allman-new-band-derek-trucks-band |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130118081214/http://articles.boston.com/2012-03-08/arts/31138669_1_devon-allman-new-band-derek-trucks-band |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-18 |title=Royal Southern Brotherhood feeding a hunger for 'real music' - Arts - The Boston Globe |publisher=Articles.boston.com |date=2012-03-10 |accessdate=2014-03-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn his twenties, Allman tried various musical styles and sounds to distance himself from his father's sound and avoid obvious comparisons, though his father did not meddle in Allman's career. In his thirties, Allman embraced the blues and rock genres.<ref name=\"interview20061206\" />\n\n\u201cWhile I\u2019m proud of my family\u2019s mark on rock history, I have my own story to write and my own work to do.\u201d Devon Allman said. <ref name=\"FatherhoodChannel\">{{cite web|url=https://fatherhoodchannel.com/2020/02/10/daddy-is-a-rock-star-the-allman-betts-band-20920/|title=Daddy is a Rock Star - The Allman Betts Band|last=McFliker|first=Todd |date=February 10, 2020|publisher=FatherhoodChannel.com|accessdate=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nAllman grew up on classic, blues-inspired rock music, and has specifically mentioned [[Santana (band)|Santana]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[The Doors]], and [[The Allman Brothers Band]] as influences,<ref name=\"interview20061206\" /> as well as heavy metal acts such as [[Iron Maiden]], [[Metallica]], [[Megadeth]] and [[Testament (band)|Testament]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.houstonpress.com/music/things-to-do-see-the-allman-betts-band-at-the-heights-theater-11284912|title=Things to Do: See the Allman Betts Band at the Heights Theater|last=Ruggiero|first=Bob|date=May 3, 2019|work=[[Houston Press]]|access-date=May 15, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked if there was one record that he could cite as the definitive recording that has influenced and inspired him,  Allman responded with [[Layla and Other Assorted Love Songs|Layla]], by [[Derek and The Dominos]]. He explained, \"Although it's not straight blues, it's obviously dripping with soulful blues guitar. Layla has always appealed to me because you can really really \u2018feel\u2019 what [[Eric Clapton|Clapton]] was going through. That man was straight up in love. It brought out a burning passion in his throat and fingers that is undeniable, and it obviously soaked into the other players on the record. My uncle [[Duane Allman|Duane]] just sounds like a bird on it as well! It has so much raw energy and passion that it sounds ultra fresh every time I put it on. Front to back, one of the few records that can bring me to tears if I let it.\"<ref name=\"interview20061206\" />\n\n\u201cBeing the son of my father, everyone expects \u201cWhipping Post\u201d right off the bat,\u201d he told an interviewer. \u201cOkay, I get it. But I am doing my own thing. So it\u2019s tough. The name helps open doors, but you have to know what you\u2019re doing. I\u2019ve seen the door slam in a lot of people\u2019s faces. So you can\u2019t just rely on the name.\u201d<ref name=\"FatherhoodChannel\"/>\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===The Dark Horses===\n{{Main|The Dark Horses}}\nIn the early 1990s Devon Allman headed up a band in St. Louis called ''The Dark Horses''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_IpP0RFA6Y |title=The Dark Horses \"UnleashThe Spirit\" |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref>\n\n===Honeytribe===\n{{Main|Honeytribe}}\nAllman formed Honeytribe in 1999. In 2001, the band broke up so Allman could spend time with his newly born son. They re-formed in 2005 with their original lineup, and have since toured in the United States, Europe, and Canada, and have recorded two albums. They recorded ''Torch'' in 2006 and played up to 300 shows a year in 42 states and ten countries.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} Allman eventually grew restless with the original Honeytribe sound and pared the band down to a power trio in 2008 with bassist George Potsos and new drummer Gabriel Strange. This incarnation of Devon Allman's Honeytribe released ''Space Age Blues'' in the fall of 2010.\n\n===Royal Southern Brotherhood===\n{{Main|Royal Southern Brotherhood}}\nIn October 2011, Allman began working on a project titled the [[Royal Southern Brotherhood]]. The blues-rock supergroup includes [[Cyril Neville]], [[Mike Zito]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalsouthernbrotherhood.com/ |title=Royal Southern Brotherhood |publisher=Royal Southern Brotherhood |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref> Grammy-award winning drummer [[Yonrico Scott]] and bassist Charlie Wooton. Allman was skeptical of joining the group at first, telling his manager \"Dude are you crazy? Thats like putting five quarterbacks in a room and saying 'go play football'. What the Hell are you talking about?\"<ref name=\"Express\">{{cite news| last=Hunsicker| first=Jason| url=http://www.kirksvilledailyexpress.com/article/20120919/NEWS/120918554|title=''Allman, Neville, Royal Southern Brotherhood headline Round Barn''| newspaper=The Kirksville Daily Express| date=19 September 2012| accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> However he soon changed his mind and the group recorded their first album in December 2011, over five days at Dockside Studio, a {{Convert|12|acre||adj=on}} estate on the banks of Vermilion Bayou, in [[Maurice, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"theadvocate.com\">{{cite web |url=http://theadvocate.com/utility/homepagestories/2544928-129/neville-allman-join-forces-in |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514191005/http://theadvocate.com/utility/homepagestories/2544928-129/neville-allman-join-forces-in |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-05-14 |title=Homepage Stories &#124; The Advocate \u2014 Baton Rouge, Louisiana |publisher=Theadvocate.com |accessdate=2015-11-03 }}</ref> The group made its stage debut in September 2011 at the [[Rock n' Bowl|Rock \u2019n\u2019 Bowl]] in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"boston.com\" /><ref name=\"theadvocate.com\"/> As of September, 2012 they have toured extensively in the U.S. and fourteen foreign countries.<ref name=\"Express\"/>\n\n===The Allman Betts Band===\nIn November 2018, the sons of Gregg Allman and Dickey Betts announced the formation of The Allman Betts Band. They kicked off 2019 with a new Allman Betts Band album and a worldwide tour that features new music, songs from their solo projects and classic Allman Brothers and Gregg Allman tunes in honor of the 50th Anniversary of The Allman Brothers Band. The new album, which was released in the June 2019, was produced by Matt Ross-Spang (Jason Isbell, Margo Price, John Prine and Elvis Presley, no relation to the musician of the same name).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnewsnet.com/2018/11/music-news-after-a-successful-year-touring-as-the-devon-allman-project-with-special-guest-duane-betts-the-sons-of-gregg-al.html|title=Devon Allman + Duane Betts Announce Spring 2019 Album & The Allman Betts Band, Initial 2019 Tour Dates Announced|website=Music News Net|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Solo===\nIn September 2012, Allman finished recording sessions for his first solo album, titled [[Turquoise (album)|''Turquoise'']], which features [[Myles Weeks]] on bass and [[Yonrico Scott]] on drums. The sessions were recorded at [[Ardent Studios]], in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], engineered by Pete Matthews and produced by Jim Gaines, and includes guest musicians [[Luther Dickinson]], [[Samantha Fish]], [[Rick Steff]] and [[Ron Holloway]]. A solo tour began in November 2012, and the touring band include Pedro Arevalo on bass, Bobby Schneck Jr. on second guitar, and Anthony Nanney on drums. The album was released on 12 February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/turquoise-mw0002472178 |title=Turquoise &#124; Overview/review |website=AllMusic |date=2013-12-09 |accessdate=2015-01-04}}</ref>\n\n===Other contributions===\nIn 2005, Allman appeared on Love, Union, Peace with bluesman [[Javier Vargas (musician)|Javier Vargas]]' Vargas Blues Band (along with [[Jack Bruce]], [[Reese Wynans]], and others), and in 2008 on the Flamenco Blues Experience recording by the same outfit. In 2007, Allman guested on [[Paris Luna]]'s ''City Lights'' album. He has also made appearances at various festivals and on MTV Europe.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo===\n* ''[[Turquoise (album)|Turquoise]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Ragged & Dirty (album)|Ragged & Dirty]]'' (Ruf Records, 2014)\n* ''[[Ride or Die (album)|Ride or Die]]'' (2016)\n\n===Ocean Six===\n* Ocean Six \u2013 ''Somewhere Between Day and Night'' (2003): Guitar and vocals<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/somewhere-between-day-and-night-r656086/credits |title=Somewhere Between Day and Night - Ocean Six &#124; Credits |website=AllMusic |date=2003-09-09 |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Honeytribe===\n* ''[[Torch (Honeytribe album)|Torch]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Space Age Blues]]'' (2010)\n\n===Royal Southern Brotherhood===\n* ''[[Royal Southern Brotherhood (album)|Royal Southern Brotherhood]]'' (2012)\n* ''Songs from the Road (Live in Germany)'' (2013)\n* ''Heartsoulblood'' (2014)\n\n===Allman Betts Band===\n* ''[[Down To The River]]'' (2019)\n\n===Other contributions===\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Love, Union, Peace'' (2005): Vocals on \"Dance Away The Blues\", \"How Verso Are You?\", and \"Magic of the Gods\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-union-peace-r833111/credits |title=Love, Union, Peace - Vargas Blues Band &#124; Credits |website=AllMusic |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdloveunionpeace.htm |title=Love, Union, Peace |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425021117/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdloveunionpeace.htm |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref>\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Lost & Found'' (2007): Vocals on \"[[One Way Out (song)|One Way Out]]\", \"[[Statesboro Blues]]\" and \"[[Layla]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdlostandfound.htm |title=Lost & Found |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703202043/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdlostandfound.htm |archivedate=2008-07-03 }}</ref>\n* Various artists \u2013 ''[[A Song for My Father (album)|A Song for My Father]]'' (2007): \"[[Midnight Rider]]\"\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Flamenco Blues Experience'' (2008): Vocals on \"Blues In My Soul\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/flamenco-blues-experience-r1416825/credits |title=Flamenco Blues Experience - Vargas Blues Band &#124; Credits |website=AllMusic |date=2008-08-05 |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdflamencobluesexperience.htm |title=Flamenco Blues Experience |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425021155/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdflamencobluesexperience.htm |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref>\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Comes Alive With Friends'' (2009): Guitar and vocals on \"[[One Way Out (song)|One Way Out]]\", \"How Verso Are You?\", and \"[[Down by the River (Neil Young song)|Down by the River]]\"; vocals on \"Blues In My Soul\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdcomesalivewithfriends.htm |title=Vargas Blues Band Comes Alive With Friends! |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425021214/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdcomesalivewithfriends.htm |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref>\n* Dan Bruder Band \u2013 ''Act of Kindness'' (2010)\n* [[Jeremiah Johnson (blues musician)|Jeremiah Johnson]] \u2013 Production work on ''Grind'' (2015)<ref name=\"Violet\">{{cite web|url=http://tickets.violetsvenue.com/events/past_event/67 |title=The Jeremiah Johnson Band and The Sliders|publisher=Tickets.violetsvenue.com |date=2015-06-20 |accessdate=2015-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==Musical equipment==\nAllman's primary guitar is a [[Gibson Les Paul]], which he calls \"Number One\". It is an exact, custom-shop replication of a '59.<ref name=\"interview20110804\">{{cite web |url=http://www.weissmanreport.com/2011-08-04-18-06-26/item/1808-devon-allman-the-ambassador-of-authenticity |title=Devon Allman: The Ambassador of Authenticity |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425050524/http://www.weissmanreport.com/2011-08-04-18-06-26/item/1808-devon-allman-the-ambassador-of-authenticity |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref> It was signed by [[Les Paul]] when they played together at the [[Iridium Jazz Club]] in New York City in 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.kshe95.com/music/avplayer/devonallman.aspx |title=KSHE 95 = REAL ROCK RADIO |publisher=Kshe95.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAllman currently uses Fuchs Overdrive Supreme amplifiers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fuchsaudiotechnology.com/artists.php?id=allman_devon |title=Devon Allman &#124; Fuchs Audio Endorser |publisher=Fuchsaudiotechnology.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous projects==\nAllman appeared in the rock comedy series called ''Who the Hell is Dan Bruder'' which launched online June 2010. It is the story of a slightly delusional, middle-aged wannabe rocker who can not let go of the dream of stardom.\n\nIn 2011, Allman began marketing his \"Devon Allman's Chipotle Blues\" branded hot sauce via Born to Hula.<ref name=\"interview20110804\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://borntohula.com/ |title=::Born To Hula Hot Sauce:: |publisher=Borntohula.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.devonallmanproject.com/ Devon Allman Project]\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/devon-allman-p592877/biography Devon Allman biography on AllMusic.com]\n* [http://www.royalsouthernbrotherhood.com/ Royal Southern Brotherhood]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allman, Devon}}\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Ruf Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Devon Allman\n| image            = DevonAllman.2018-05-28.LasVegas-NV-BrooklynBowl.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Devon Allman performing at [[Brooklyn Bowl]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on May 28, 2018\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|08|10}}\n| birth_place      = [[Corpus Christi, Texas]]\n| origin           = [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Blues rock]], [[Rock music|rock]]\n| occupation       = Singer, guitarist, songwriter, producer, actor\n| instrument       = Guitar, Keyboard\n| years_active     = 1999\u2013present\n| label            = [[Ruf Records]]\n| associated_acts  = Devon Allman Project [[Honeytribe]], [[Royal Southern Brotherhood]]\n| website          = {{URL|devonallmanproject.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Devon Allman''' (born August 10, 1972) is an American guitarist, vocalist, keyboardist, songwriter, and record producer. He is the son of musician [[Gregg Allman]] and has appeared occasionally as a guest musician for [[Gregg Allman]] and [[The Allman Brothers Band]]. In addition, he is the now ex-stepson of musician [[Cher]]. Allman was the founder and bandleader of [[Honeytribe]], also known as Devon Allman's Honeytribe, with whom he released two albums and toured across North America and Europe. Prior to Honeytribe, Allman contributed to several other musical recordings, notably [[Javier Vargas (musician)|Vargas Blues Band]] and the ''[[A Song for My Father (album)|A Song for My Father]]'' compilation album. He was one of the original members of [[Royal Southern Brotherhood]] and contributed to their first two studio albums and toured with them. In 2013, Allman launched his solo career as the Devon Allman Band, and has since released three albums. His latest tour, branded as the Devon Allman Project, features special guest [[Duane Betts]].<ref name=\"rollingstone2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/gregg-allmans-son-devon-talks-carrying-on-the-family-legacy-w521508 |title=Gregg Allman's Son Devon Talks Carrying on the Family Legacy |publisher=rollingstone.com |date=2018-06-18 |accessdate=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAllman is the son of Gregg Allman (of [[The Allman Brothers Band]]) and Shelley Kay Jefts. His parents divorced when he was an infant, and he grew up in [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], as well as [[Tennessee]] and [[St. Louis, Missouri]], raised by his mother.<ref name=\"interview2010\">{{cite web |url=http://blues.about.com/od/bluesinterviews/a/Devon-Allman-Interview-2010.htm |title=Devon Allman of Devon Allman's Honeytribe - Interview with Devon Allman of Devon Allman's Honeytribe |publisher=Blues.about.com |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2014-03-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325011426/http://blues.about.com/od/bluesinterviews/a/Devon-Allman-Interview-2010.htm |archive-date=2014-03-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAllman began playing music as a teen, but was not influenced by his father.<ref name=\"interview2010\" /> He did not meet his father until he was in his teens, but they then bonded instantly.<ref name=\"interview20061206\">{{cite web |url=http://blogcritics.org/music/article/an-interview-with-devon-allman-like/ |title=An Interview with Devon Allman - Like Father, Like Son - Blogcritics Music |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725085811/http://blogcritics.org/music/article/an-interview-with-devon-allman-like/ |archivedate=2011-07-25 }}</ref> For several years in the 1990s he performed around the growing St. Louis blues and rock music scene, while also managing a suburban [[Guitar Center]] store where he met his future Royal Southern Brotherhood bandmate, Mike Zito.<ref name=\"boston.com\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://articles.boston.com/2012-03-08/arts/31138669_1_devon-allman-new-band-derek-trucks-band |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130118081214/http://articles.boston.com/2012-03-08/arts/31138669_1_devon-allman-new-band-derek-trucks-band |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-18 |title=Royal Southern Brotherhood feeding a hunger for 'real music' - Arts - The Boston Globe |publisher=Articles.boston.com |date=2012-03-10 |accessdate=2014-03-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn his twenties, Allman tried various musical styles and sounds to distance himself from his father's sound and avoid obvious comparisons, though his father did not meddle in Allman's career. In his thirties, Allman embraced the blues and rock genres.<ref name=\"interview20061206\" />\n\n\u201cWhile I\u2019m proud of my family\u2019s mark on rock history, I have my own story to write and my own work to do.\u201d Devon Allman said. <ref name=\"FatherhoodChannel\">{{cite web|url=https://fatherhoodchannel.com/2020/02/10/daddy-is-a-rock-star-the-allman-betts-band-20920/|title=Daddy is a Rock Star - The Allman Betts Band|last=McFliker|first=Todd |date=February 10, 2020|publisher=FatherhoodChannel.com|accessdate=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nAllman grew up on classic, blues-inspired rock music, and has specifically mentioned [[Santana (band)|Santana]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[The Doors]], and [[The Allman Brothers Band]] as influences,<ref name=\"interview20061206\" /> as well as heavy metal acts such as [[Iron Maiden]], [[Metallica]], [[Megadeth]] and [[Testament (band)|Testament]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.houstonpress.com/music/things-to-do-see-the-allman-betts-band-at-the-heights-theater-11284912|title=Things to Do: See the Allman Betts Band at the Heights Theater|last=Ruggiero|first=Bob|date=May 3, 2019|work=[[Houston Press]]|access-date=May 15, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked if there was one record that he could cite as the definitive recording that has influenced and inspired him,  Allman responded with [[Layla and Other Assorted Love Songs|Layla]], by [[Derek and The Dominos]]. He explained, \"Although it's not straight blues, it's obviously dripping with soulful blues guitar. Layla has always appealed to me because you can really really \u2018feel\u2019 what [[Eric Clapton|Clapton]] was going through. That man was straight up in love. It brought out a burning passion in his throat and fingers that is undeniable, and it obviously soaked into the other players on the record. My uncle [[Duane Allman|Duane]] just sounds like a bird on it as well! It has so much raw energy and passion that it sounds ultra fresh every time I put it on. Front to back, one of the few records that can bring me to tears if I let it.\"<ref name=\"interview20061206\" />\n\n\u201cBeing the son of my father, everyone expects \u201cWhipping Post\u201d right off the bat,\u201d he told an interviewer. \u201cOkay, I get it. But I am doing my own thing. So it\u2019s tough. The name helps open doors, but you have to know what you\u2019re doing. I\u2019ve seen the door slam in a lot of people\u2019s faces. So you can\u2019t just rely on the name.\u201d<ref name=\"FatherhoodChannel\"/>\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===The Dark Horses===\n{{Main|The Dark Horses}}\nIn the early 1990's Devon Allman headed up a band in St. Louis called ''The Dark Horses''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_IpP0RFA6Y |title=The Dark Horses \"UnleashThe Spirit\" |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref>\n\n===Honeytribe===\n{{Main|Honeytribe}}\nAllman formed Honeytribe in 1999. In 2001, the band broke up so Allman could spend time with his newly born son. They re-formed in 2005 with their original lineup, and have since toured in the United States, Europe, and Canada, and have recorded two albums. They recorded ''Torch'' in 2006 and played up to 300 shows a year in 42 states and ten countries.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} Allman eventually grew restless with the original Honeytribe sound and pared the band down to a power trio in 2008 with bassist George Potsos and new drummer Gabriel Strange. This incarnation of Devon Allman's Honeytribe released ''Space Age Blues'' in the fall of 2010.\n\n===Royal Southern Brotherhood===\n{{Main|Royal Southern Brotherhood}}\nIn October 2011, Allman began working on a project titled the [[Royal Southern Brotherhood]]. The blues-rock supergroup includes [[Cyril Neville]], [[Mike Zito]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalsouthernbrotherhood.com/ |title=Royal Southern Brotherhood |publisher=Royal Southern Brotherhood |date=2013-11-26 |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref> Grammy-award winning drummer [[Yonrico Scott]] and bassist Charlie Wooton. Allman was skeptical of joining the group at first, telling his manager \"Dude are you crazy? Thats like putting five quarterbacks in a room and saying 'go play football'. What the Hell are you talking about?\"<ref name=\"Express\">{{cite news| last=Hunsicker| first=Jason| url=http://www.kirksvilledailyexpress.com/article/20120919/NEWS/120918554|title=''Allman, Neville, Royal Southern Brotherhood headline Round Barn''| newspaper=The Kirksville Daily Express| date=19 September 2012| accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> However he soon changed his mind and the group recorded their first album in December 2011, over five days at Dockside Studio, a {{Convert|12|acre||adj=on}} estate on the banks of Vermilion Bayou, in [[Maurice, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"theadvocate.com\">{{cite web |url=http://theadvocate.com/utility/homepagestories/2544928-129/neville-allman-join-forces-in |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514191005/http://theadvocate.com/utility/homepagestories/2544928-129/neville-allman-join-forces-in |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-05-14 |title=Homepage Stories &#124; The Advocate \u2014 Baton Rouge, Louisiana |publisher=Theadvocate.com |accessdate=2015-11-03 }}</ref> The group made its stage debut in September 2011 at the [[Rock n' Bowl|Rock \u2019n\u2019 Bowl]] in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=\"boston.com\" /><ref name=\"theadvocate.com\"/> As of September, 2012 they have toured extensively in the U.S. and fourteen foreign countries.<ref name=\"Express\"/>\n\n===The Allman Betts Band===\nIn November 2018, the sons of Gregg Allman and Dickey Betts announced the formation of The Allman Betts Band. They kicked off 2019 with a new Allman Betts Band album and a worldwide tour that features new music, songs from their solo projects and classic Allman Brothers and Gregg Allman tunes in honor of the 50th Anniversary of The Allman Brothers Band. The new album, which was released in the June 2019, was produced by Matt Ross-Spang (Jason Isbell, Margo Price, John Prine and Elvis Presley, no relation to the musician of the same name).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnewsnet.com/2018/11/music-news-after-a-successful-year-touring-as-the-devon-allman-project-with-special-guest-duane-betts-the-sons-of-gregg-al.html|title=Devon Allman + Duane Betts Announce Spring 2019 Album & The Allman Betts Band, Initial 2019 Tour Dates Announced|website=Music News Net|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Solo===\nIn September 2012, Allman finished recording sessions for his first solo album, titled [[Turquoise (album)|''Turquoise'']], which features [[Myles Weeks]] on bass and [[Yonrico Scott]] on drums. The sessions were recorded at [[Ardent Studios]], in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], engineered by Pete Matthews and produced by Jim Gaines, and includes guest musicians [[Luther Dickinson]], [[Samantha Fish]], [[Rick Steff]] and [[Ron Holloway]]. A solo tour began in November 2012, and the touring band include Pedro Arevalo on bass, Bobby Schneck Jr. on second guitar, and Anthony Nanney on drums. The album was released on 12 February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/turquoise-mw0002472178 |title=Turquoise &#124; Overview/review |website=AllMusic |date=2013-12-09 |accessdate=2015-01-04}}</ref>\n\n===Other contributions===\nIn 2005, Allman appeared on Love, Union, Peace with bluesman [[Javier Vargas (musician)|Javier Vargas]]' Vargas Blues Band (along with [[Jack Bruce]], [[Reese Wynans]], and others), and in 2008 on the Flamenco Blues Experience recording by the same outfit. In 2007, Allman guested on [[Paris Luna]]'s ''City Lights'' album. He has also made appearances at various festivals and on MTV Europe.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo===\n* ''[[Turquoise (album)|Turquoise]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Ragged & Dirty (album)|Ragged & Dirty]]'' (Ruf Records, 2014)\n* ''[[Ride or Die (album)|Ride or Die]]'' (2016)\n\n===Ocean Six===\n* Ocean Six \u2013 ''Somewhere Between Day and Night'' (2003): Guitar and vocals<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/somewhere-between-day-and-night-r656086/credits |title=Somewhere Between Day and Night - Ocean Six &#124; Credits |website=AllMusic |date=2003-09-09 |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Honeytribe===\n* ''[[Torch (Honeytribe album)|Torch]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Space Age Blues]]'' (2010)\n\n===Royal Southern Brotherhood===\n* ''[[Royal Southern Brotherhood (album)|Royal Southern Brotherhood]]'' (2012)\n* ''Songs from the Road (Live in Germany)'' (2013)\n* ''Heartsoulblood'' (2014)\n\n===Allman Betts Band===\n* ''[[Down To The River]]'' (2019)\n\n===Other contributions===\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Love, Union, Peace'' (2005): Vocals on \"Dance Away The Blues\", \"How Verso Are You?\", and \"Magic of the Gods\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-union-peace-r833111/credits |title=Love, Union, Peace - Vargas Blues Band &#124; Credits |website=AllMusic |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdloveunionpeace.htm |title=Love, Union, Peace |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425021117/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdloveunionpeace.htm |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref>\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Lost & Found'' (2007): Vocals on \"[[One Way Out (song)|One Way Out]]\", \"[[Statesboro Blues]]\" and \"[[Layla]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdlostandfound.htm |title=Lost & Found |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703202043/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdlostandfound.htm |archivedate=2008-07-03 }}</ref>\n* Various artists \u2013 ''[[A Song for My Father (album)|A Song for My Father]]'' (2007): \"[[Midnight Rider]]\"\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Flamenco Blues Experience'' (2008): Vocals on \"Blues In My Soul\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/flamenco-blues-experience-r1416825/credits |title=Flamenco Blues Experience - Vargas Blues Band &#124; Credits |website=AllMusic |date=2008-08-05 |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdflamencobluesexperience.htm |title=Flamenco Blues Experience |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425021155/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cdflamencobluesexperience.htm |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref>\n* Vargas Blues Band \u2013 ''Comes Alive With Friends'' (2009): Guitar and vocals on \"[[One Way Out (song)|One Way Out]]\", \"How Verso Are You?\", and \"[[Down by the River (Neil Young song)|Down by the River]]\"; vocals on \"Blues In My Soul\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdcomesalivewithfriends.htm |title=Vargas Blues Band Comes Alive With Friends! |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425021214/http://www.abbdiscography.com/cddvdcomesalivewithfriends.htm |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref>\n* Dan Bruder Band \u2013 ''Act of Kindness'' (2010)\n* [[Jeremiah Johnson (blues musician)|Jeremiah Johnson]] \u2013 Production work on ''Grind'' (2015)<ref name=\"Violet\">{{cite web|url=http://tickets.violetsvenue.com/events/past_event/67 |title=The Jeremiah Johnson Band and The Sliders|publisher=Tickets.violetsvenue.com |date=2015-06-20 |accessdate=2015-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==Musical equipment==\nAllman's primary guitar is a [[Gibson Les Paul]], which he calls \"Number One\". It is an exact, custom-shop replication of a '59.<ref name=\"interview20110804\">{{cite web |url=http://www.weissmanreport.com/2011-08-04-18-06-26/item/1808-devon-allman-the-ambassador-of-authenticity |title=Devon Allman: The Ambassador of Authenticity |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=2017-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425050524/http://www.weissmanreport.com/2011-08-04-18-06-26/item/1808-devon-allman-the-ambassador-of-authenticity |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref> It was signed by [[Les Paul]] when they played together at the [[Iridium Jazz Club]] in New York City in 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.kshe95.com/music/avplayer/devonallman.aspx |title=KSHE 95 = REAL ROCK RADIO |publisher=Kshe95.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAllman currently uses Fuchs Overdrive Supreme amplifiers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fuchsaudiotechnology.com/artists.php?id=allman_devon |title=Devon Allman &#124; Fuchs Audio Endorser |publisher=Fuchsaudiotechnology.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Miscellaneous projects==\nAllman appeared in the rock comedy series called ''Who the Hell is Dan Bruder'' which launched online June 2010. It is the story of a slightly delusional, middle-aged wannabe rocker who can not let go of the dream of stardom.\n\nIn 2011, Allman began marketing his \"Devon Allman's Chipotle Blues\" branded hot sauce via Born to Hula.<ref name=\"interview20110804\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://borntohula.com/ |title=::Born To Hula Hot Sauce:: |publisher=Borntohula.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.devonallmanproject.com/ Devon Allman Project]\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/devon-allman-p592877/biography Devon Allman biography on AllMusic.com]\n* [http://www.royalsouthernbrotherhood.com/ Royal Southern Brotherhood]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allman, Devon}}\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Texas]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Ruf Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devon_Allman"}
{"title_page": "Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\nMost '''[[expatriate]]s in the [[United Arab Emirates]]''' reside in [[Dubai]] and [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name=\"List\">{{cite web |last=Snoj |first=Jure |url=http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality |title=UAE's population - by nationality |publisher=Bqdoha.com |accessdate=1 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711160839/http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality |archivedate=11 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A number of expatriates settled in the country prior to [[History of the United Arab Emirates#Independence|independence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/heritage/former-expat-donates-snapshot-of-uae-history-to-the-emirates |title=Former expat donates snapshot of UAE history to the Emirates|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|publisher=Thenational.ae |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/personal-finance/uae-expats-priced-out-of-their-lives |title=UAE expats priced out of their lives|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The UAE is home to over 200 nationalities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/society/what-makes-uae-a-role-model-of-cohesion-1.1836341|title=What makes UAE a role model of cohesion|work=Gulf News|date=28 May 2016|accessdate=22 April 2017|first=Suchitra Bajpai|last=Chaudhry}}</ref> [[Emiratis]] constitute roughly 20% of the total population, making UAE home to one of the world's highest percentage of immigrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bq-magazine.com/economy/socioeconomics/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality|title=UAE\u00b4s population \u2013 by nationality|first=Jure|last=Snoj|work=BQ Magazine|date=12 April 2015|accessdate=22 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321184658/http://www.bq-magazine.com/economy/socioeconomics/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality|archivedate=21 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Indians in the United Arab Emirates|Indians]] and [[Pakistanis in the United Arab Emirates|Pakistanis]] form the largest expatriate groups in the country, constituting 28% <ref name=\"Pew research\">{{cite news|title=India is a top source and destination for world\u2019s migrants|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2017/03/03/india-is-a-top-source-and-destination-for-worlds-migrants/|accessdate=7 March 2017|work=Pew Research Center|date=3 March 2017}}</ref> and 12% of the total population respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/society/indians-pakistanis-make-up-37-of-dubai-sharjah-ajman-population-1.1562336|title=Indians, Pakistanis make up 37% of Dubai, Sharjah, Ajman population|first=Jumana Khamis, Staff|last=Reporter|date=6 August 2015|publisher=}}</ref> 461,000 [[Westerners]] live in the [[United Arab Emirates]], making up 5,1% of its total population.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">https://web.archive.org/web/20150711160839/http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality</ref><ref>https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/comment/the-other-special-relationship-the-uae-and-the-uk-1.549898</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe United Arab Emirates is the home of immigrants from all over the world; this may be because UAE nationals  prefer to work for the government or military.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/heritage/top-chef-wants-more-emiratis-to-try-a-career-in-the-kitchen |title=Top chef wants more Emiratis to try a career in the kitchen|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/emiratisation-wont-work-if-people-dont-want-to-learn |title=Emiratisation won't work if people don't want to learn|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=18 March 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>  The country's relatively liberal society compared to some of its neighbours has attracted many global expatriates, including people from [[Western world|western nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.yahoo.com/top-5-most-liberal-muslim-countries-1570105.html|title=Yahoo|website=Yahoo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729040734/http://voices.yahoo.com/top-5-most-liberal-muslim-countries-1570105.html|archivedate=29 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Emiratis are outnumbered in their own country by a ratio of nine to one. Under Article 8 of UAE Federal Law no. 17, an expatriate can apply for UAE citizenship after residing in the country for a period not less than 30 years, of which 20 years at least after the said law comes into force, providing that person has never been convicted of a crime and can speak fluent [[Arabic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ilovetheuae.com/2010/07/13/federal-law-no-17-concerning-nationality-and-passports|title=ilovetheuae.com|website=ilovetheuae.com|access-date=14 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226044910/http://ilovetheuae.com/2010/07/13/federal-law-no-17-concerning-nationality-and-passports|archive-date=26 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Arab League populations==\n\n===Algerians===\nAn estimated 10,000 [[Algeria]]ns live in the UAE\u2014one of the smallest Arab communities in the UAE.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n===Bahrainis===\nA small but unknown number of [[Bahrani people]] are present in the UAE.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/source/XXX/359/images/page1.pdf|title=Bahrainis in UAE safe|date=13 March 2008|accessdate=4 April 2015|work=Gulf Daily News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924043506/http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/source/XXX/359/images/page1.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bahrain is also a member of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC); this membership enables Bahraini nationals to enter the UAE without restrictions.\n\n===Comorians===\nMany members of the UAE's 10,000-strong stateless [[Bedoon (ethnicity)|Bedoon]] community have obtained [[Comoro Islands]] passports, providing them a legal status and a pathway towards naturalised UAE citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/heritage/bidoon-celebrate-uae-national-day-as-emiratis |title=UAE bidoon celebrate National Day as Emiratis |work=The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=24 November 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126150126/http://www.thenational.ae/uae/heritage/bidoon-celebrate-uae-national-day-as-emiratis |archivedate=26 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/citizenship-hope-for-uaes-stateless |title=Citizenship hope for UAE's stateless|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> This move came following the Comorian legislature's decision to sell Comorian nationalities to stateless Bedoons in the Gulf countries, including UAE, in return for these Gulf countries' economic investment in Comoros.<ref>{{cite web|last=Araxia |first=Atossa |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/11/10/kuwait-statelesscitizenshipcomoros.html |title=Kuwait offers stateless group citizenship \u2014 from Comoros|work= Al Jazeera America |publisher=America.aljazeera.com |date=10 November 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The number of such Bedoons with Comorian passports in the UAE is estimated to be at least a thousand.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hall |first=Camilla |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8abfc14a-a8aa-11e1-be59-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3WKh9eVbB |title=UAE's stateless acquire foreign passports |publisher=FT.com |date=4 June 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Egyptians===\nThere is a high number of [[Egyptians]] living in the [[UAE]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/community-reports/upbeat-egyptian-expatriates-vote-in-first-free-presidential-elections-1.1021717|title=Upbeat Egyptian expatriates vote in first free presidential elections|first=Samir Salama, Associate|last=Editor|date=12 May 2012|access-date=21 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516234516/http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/community-reports/upbeat-egyptian-expatriates-vote-in-first-free-presidential-elections-1.1021717|archive-date=16 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> forming the largest community of non-citizens from the Arab world in the UAE.\n\n===Iraqis===\n{{Main|Iraqis in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nIraqis in the UAE have a population exceeding 100,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzflash.com/mediawatch/05/01/wmw05009.html|title=Buzzflash Headlines|website=www.buzzflash.com|access-date=12 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606160625/http://www.buzzflash.com/mediawatch/05/01/wmw05009.html|archive-date=6 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most Iraqis are recent immigrants who fled instability at home; while Syria, Jordan, Iran and Lebanon were ultimate destinations for most refugees, a large number settled in the United Arab Emirates. In addition, an increasing number of Iraqi students seeking education and career opportunities opted for the country in light of its relatively reputable institutions across the [[Middle East]].\n\n===Jordanians===\n{{main|Jordanians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAs of 2009, the Jordanian population was estimated at 250,000,<ref>{{cite web|last=Husseini |first=Rana |url=http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=14910 |title=Jordan Times |publisher=Jordan Times |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> an increase from 80,000 in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.asp?StoryId=26140|title=Business & Financial - International News, Currencies & Economic Indicators|last=MENAFN|access-date=22 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306002844/http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.asp?StoryId=26140|archive-date=6 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> making them one of the largest Jordanian diaspora communities both worldwide and in the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|Persian Gulf]] region. Jordanian labour is in high value and demand throughout the country. A large number of Jordanians are highly qualified and occupy jobs that require skill and training. Most work in white-collar jobs as professors, managers, bankers, doctors, and engineers. The UAE remains a popular tourist destination for many Jordanians. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n===Kuwaitis===\nA small community of [[Kuwait]]is lives in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/multimedia/framed/spotlight/proud-to-be-kuwaiti-1.1153002 |title=Proud to be Kuwaiti |publisher=GulfNews.com |date=2 March 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531034641/http://gulfnews.com/multimedia/framed/spotlight/proud-to-be-kuwaiti-1.1153002 |archive-date=31 May 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It includes around 1,000 Kuwaiti students studying at eight universities across the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/kuwait-in-shock-over-death-of-sharjah-student-beaten-by-friends |title=Kuwait in shock over death of Sharjah student beaten by 'friends' |work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=27 February 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-251959007.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152913/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-251959007.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2015|title=Kuwaiti students in UAE to observe annual gathering.|date=19 March 2011|newspaper=Kuwait News Agency (Kuna)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2224776&Language=en |title=Kuwaiti students in UAE hold annual event - Education - 03/03/2012 |publisher=KUNA |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>  Kuwait is also a member of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC); this membership enables Kuwaiti nationals to live and work in the UAE without restrictions.\n\n===Lebanese===\n{{Main|Lebanese people in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAn estimated 80,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/01/lebanese-uae-fears-deportation.html|title=Lebanese Living in UAE Fear Deportation|date=21 January 2013|access-date=6 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016142536/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/01/lebanese-uae-fears-deportation.html|archive-date=16 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lebanese live in the UAE, mostly in Dubai, Abu Dhabi, and Sharjah. The UAE remains a popular touring destination for many Lebanese. The majority of [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] expatriates who work in the UAE are [[educated]], with some being fluent in both French and English languages. Many Lebanese are involved in business and the [[News media|media]] as plastic surgeons, businessmen, artists, presenters, hairdressers, and news anchors.\n\nOver 15,000 Lebanese companies operate in the [[Jebel Ali Free Zone]] alone, an economic hub located in [[Jebel Ali]], a city in Dubai. Notable Lebanese nationals who have lived in UAE include the late [[Antoine Choueiri]], the owner of the Middle East's largest media broker (Choueiri Group), which controls Arabian Media Services International, MEMS, Arabian Outdoor, Times International, Audio Visual Media, C Media, Press Media, Digital Media Services, Interadio, Promofair, AMC and SECOMM; and [[Elias Bou Saab]], the founder of the [[American University in Dubai]] (AUD).\n\n===Libyans===\nAn estimated 2,000 Libyans live in the UAE, forming one of the smaller non-citizen Arab communities. Many Libyans who have lived in exile in UAE for decades returned to Libya after the fall of the former Libyan regime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/libyans-in-uae-are-already-booking-their-tickets-home|title=Libyans in UAE are already booking their tickets home - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Mauritanians===\nAround 5,000 Mauritanians are residing and working in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/31/3106505_mauritania-africa-uea-terminates-contracts-of-mauritanians.html |title=The Global Intelligence Files - MAURITANIA/AFRICA-UEA terminates contracts of Mauritanians employed in police corps |publisher=Wikileaks.org |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=McDougall|first1=James|last2=Scheele|first2=Judith|title=Saharan Frontiers: Space and Mobility in Northwest Africa|date=2012|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253001245|page=178|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=OWONbhuKBlQC&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Moroccans===\nAn estimated 100,000 Moroccans live in the UAE. They form one of the biggest communities from North Africa of citizens from the Arab world in the UAE. Morocco and the UAE are known to be close allies.\n\n===Omanis===\nOmanis consist of expatriates and residents in the United Arab Emirates who hail from Oman. Being a bordering country and sharing cultural links, thousands of Omanis live in the U.A.E. They are predominantly Arabs and belong to the Muslim [[Ibadi]] sect.\n\nOmanis make a large percentage of the UAE's officer corps and also dominate the police forces.<ref>[http://www.jepeterson.net/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/Future_of_Federalism_in_UAE.pdf J.E. Peterson. The Future of Federalism in the United Arab Emirates], pp. 18</ref>\nMany are originally students pursuing higher education in various institutions across the country. In 2003, their number was estimated at over 9,000.<ref name=\"V\"/> According to the ''Times of Oman'', the United Arab Emirates is the most popular destination for Omani students who choose to study abroad; its close location and sharing of the language and culture makes them more comfortable at places like Dubai, Abu Dhabi, [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]] and the border town of [[Al Ain]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofoman.com/innercat.asp?detail=39494|title=More Omanis opting to study overseas|first=Aftab H.|last=Kola|work=Times of Oman|date=4 October 2010|accessdate=29 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617012859/http://www.timesofoman.com/innercat.asp?detail=39494|archivedate=17 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBoth countries have signed a memorandum of understanding aimed at providing benefits to Omani nationals and citizens in the UAE as well as treating Omani labour and work force at par with the country's nationals.<ref name=\"MOU\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oeronline.com/php/2006_july/inthe_news.php|title=Omani workers to get same status as UAE nationals|date=July 2006|work=Oman Economic Review|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522183909/http://www.oeronline.com/php/2006_july/inthe_news.php|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Being a member of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)]] (like the UAE) enables Omani nationals to move and work freely within the country and enjoy contrasting residential benefits as compared to expatriates in the UAE from non-GCC states.\n\nIn 2003, Omanis in the UAE were allowed to vote for council members in the elections of the [[Consultative Assembly of Oman|Omani Majlis al-Shura]]. It was the first-ever overseas [[suffrage]] in Oman's history.<ref name=\"V\">{{cite news |last=Bibbo |first=Barbara |date=28 September 2003 |title=Omanis in UAE allowed to vote in Shura council polls |url=http://www.mafhoum.com/press6/162S25.htm |newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Palestinians===\nAn estimated 100,000<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/report-uae-to-deport-hundreds-of-palestinians-by-month-s-end-1.8448|title=Report: UAE to Deport Hundreds of Palestinians by Month's End|first=Haaretz|last=Service|date=4 September 2009|publisher=|via=Haaretz|newspaper=Haaretz}}</ref> Palestinians live in the UAE and form one of the largest community of non-citizens from the Arab world in the UAE.\n\n===Qataris===\nSome [[Qatar]]i citizens are based in the UAE. Qatar was a member of the GCC and thus citizens of both countries were free to live and work in each other's countries without restrictions. The [[2017\u201318 Qatar diplomatic crisis]] began when several countries abruptly cut off diplomatic relations with Qatar in June 2017. These countries included Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt. The severing of relations included withdrawing ambassadors and imposing trade and travel bans.<ref>{{cite news |last=Al Ramahi |first=Nawal |title=Qataris in the UAE express cautious optimism over resolving dispute |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/qatar/qataris-in-the-uae-express-cautious-optimism-over-resolving-dispute-1.1305191 |newspaper=Gulf News |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ahmed Shaaban |url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/kt-article-display-1.asp?xfile=data/community/2013/June/community_June43.xml&section=community |title=Qataris in UAE hail Hamad's move to hand power to son |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author='+readFromCookie(\"jsonUserName\")+' |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/crime/qatari-cell-members-arrested-in-uae-1.1357928 |title=Qatari cell members arrested in UAE |publisher=GulfNews.com |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Also, Qatari citizens who have family members from the UAE will not be affected.<ref>https://www.thenational.ae/world/saudi-arabia-and-the-uae-exempt-qatari-spouses-caught-in-gcc-crisis-1.42885</ref>\n\n===Saudis===\nA total of 4,895 Saudis were living in the UAE in 2007;<ref>[http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=6&section=0&article=111912&d=17&m=7&y=2008&pix=business.jpg&category=Business Nearly 5,000 Saudis are living in UAE - Arab News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616060042/http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=6&section=0&article=111912&d=17&m=7&y=2008&pix=business.jpg&category=Business |date=16 June 2012 }}</ref> this number grew when a further 700 entered at the start of 2008.\n\nThey are mostly found working in the sectors of commerce and industry as well as medicine, law, insurance and shipping. Both the UAE and Saudi Arabia are Arab states and part of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]; according to agreements, the citizens of each GCC member can live and work in any of the six countries without a visa and other restrictions. The Saudis own a total of 1,357 houses and 1,450 pieces of land in various [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]] in the UAE.\n\n===Somalis=== \nMore 50,000 Somalis live in the United Arab Emirates.Many of these are people who settled in the UAE before its creation.There is up to 35,000 of people who are Citizens of Western Nations. They came as in the hopes to invest in the UAE.Since many Somali passport holders face many restrictions in the UAE, which makes it easier for Western Passport holders of Somali origin . There's a lot of Gold Stores, where people who left Western nations choose to invest in the UAE, while is closer to Somalia. The Somali Business Council based in Dubai regulates 175 Somali companies.<ref name=\"Cdsdhfc\">{{cite news|title=Dubai's Somali diaspora hope for change|url=http://english.cntv.cn/program/newsupdate/20120911/105653.shtml|accessdate=4 February 2015|agency=CCTV|date=11 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701165012/http://english.cntv.cn/program/newsupdate/20120911/105653.shtml|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Somali-owned businesses line the streets of [[Deira, Dubai|Deira]], the Dubai city centre,<ref name=\"Sciodb\">{{cite news|title=Somalis cash in on Dubai boom|url=http://newsvote.bbc.co.uk/mpapps/pagetools/print/news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4535642.stm|accessdate=29 January 2015|agency=BBC}}</ref> with only [[Iran]]ians exporting more products from the city at large.<ref>{{cite news|title=Forget piracy, Somalia's whole 'global' economy is booming - to Kenya's benefit|url=http://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/-/2558/914994/-/view/printVersion/-/yvxnho/-/index.html|accessdate=29 January 2015|agency=TEA}}</ref> [[Internet caf\u00e9]]s, [[hotel]]s, [[Coffeehouse|coffee shop]]s, [[restaurant]]s and [[International trade|import-export businesses]] are all testimony to the Somalis' entrepreneurial spirit. Star African Air is also one of three Somali-owned [[airline]]s based in Dubai.<ref name=\"Sciodb\"/>\n\n===Sudanese===\n79,000 Sudanese live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/> Most of them are based mainly in Dubai, with smaller populations in other emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle09.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2010/April/theuae_April278.xml&section=theuae|title=Sudanese expats cast votes in UAE|first=Amira|last=Agarib|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Syrians===\n{{Main|Syrians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nA large number of Syrians live in the UAE. Many of whom have been in the country since its prosperity, even before 1971. Syrians, similarly to the Lebanese, are educated and highly respected. Many Syrians have opened restaurants, opened businesses, and many of them work in both the public and private sectors. Most Syrians reside in Abu Dhabi, Dubai, and Sharjah.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/syrians-in-dubai-look-to-rebuild-homeland |title=Syrians in Dubai look to rebuild homeland|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=5 June 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Their population is over 242,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/government/uae-home-to-242000-syrians|title=UAE home to 242,000 Syrians|last=AP|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Tunisians===\nA small but unknown number of Tunisians live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates/1395278208262.html |title=Nahyan bin Mubarak attends Tunisian Embassy's reception |work=WAM |publisher=Wam.ae |date=20 March 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610135815/https://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates/1395278208262.html |archivedate=10 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abudhabinews.net/index.php/sid/231255149|title=Nahyan bin Mubarak attends Tunisian Embassys reception|access-date=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306135223/http://www.abudhabinews.net/index.php/sid/231255149|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tn.webradar.me/portal/2599846|title=WebRadar - Log in|website=tn.webradar.me}}</ref> There is a Tunisian Business Council based in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbcauh.ae/en/info/Members_Benefits|title=Members Benefits|website=tbcauh.ae}}</ref> There is also a web radio operated by the Tunisian community, known as 3ASLEMA Dubai.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.3aslemadubai.com/ |title= 3ASLEMA Dubai |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525213813/http://www.3aslemadubai.com/ |archivedate=25 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Yemenis===\nOver 98,000 Yemeni expatriates lives in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/news/463272|title=Etihad Airways introduces maiden flight to Sanaa|date=2 September 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==African populations==\n===Angolans===\nAround 900 [[Angola]]ns reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Chadians===\n200 [[Chad]]ian nationals reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Eritreans===\nThere were 3,000 to 4,000 Eritreans in the UAE as of 2010. 60% of them were women working as baby-sitters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/darticlen.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2010/June/theuae_June112.xml&section=theuae|title=Eritreans in UAE celebrate independence day|first=Afkar|last=Abdullah|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Ethiopians===\nAn estimated 100,000 Ethiopian nationals live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/business/uae-and-ethiopia-love-story-foreign-direct-investment-503605|title=The UAE and Ethiopia: a love story of foreign direct investment|date=2 July 2013|publisher=}}</ref> A large number of them are domestic workers, housemaids or involved in labour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/ethiopia-wants-dh1-200-minimum-wage-for-its-citizens-in-the-uae|title=Ethiopia wants Dh1,200 minimum wage for its citizens in the UAE - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/employers-of-ethiopian-maids-in-uae-urged-to-inform-embassy|title=Employers of Ethiopian maids in UAE urged to inform embassy - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Ghanaians===\nA community of over 300 [[Ghana]]ian expatriates live in the country. They have two main associations, the Ghana Community in Dubai and the Ghana Social Club in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=232388|title=Ghanaians in UAE Celebrate Ghana at 55|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref> Ghana has a consulate-general in Dubai serving the community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/artikel.php?ID=236432|title=Vice President  Interacts With Ghanaians In Dubai|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/artikel.php?ID=204383|title=Independence Day Celebration:  Ghanaians in Dubai|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/diaspora.news.php?country=AE|title=News About Ghanaian Community in United Arab Emirates|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/artikel.php?ID=313817|title=Ghanaians in Abu Dhabi Elect New Leaders|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref>\n\n===Kenyans===\nKenyans in the United Arab Emirates had an estimated population numbering 50,000 in 2019. Of these, many work in Dubai in the hospitality and construction industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hseassignmentabroad.in/blog|title=Abroad Experience in Kuwait|author=Hybridrain|date=December 2019 |website=hseassignmentabroad.in}}</ref>\n\n===Nigerians===\nAround 2,000 to 5,000 Nigerians live in UAE. Notable Nigerians living in the [[UAE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaeinteract.com/docs/Nigerian_President_receives_outgoing_UAE_envoy/62002.htm|title=UAE Interact, United Arab Emirates information, news, photographs, maps and webcams|last=UAEINTERACT|website=www.uaeinteract.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201310180816.html|title=Nigeria: Why People Visit Dubai|first=Shehu|last=Abubakar|date=18 October 2013|publisher=|via=AllAfrica}}</ref>\n\n===Senegalese===\nThe population of [[Senegal]]ese people in the UAE is around 700 to 800.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===South Africans===\n{{main|South Africans in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===South Sudanese===\nA South Sudanese community is present in the UAE. They are mainly Christians. They were treated as part of the Sudanese community; however, after [[South Sudan]] achieved independence from [[Sudan]] in 2011, South Sudanese expatriates living in the UAE were required to apply for new [[South Sudanese passport]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/south-sudanese-in-uae-fear-diplomatic-limbo|title=South Sudanese in UAE fear diplomatic limbo - The National|publisher=}}</ref> The UAE airline [[flydubai]] operates several flights a week from Dubai to [[Juba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flydubai.com/en/news/article/flydubai-makes-maiden-flight-to-juba/|title=flydubai makes maiden flight to Juba<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Ugandans===\nA small number of Ugandans live in Dubai. There is a Ugandans in Dubai Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/dh20-000-to-send-a-body-home-from-uae-for-burial|title=Dh20,000 to send a body home from UAE for burial - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/676843|title=Ugandan robs bank in Dubai<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141022160604/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/676843|archivedate=22 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Zimbabweans===\nA number of Zimbabweans live in Dubai, although their population is unknown. They are mainly employed in the tourism and hospitality sectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b-metro.co.zw/dubai-mystery-revealed/|title=Dubai mystery revealed|work=B-Metro|first=Nhlalwenhle |last=Ncube|date=2 March 2015|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Central Asian populations==\n===Kazakhs===\nMost Kazakhs are business people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/kazakh-community-celebrates-independence-day-1.149859|title=Kazakh community celebrates Independence Day|first=Binsal Abdul Kader, Staff|last=Reporter|date=20 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref> The Kazakhstan Society in UAE is an association of Kazakh expatriates based in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vk.com/club5112953|title=\u2654=====KAZAKHSTAN=====\u2654 \u2654=======SOCIETY======\u2654 \u2654=========in========\u2654 \u2654========UAE========\u2654|website=vk.com}}</ref> As of 2015, the population was 5,000 to 6,000.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Kyrgyz===\nUp to 4,000 Kyrgyz expatriates were residing and working in the UAE as of 2012. There is a Kyrgyz Club in Dubai and the community celebrates events such as the Independence Day of Kyrgyzstan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/dubai-s-kyrgyz-community-come-together-for-independence-day-1.1069496|title=Dubai's Kyrgyz community come together for Independence Day|first=Jumana Khamis, Staff|last=Reporter|date=3 September 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyrgyzclub.org/en/Global/64|title=About us|publisher=Kyrgyz Club}}</ref>\n\n===Tajiks===\nEthnic Tajiks living in the UAE hail from [[Tajikistan]] and Afghanistan. They celebrate cultural events including [[Nowruz]].<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/dubai-expats-celebrate-persian-new-year-nowruz-1.1306593|title=Dubai expats celebrate Persian New Year Nowruz|first=Faisal|last=Masudi|date=20 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Uzbeks===\nA small number of Uzbeks live and work in the UAE. They celebrate cultural events such as [[Nowruz]].<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/a-bit-like-attending-college-departing-expat-looks-back-on-his-uae-experience|title=A bit like attending college: departing expat looks back on his UAE experience - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uznews.net/en/society/23666-shoot-me-why-is-dubai-so-desirable|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141020133402/http://www.uznews.net/en/society/23666-shoot-me-why-is-dubai-so-desirable|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-10-20|title=\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440-1 / Centre1.com - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|website=\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440-1 / Centre1.com - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438}}</ref> Their number has grown to about 14,000 in 2016 from 4000 in 2014.\n\n==East Asian populations==\n===Chinese===\n{{see also|Chinese people in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Japanese===\nAlmost 4,000 Japanese live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/region/middle_e/uae/index.html|title=Japan-United Arab Emirates Relations|website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan}}</ref> Over 2,000 of them reside in Dubai, making the city home to the largest Japanese community in the whole of the Arab world.<ref name=\"AME\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ameinfo.com/112883.html|title=JAFZA home to Hitachi Construction Machinery's new regional centre|date=7 March 2007|work=[[AMEinfo.com]]|accessdate=21 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828111024/http://www.ameinfo.com/112883.html|archivedate=28 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Japan]] also maintains a sizeable trade presence in the UAE through representative offices of multinational corporations and organisations; as of 2007, there were an estimated 105 Japanese companies operating in the [[Jebel Ali Free Zone]] alone.<ref name=\"AME\"/>\n\nAccording to registrations based with local embassies and consulates, the community has been growing at an average of 20 percent per year, much larger than the population during the 1980s when only a few hundred Japanese expatriates lived in the country.<ref name=\"Judo\">{{cite news |last=Constantine |first=Zoi |date=11 October 2007 |title='I planted a judo seed in the desert' |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/i-planted-a-judo-seed-in-the-desert-1.206249 |newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=21 November 2010}}</ref> The Japanese have introduced [[judo]] in the country. Most immigrants are principally skilled workers employed in white-collar business and industry sectors. Dubai has one Japanese association and there is also a [[Dubai Japanese School]], which is based on Japanese curriculum. The [[Japanese School in Abu Dhabi]] also serves Japanese expatriates.\n\n===Koreans===\nApproximately 3,100 Koreans live in the United Arab Emirates.<ref name=\"MOFAT\">{{Citation|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade |location=South Korea |year=2009 |accessdate=21 May 2009 |url=http://www.mofat.go.kr/consul/overseascitizen/compatriotcondition/index6.jsp?TabMenu=TabMenu6 |title={{asiantitle|\uc7ac\uc678\ub3d9\ud3ec\ud604\ud669||Current Status of Overseas Compatriots|a}} |ref=none |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023213104/http://www.mofat.go.kr/consul/overseascitizen/compatriotcondition/index6.jsp?TabMenu=TabMenu6 |archivedate=23 October 2010 }}</ref> The United Arab Emirates received a small contingent of Korean migrant workers in the late 1970s and early 1980s, but it was never a major destination.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Seok|first=Hyunho|chapter=Korean migrant workers to the Middle East|title=Migration to the Arab World: Experience of Returning Migrants|editor-last=Gunatilleke|editor-first=Godfrey|pages=56\u201358|publisher=United Nations University Press|year=1991|isbn=978-92-808-0745-5}}</ref> However, due to rapid growth since 2005, the country has come to have the Arab world's largest Korean population.<ref name=\"MOFAT\"/> {{as of|2008}}, roughly 2,500 South Koreans live in [[Dubai]] alone, largely businessmen working at the 90 Korean companies in the country.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?section=theuae&xfile=data/theuae/2008/february/theuae_february897.xml|date=26 February 2008|accessdate=22 May 2009|title=South Korea to open consulate in Dubai|periodical=Khaleej Times}}</ref> There were also many flight attendants working for [[Emirates Airlines]]; the number of Koreans working for Emirates Airlines increased from 15 in 1998 to 620 as of 2007, mostly based out of Dubai. Dubai has the UAE's largest community of South Koreans.<ref>{{citation|title=Korean Female Crew Capture Middle East|periodical=Chosun Ilbo|date=4 May 2007|accessdate=4 May 2007|url=http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200705/200705040012.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070510014534/http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200705/200705040012.html|archivedate=10 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, a consulate was not opened in Dubai until March 2008.<ref>{{citation|url=http://are-dubai.mofat.go.kr/eng/af/are-dubai/mission/about/index.jsp|title=About us|publisher=The Consulate General of the Republic of Korea in Dubai|accessdate=22 May 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405235607/http://are-dubai.mofat.go.kr/eng/af/are-dubai/mission/about/index.jsp|archivedate=5 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRoughly 1,300 North Korean workers live in the UAE, primarily in Dubai and [[Abu Dhabi]]. They earn between US$300 and $500 per month, but must make so-called \"loyalty payments\" of $150 to $250 to the North Korean government. This has sparked discontent among those workers\u2014and in response, the North Korean government has sent security agents to patrol North Korean work camps and look for people making critical comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/12/25/2009122500238.html|title=N.Korean Workers Brave Hard Times in UAE|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Won Ho Chung]] is a famous Arabic language comedian of Korean origin who is based in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wonhochung.com/|title=Wonho Chung|website=Wonho Chung}}</ref> In 2010, Chung was appointed goodwill ambassador for the Korea Tourism Organization in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/content/cms_view_994589.jsp|title=The First Ethnic Korean Comedian of the Middle East|website=english.visitkorea.or.kr}}</ref>\n\n===Mongolians===\nAbout 6,100 of [[Mongols|Mongolians]] working in [[Dubai]] and [[Abu Dhabi]].\n\n===Taiwanese===\nAround 400 [[Taiwan]]ese people reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n==South Asian populations==\n\n===Bangladeshis===\nOver 500,000 Bangladeshis live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdnews24.com/economy/2016/10/10/uae-to-consider-taking-bangladesh-workers-in-future|title=UAE to consider taking Bangladesh workers in future - bdnews24.com|website=bdnews24.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/displayarticle.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2010/February/theuae_February665.xml&section=theuae&col=|title=Bangladeshis Observe Martyrs' Day|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref> Expatriates from [[Bangladesh]] in the United Arab Emirates form one of the largest communities along with others hailing from the [[Indian subcontinent]]. They are spread out over the various [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]] of the country, with many based in Dubai and [[Abu Dhabi]]. A sizeable number of the South Asian labour force in the UAE is from Bangladesh. In the fiscal year 2005-2006, remittances from Bangladeshis were marked up to US$512.6M.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200609/04/eng20060904_299331.html|title=People's Daily Online  -- Expatriate Bangladeshis in UAE remit more money home|last=english@peopledaily.com.cn|website=english.peopledaily.com.cn}}</ref>\n\nA number of Bangladeshi-curriculum schools operate in the UAE, including the [[Shaikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Bangladesh Islamia School]] in Abu Dhabi.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n===Bhutanese===\nMost Bhutanese nationals in the UAE are labour force and service industry workers. Employ Bhutan Overseas is a Bhutanese government-authorized employment agency that sends Bhutanese workers to the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.employbhutanoverseas.com/|title=Home|work=Employ Bhutan Overseas|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Indians===\n{{main|Indians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Nepalese===\nNepalese in the United Arab Emirates are a large community numbering around 125,258; of these, 75,000 are in [[Dubai]], some 30,000 in [[Abu Dhabi]] remaining are spread out over the northern [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]]. As per IOM Report of 2012-14, most of [[Nepalese people|Nepalese]] migrant workers in [[UAE]] number up to 97,874.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://nepal.iom.int/jupgrade/index.php/en/press-room/18-topic-details/115-art-latest-news-28|title=Total hill and Madheshi migrant workers in UAE}}</ref>\nOut of the population, half are labour migrants in the construction sector, while others work in hospitality and security services (as security guards). Nepalese security guards are popular in the UAE for their trustworthiness.<ref>{{citation|last=Abdul Kader|first=Binsal|title=Number of Nepalese in UAE steady|periodical=Gulf News|date=17 May 2010|accessdate=17 July 2010|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/number-of-nepalese-in-uae-steady-1.627869}}</ref> There are also some skilled professionals.\n\nAs part of curbing illegal migration, the UAE made new amendments to visit visa regulations in 2008. According to experts, the changes were likely to affect Nepalese the most, along with Indians and Pakistanis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/new-uae-visa-rules-likely-to-affect-indians-pakistanis-and-nepalis_10075731.html|title=New UAE visa rules likely to affect Indians, Pakistanis and Nepalis|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistanis===\n{{main|Pakistanis in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Sri Lankans===\nSri Lankans in the United Arab Emirates have grown to a population of over 300,000;<ref>{{cite news |last=Abdul Kade |first=Binsal |title=Sri Lankan expats to get free IT and English language training |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/sri-lankan-expats-to-get-free-it-and-english-language-training-1.975908|newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AG\">{{cite news |title=Sri Lankans in UAE asked to register themselves |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/sri-lankans-in-uae-asked-to-register-themselves-1.28877 |newspaper=Gulf News |date=24 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711135608/http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/sri-lankans-in-uae-asked-to-register-themselves-1.28877 |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> they mostly form the country's large foreign labour force. In 2009, community members were urged to register themselves. A lack of community data has often resulted in difficulties in reaching out to the community at the time of major announcements, rules and regulation.<ref name=\"AG\"/> Most expatriates from Sri Lanka, along with other immigrants from the [[Indian subcontinent]], tend to be found in [[Dubai]], although sizeable communities are existent in [[Abu Dhabi]], [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]], [[Al-Ain]] and [[Ras al-Khaimah]].\n\nThere is a huge demand for Sri Lankan Quantity Surveyors, Commercial Managers and Contract Administrators in ever expanding UAE construction industry. They are usually highly paid due to the high demand for their quality of professionalism. Not only them, there are lots of Sri Lankans well off in UAE banking and hotel/tourism industries.\n\n==Southeast Asian populations==\n===Burmese===\nAround 10,000 reside in the UAE.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/myanmar-violence-traps-rohingya-bangladesh-border-170826101215439.html|title=Myanmar troops open fire on civilians fleeing attacks|work=Al Jazeera|date=27 August 2017|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cambodians===\nAround 7,600 [[Khmer people]] reside and work in [[Dubai]], [[Sharjah]], and [[Abu Dhabi]].\n\n===Filipinos===\n{{main|Filipinos in the United Arab Emirates}}\nAn estimated 700,000 expatriates from the [[Philippines]] live or work in the UAE. Particularly in [[Dubai]], [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Al-Ain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-filipinos-rejoice-as-cebu-pacific-arrives-with-cheap-deals-2013-01-21-1.491817|title=Dubai Filipinos rejoice as Cebu Pacific arrives with cheap deals|first=Bindu Suresh|last=Rai|date=21 January 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesians===\n{{main|Indonesians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Laotians===\nAround 62,500 [[Lao people|Laotians]] living and working in the United Arab Emirates.\n\n===Malaysians===\nThere were 6,000 Malaysians living and working in the United Arab Emirates as of 2010. Most are found in [[Dubai]] and can be seen working with foreign and local companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2010/1/25/nation/5536408&sec=nation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128011812/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2010%2F1%2F25%2Fnation%2F5536408&sec=nation|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2010|title=Looking to the Middle East|work=The Star Online|date=25 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In addition, a small number of Malaysian pilots work for the Abu Dhabi-based [[Etihad Airways]]. {{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n===Singaporeans===\nThere is a small community of Singaporeans in the UAE numbering around 2,100, the largest Singaporean community in the Middle East.<ref name=\"Singaporeans\"/> The community includes Singaporean Malays, [[Chinese Singaporean]]s and [[Indian Singaporeans]]. Dubai has three Singaporean expatriate clubs: the Singapore Business Council (SBC), Singapore Malay-Muslim Group (SMG) and the Singapore Women's Group (SWG).<ref name=\"Singaporeans\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/singapore-embassy-in-uae-hosts-national-day-celebrations-1.1231843|title=Singapore Embassy in UAE hosts National Day celebrations|first=Staff|last=Report|date=16 September 2013|publisher=}}</ref> Many Singaporeans visit the UAE for tourism or transit through its airports.\n\n===Thais===\nThais in the United Arab Emirates are based predominantly in [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Dubai]]. Smaller populations also live in the northern [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]]. A significant number of Thais work in the construction sector. In 2006, there were some 3,500 Thai workers in Dubai alone. This figure jumped to 6,500 in 2007 and recent numbers are predicted to be as high as 8,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/opinions/columnists/the-missing-pillar-in-thai-gulf-ties-1.103442|title=The missing pillar in Thai-Gulf ties|first=Abdullah Al Madani, Special to Gulf|last=News|date=4 May 2008|access-date=31 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718084949/http://gulfnews.com/opinions/columnists/the-missing-pillar-in-thai-gulf-ties-1.103442|archive-date=18 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The UAE and Thailand have signed a memorandum of understanding aimed at protecting the rights of Thai workers living and working in the UAE.\n\n=== Vietnamese ===\nMore than 5,000 Vietnamese nationals and people of Vietnamese descent live in the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/government/169253/na-chairwoman-s-uae-trip-to-improve-vietnam-s-stature.html|title=NA Chairwoman's UAE trip to improve Vietnam's stature - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other populations==\n===Afghans===\nAbout 150,000 [[Afghans]] live in the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/afghans-take-hope-from-uae-s-achievements-1.1112640|title=Afghans take hope from UAE's achievements|first=Shafaat Shahbandari, Staff|last=Reporter|date=30 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nExpatriate Afghan businessmen, traders, and entrepreneurs formed an Afghan Business Council of Dubai in 2005. The organisation strives to develop economic, cultural, and social relations between Afghanistan and the UAE, and to promote the interests of the Dubai Afghan business community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcdxb.com/|title=Afghan Business Council|website=www.abcdxb.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Afghan community in the UAE forms the second largest diaspora of Afghans after the [[United States]].\n\n===Albanians===\nAround 50 to 3000 [[Albania]]ns reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Americans===\n{{Main|Americans in the United Arab Emirates}}\nAmericans in the United Arab Emirates form one of the largest Western expatriate communities in the [[UAE]]. Over 50,000 United States nationals reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/> The bulk of these live in Dubai while sizable populations are also found in Abu Dhabi. According to statistics produced in 1999, there were 7,500 United States citizens in Abu Dhabi and as many as 9,000 United States citizens in Dubai.<ref>[http://www.overseasdigest.com/amcit_nu2.htm Private American Citizens Residing Abroad] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326040310/http://www.overseasdigest.com/amcit_nu2.htm |date=26 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Argentines===\nArgentines in the United Arab Emirates are 2,000 and form the third largest community of Argentines in the Middle East (after Lebanon and Israel) and are mainly expatriates (bankers, pilots, stewards and technicians  {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} working with the two main airlines in the country) and professional footballers playing in the [[UAE Football League]]. Even the legendary Argentine player [[Diego Maradona]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/maradona-named-as-coach-at-al-wasl.aspx?pageID=238&nID=7144&NewsCatID=364|title=Maradona named as coach at Al-Wasl - MIDEAST|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News - LEADING NEWS SOURCE FOR TURKEY AND THE REGION}}</ref> was an expat for a while in UAE.\n\n===Azerbaijanis===\nAzerbaijanis in United Arab Emirates number around 12,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diaspora.az|title=Diaspora.az|website=Diaspora.az}}</ref> This figure however, only includes Azerbaijani nationals and not ethnic Azerbaijanis from Iran, otherwise the figure would be much higher. The Azerbaijanis mostly live in Dubai, Abu Dhabi and Sharjah.\n\n===Armenians===\nArmenians in United Arab Emirates number around 3,000.<ref>{{in lang|hy}} [http://encyclopedia.am/pages.php?bId=1&hId=71&sWord=Array \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0565\u0580\u0568 \u0531\u0544\u0537-\u0578\u0582\u0574]. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\n===Australians===\n{{Main|Australians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAustralians in the United Arab Emirates consist of 7,000 expatriates, half of whom live in the capital of Abu Dhabi (3,500) and the other half of whom live in  Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southern-cross-group.org/archives/Statistics/Numbers_of_Australians_Overseas_in_2001_by_Region_Feb_2002.pdf|title=Statistics - Numbers of Australians Overseas in 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720101723/http://www.southern-cross-group.org/archives/Statistics/Numbers_of_Australians_Overseas_in_2001_by_Region_Feb_2002.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAustralians have been attracted by the lifestyle Dubai offers, including the wealth of outdoor activities for their families.<ref>[http://gulfnews.com/in-focus/australia/living-it-up-in-dubai-1.28037 Gulfnews: InFocus Australia - Living it up in Dubai] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020200022/http://gulfnews.com/in-focus/australia/living-it-up-in-dubai-1.28037 |date=20 October 2012 }}</ref> However, their population fell in 2009 due to the downturn in the [[economy of Dubai]], as retrenched Australian expatriates with underwater real-estate loans fled the country to avoid [[debtor's prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/debt-laden-jobless-aussies-flee-dubai/news-story/76649c215e51f9e8d2417e142586a13a|title=Debt-laden jobless Aussies flee Dubai|date=9 May 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Dubai, Australian and New Zealander expatriates joined together to set up the Australia New Zealand Association, which aims to provide mutual support for their communities in the entire UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/australian-expatriates-celebrate-national-day-1.46995|title=Australian expatriates celebrate national day|first=Kevin Scott, Staff|last=Reporter|date=26 January 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian International School in [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]] is an established international school, catering to much of the Australian community. The school's education system and syllabus is [[Queensland]]-curriculum based.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ais.ae/|title=Australian International School|website=www.ais.ae}}</ref>\n\n===Austrians===\nThe UAE is home to 1,800 Austrians, and 36 Austrian companies operate directly in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/politics/uae-urges-austria-to-change-stance-on-euro-visa-free-travel|title=UAE urges Austria to change stance on euro visa-free travel - The National|access-date=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821060223/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/politics/uae-urges-austria-to-change-stance-on-euro-visa-free-travel|archive-date=21 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \nJumeirah Park in Dubai, as of 2019, is the preferred neighborhood for Austrians living in Dubai.\n\n===Belarusians===\nAround 2,500 [[Belarus]]ians reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Belgians===\n3,000 Belgians reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Bosnians===\nA community of Bosnian expatriates lives in the UAE, numbering from 1,000 to 2,000.<ref name=\"List\"/> In 2014, the Bosnian community of Dubai provided humanitarian aid to affectees of floods in Bosnia and also in Serbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/serbian-and-bosnian-communities-rally-aid-for-flood-victims-1.1336117|title=Serbian and Bosnian communities rally aid for flood victims|first=Janice Ponce de Leon, Staff|last=Reporter|date=21 May 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilians===\nBrazilians in the United Arab Emirates are the third largest community of Brazilians in the Middle East (after Israel and Lebanon) and are mainly expatriates and professional footballers. In 2002, up to 235 Brazilians were reported  living in the country ([[Abu Dhabi]] and Dubai).<ref>[http://www.acontece.com/?act=25&actB=6 Estimates of Brazilians living abroad by region] (''Portuguese'')</ref> These figures increased ten-fold, with data disclosed by the embassy of Brazil in Abu Dhabi putting the number as high as 2,000 by 2010.<ref name=\"AN\">{{cite news|url=http://www2.anba.com.br/noticia_especiais.kmf?cod=10525305|title=Brazilian immigrants in the Arab world|work=Brazil-Arab News Agency|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204190550/http://www2.anba.com.br/noticia_especiais.kmf?cod=10525305|archive-date=4 December 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most immigrants are pilots, stewards and technicians working with the two main airlines in the country, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] and [[Etihad Airways|Etihad]]. The Emirates airline alone has over 100 Brazilian pilots and 600 [[Flight attendant|stewards]].<ref name=\"AN\"/> Brazil also has a large business presence in the UAE, with representative offices for several [https://www.makinabook.com/ construction companies], exporters and banks.\nFootballers from Brazil top the list of foreigners playing in the [[UAE Football League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.emirates247.com/sports/football/13-brazilians-in-uae-football-clubs-2010-09-15-1.291242|title=13 Brazilians in UAE football clubs|work=[[Emirates Business 24/7]]|date=15 September 2010}}</ref> The UAE remains a popular touring destination for many Brazilians and airlines provide links between both countries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwood |first=Gemma |date=23 March 2008 |title=Brazilians to flock to Dubai |url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/brazilians-flock-dubai-52059.html |work=[[Arabian Business]]}}</ref>\n\n===British===\nBritish presence in the country dates back to the 19th century, when the region was a protectorate. In 2012, there were an estimated 240,000 Britons living in the country, representing the largest [[Western world|western community]] in the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/news-comment/the-other-special-relationship-the-uae-and-the-uk|title=The other special relationship: the UAE and the UK - The National|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to 2008, there were 120,000 expatriates holding British passports in the UAE. However, after the [[Late-2000s recession in Europe|2008 UK recession]] another 120,000 British nationals emigrated to the UAE to find work, doubling their numbers within a period of just four years. Most Britons took their entire families with them.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} The main localities where British citizens are based include Dubai, [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]]. A number of Britons working in the UAE are high-salary white-collar job professionals. Probationary work permits are valid for up to three months for Britons. In the 2010 UK general elections, following a drop in sterling, UAE-based British expats were seen taking advantage by sending increased funds back home to the [[UK]], with the number of [[United Arab Emirates dirham|dirham]] trades flowing back to the UK rising by over 40 percent in two days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/588002-uk-expats-take-advantage-of-weak-sterling|title=UK expats take advantage of weak sterling|publisher=|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515123824/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/588002-uk-expats-take-advantage-of-weak-sterling|archive-date=15 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Bulgarians===\nAround 7,000 [[Bulgaria]]ns live in the UAE, the largest population of Bulgarian people in the Arab World.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulgaria-news.bg/category/world/tourism/article/post1110.html|script-title=bg:\u0429\u0415 \u041f\u0420\u0418\u0412\u041b\u0418\u0427\u0410\u041c\u0415 \u0422\u0423\u0420\u0418\u0421\u0422\u0418 \u041e\u0422 \u041e\u0410\u0415 \u0427\u0420\u0415\u0417 \u0414\u0418\u0420\u0415\u041a\u0422\u041d\u0418 \u041f\u041e\u041b\u0415\u0422\u0418|first=Toxic Media|last=Ltd.|website=www.bulgaria-news.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nazmibaycin.com|title=www.nazmibaycin.com|first=\u0413\u0438\u043c\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0437\u044a\u043c \u0441\u0435 \u0432\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0438 \u0432|last=Editor|date=15 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref> They mostly live in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plovdivmedia.com/6345.html|title=- www.PlovdivMedia.com|website=www.plovdivmedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloomstart.eu/bg/index.php?action=addon_news_article&id=56 |title=\u0412 \u0442\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u044f\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430  |accessdate=6 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417113810/http://www.bloomstart.eu/bg/index.php?action=addon_news_article&id=56 |archivedate=17 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Canadians===\n{{see also|Canadians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAround 40,000 Canadians live in the United Arab Emirates as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/visa/canada-may-limit-services-for-dual-citizens-1.1277888|title=Canada may limit services for dual citizens|first=Mick O\u2019Reilly Senior Associate|last=Editor|date=15 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/business/story.html?id=71a7f906-61d3-4be2-b4f3-7eae5c8df15f&p=1 Dubai Mighty Camels playing our game - Canada.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007015148/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/business/story.html?id=71a7f906-61d3-4be2-b4f3-7eae5c8df15f&p=1 |date=7 October 2015 }}</ref> There is a Canadian Club in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubforcanadians-dubai.com/|title=ClubForCanadiansDubai \u2013 Just another WordPress site|website=www.clubforcanadians-dubai.com}}</ref>\n\n===Caribbeans===\nThe Caribbean community in UAE numbers around 2,000 as of 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Celebrating-Ja-in-Dubai_17270367|title=Celebrating Ja in Dubai|first=Jamaica Observer|last=Limited|website=Jamaica Observer}}</ref> which is an increase since 2006 when it barely numbered 100. The majority of them are [[Jamaica]]ns, and a few dozen Jamaican pilots are presently working for the Emirates airline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/heritage-culture/cool-and-caribbean-1.24564|title=Cool and Caribbean!|first=Shalaka|last=Paradkar|date=4 May 2006|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationwideradiojm.com/jamaicans-languishing-in-dubai-prison/|title=Jamaicans Languishing in Dubai Prison - Nationwide 90FM - Jamaica|website=nationwideradiojm.com}}</ref>\n\n===Chileans===\nAround 270 [[Chile]]ans live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Colombians===\n{{see also|Colombian people in the United Arab Emirates}}\nOver 14,000 Colombians live in the [[United Arab Emirates]], primarily in [[Dubai]]. Is one of the biggest growing communities in the country, and is the second Latin American community after Brazilians. They work in the tourism sector in Dubai, as footballers.\n\n===Croatians===\nOver 500 Croatians are currently living in the UAE, primarily in Dubai. The community is growing. Migration occurred in two waves, with the first wave taking place 15 years ago and the latest and larger wave comprising recent migrants. Croatians can be found working as cooks, stewards, waiters and in white-collar positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatiaweek.com/croatian-community-growing-in-dubai/|title=Croatian Community Growing In Dubai|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Cubans===\nA small Cuban community is present in Dubai. The population has increased over the years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubaminrex.cu/en/cubans-living-dubai-meet-cuban-ambassador|title=Cubans living in Dubai meet with Cuban Ambassador - CubaMINREX<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402172803/http://www.cubaminrex.cu/en/cubans-living-dubai-meet-cuban-ambassador|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/cubans-in-uae-see-no-changes-with-power-transfer-1.248243|title=Cubans in UAE see no changes with power transfer|first=Emmanuelle Landais, Staff|last=Reporter|date=31 July 2006|publisher=}}</ref> Cuban [[cigar]]s are popular in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/the-life/cigar-smokers-hold-fierce-to-tradition-in-the-uae|title=Cigar smokers hold fierce to tradition in the UAE - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/features/cigar-sales-in-the-uae-light-up-1.1030625|title=Cigar sales in the UAE light up|first=Mick O'Reilly, Senior Associate|last=Editor|date=1 June 2012|publisher=}}</ref> Cuban food and salsa clubs are available in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ritmo-de-havana.com/about-us/|title=About - Ritmo de Havana|access-date=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009185028/http://www.ritmo-de-havana.com/about-us/|archive-date=9 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Cypriots===\nAs many as 1,000 [[Cyprus|Cypriots]] live in the UAE. They are mainly involved in the construction and trading industry. Others work as pilots and aeronautical engineers with local airlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/tourism/emiratis-visa-free-travel-to-europe-applauded-by-cyprus|title=Emiratis' visa-free travel to Europe applauded by Cyprus - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Czechs===\nAround 1,500 [[Czechs]] reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Danes===\nAs of 2010, their number was around 2,000, up from just 400 since 2005.<ref>[http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100422/NATIONAL/704219884/1010/rss Danes to reopen embassy in Abu Dhabi: The National (UAE)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223070044/http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20100422%2FNATIONAL%2F704219884%2F1010%2Frss |date=23 February 2014 }}</ref> The [[Danes|Danish]] community of Dubai has founded a cultural organisation known as ''Danes in Dubai'', which aims at fostering relations between Denmark and the UAE.<ref>[http://www.danesindubai.com/script/site/page.asp?artid=25&cat_id=27 Danes in Dubai - Official homepage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708223621/http://www.danesindubai.com/script/site/page.asp?artid=25&cat_id=27 |date=8 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Dominicans===\nAround 2,000 to 3,000 [[Dominican Republic|Dominicans]] reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Dutch===\nCurrently there is a growing population of Dutch nationals. As of 2011 members of the community number at 4,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/dutch-consulate-opens-newoffice-in-dubai-marina-1.918111|title=Dutch consulate opens newoffice in Dubai Marina|first=Janice Ponce de Leon, Staff|last=Reporter|date=25 October 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Fijians===\nA small Fijian community numbering in the hundreds exists in the UAE, based in Dubai, Abu Dhabi, Al Ain and other places.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/lifestyle/house-home/were-the-only-fijians-in-rak|title='We're the only Fijians in RAK' - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mailife.com.fj/president-visits-fijian-community-in-the-emirates/|title=President visits Fijian community in the Emirates - Mai Life Magazine|website=www.mailife.com.fj|date=21 May 2014}}</ref> They include both native Fijians and [[Indians in Fiji|Indo-Fijians]]. New job opportunities have prompted some Fijians to migrate to the UAE. Most Fijians in the UAE can be found working in retail, tourism and hospitality, as nurses,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Connell|first1=John|title=The Global Health Care Chain: From the Pacific to the World|date=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135912826|pages=111, 112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lkuSAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 }}</ref> pilots,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/fiji-interested-in-airline-partnership-with-uae|title=Fiji interested in airline partnership with UAE - The National|publisher=}}</ref> seafarers teachers, hotel workers, sportspeople and in other jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijilive.com/news/2013/02/new-uae-job-opportunities-for-fijians/52044.Fijilive|title=New UAE job opportunities for Fijians<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028060602/http://fijilive.com/news/2013/02/new-uae-job-opportunities-for-fijians/52044.Fijilive|archivedate=28 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/10/14/fiji-embassy-uae-hosts-first-fiji-day-celebrations/|title=FIJI EMBASSY UAE HOSTS FIRST FIJI DAY CELEBRATIONS - THE JET - Fiji's First Community Newspaper|last=admin|access-date=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106123809/http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/10/14/fiji-embassy-uae-hosts-first-fiji-day-celebrations/|archive-date=6 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/08/06/an-interview-with-dr-robin-nair-fijis-envoy-in-the-middle-east/|title=An Interview with Dr Robin Nair \u2013 Fiji's Envoy in the Middle East - THE JET - Fiji's First Community Newspaper|last=admin|access-date=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323102456/http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/08/06/an-interview-with-dr-robin-nair-fijis-envoy-in-the-middle-east/|archive-date=23 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=224111|title=Fiji Times Online : Page Not Found|website=www.fijitimes.com|access-date=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020220816/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=224111|archive-date=20 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Fijian community in Abu Dhabi convenes celebrations for Fiji Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/10/celebration-in-abu-dhabi/|title=Celebration In Abu Dhabi - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Finns===\nFinns in the United Arab Emirates form a community of 1,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finland.ae/public/default.aspx?nodeid=42992&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI|title=Embassy - Embassy of Finland, Abu Dhabi : Embassy|website=www.finland.ae |language=fi}}</ref>\n\n===French===\nOver 10,000 [[France|French]] people live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mofa.gov.ae/mofa_english/portal/b04da0f7-4a48-4358-9999-68fa599464a2.aspx|title=His Highness Sheikh Mohammed Bin Rashid receives French PM<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617130822/http://mofa.gov.ae/mofa_english/portal/b04da0f7-4a48-4358-9999-68fa599464a2.aspx|archivedate=17 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/french-website-helps-uae-residents-find-la-vie-en-rose-1.96004|title=French website helps UAE residents find la vie en rose|first=Kevin Scott, Staff|last=Reporter|date=2 April 2008|publisher=}}</ref> The French maintain numerous community organisations, schools, restaurants, and academies throughout the country. According to various statistics, the French population of UAE has been growing at a rate of 5% a year.<ref name=\"A\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.justlanded.com/just-landed-news/guide-de-dubai-en-francais-expatries/|title=Dubai Guide in French / Guide de Duba\u00ef fran\u00e7ais|publisher=}}</ref> France also has an industrial presence with close to 300 French enterprises and businesses. Roughly half of these are in Dubai.<ref name=\"A\"/>\n\n===Germans===\nGermans in the United Arab Emirates number 10,000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/community/features/3686-german-expats-in-dubai|title=German expats in Dubai|website=Time Out Dubai}}</ref> found across major cities of the country.\n\nThe UAE has three German schools:\n\n* [[Deutsche Schule Abu Dhabi]]\n* [[Deutsche Schule Sharjah]]\n* [[Deutsche Internationale Schule Dubai]]\n\n===Greeks===\nOver 5,000 Greeks live in the UAE, mostly in [[Dubai]].<ref name=\"List\"/><ref name=\"MFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/en-US/Policy/Geographic+Regions/Mediterranean+-+Middle+East/Bilateral+Relations/United+Arab+Emirates/|title=Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Greece) - United Arab Emirates|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"EG\"/> They are predominantly professionals in white-collar industry, serving in various positions such as executives and businessmen.<ref name=\"MFA\"/> Many of them have been living in the country for more than 20 years, while every year an increasing number of newcomers are setting up in the UAE.<ref name=\"EG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emiratesgreeks.com/news.php?op=details&id=71|title=Emirates Greeks - Embassy of Greece in the UAE honours economic and commercial partners|website=www.emiratesgreeks.com|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710191018/http://www.emiratesgreeks.com/news.php?op=details&id=71|archive-date=10 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition, more than 120 Greek companies of different sectors currently operate in the country.<ref name=\"EG\"/>\n\nThe Greek community is organised through social circles. There are two (informal) Greek schools, whose teachers are posted and managed by the [[Minister of Education (Greece)|Greek Ministry of Education]].\n\nThe [[Greek Orthodox Church]] of the UAE is under the jurisdiction of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Antioch Patriarchate]]; the current bishop is the Metropolitan of Bagdad and Kuwait Constantine. There is a Greek Orthodox Church of St Nikolaos in [[Abu Dhabi]].  Prior to its construction, there existed no Greek church in the UAE and the community had to use other churches for their services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyfrappe.com/Home/tabid/36/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/58/Default.aspx|title=Construction of Greek Orthodox Church to begin in UAE: Daily Frappe|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119153123/http://www.dailyfrappe.com/Home/tabid/36/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/58/Default.aspx|archivedate=19 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Hungarians===\nAccording to a Hungarian aviation official, \"there is a sizeable Hungarian community already working in the UAE\" and many Hungarians travel to Dubai for tourism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.routes-news.com/tourism-and-destinations/4-tourism-destinations/1774-a-route-in-focus-budapest-dubai|title=Routes News - A route in focus: Budapest\u2013Dubai<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221103329/http://www.routes-news.com/tourism-and-destinations/4-tourism-destinations/1774-a-route-in-focus-budapest-dubai|archivedate=21 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=February 2016}}\n\n===Iranians===\n{{Main|Iranians in the United Arab Emirates}}\nIranians in the UAE number 400,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/region/iran/iranian-expats-in-the-uae-see-polls-as-a-pointless-exercise-1.988403 |title=Iranian expats in the UAE see polls as a pointless exercise |accessdate=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303195423/http://gulfnews.com/news/region/iran/iranian-expats-in-the-uae-see-polls-as-a-pointless-exercise-1.988403 |archivedate=3 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> to half a million.\n\n===Irish===\nMore than 8,000 Irish expatriates live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/desert-dreaming-29384974.html|title=Desert Dreaming - Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/irish-youth-flock-to-uae-in-search-of-better-job-opportunities-2013-03-02-1.497046|title=Irish youth flock to UAE in search of better job opportunities|first=Majorie van|last=Leijen|date=2 March 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/economy/irish-minister-jimmy-deenihan-makes-uae-first-stop-on-post-appointment-tour|title=Irish minister Jimmy Deenihan makes UAE first stop on post-appointment tour - The National|publisher=}}</ref> There is an Abu Dhabi Irish Society and a Dubai Irish Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/world/other-world/why-irish-eyes-are-smiling-in-the-uae-1.1304746|title=Why Irish eyes are smiling in the UAE|first=Marianna Wright Special to Gulf|last=News|date=16 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Israelis===\nThe United Arab Emirates does not recognise Israel due to the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict|Palestinian conflict]], and therefore Israeli passport-holders cannot legally enter the UAE. Restrictions were tightened against the entry of Israeli citizens following the [[assassination of Mahmoud Al-Mabhouh]] in Dubai, which was blamed on Israeli intelligence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/israelis-no-longer-allowed-in-dubai-after-hamas-hit-1.263926|title=Israelis No Longer Allowed in Dubai After Hamas Hit|first=News|last=Agencies|date=1 March 2010|publisher=|via=Haaretz|newspaper=Haaretz}}</ref> However, there are [[History of the Jews in the United Arab Emirates|Jewish expatriates in the UAE]], and Israelis with [[dual citizenship]] who live, visit, and work in the UAE as citizens of other countries.<ref name=\"Israelis\"/> Some Israeli companies conduct business in the UAE indirectly through third parties.<ref name=\"Israelis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Israelis-doing-business-in-Dubai-will-wait-out-storm|title=Israelis doing business in Dubai will wait out storm|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Italians===\n{{main|Italians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Latvians===\nAbout 300 Latvians live in the UAE. To serve the community, Latvia opened an embassy in Abu Dhabi in September 2014, its first diplomatic mission in the [[Persian Gulf]] region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/uae-latvian-community-will-benefit-from-embassy-opening|title=UAE Latvian community will benefit from embassy opening - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Mexicans===\nApproximately 3,000 Mexican citizens live and work in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/first-mexican-embassy-in-uae-inaugurated|title=First Mexican Embassy in UAE inaugurated - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Moldovans===\nA relatively large population of Moldovans live in the UAE, especially in Sharjah. Abu Dhabi and Dubai have a joint population of around 22,000 Moldovans.\n\n===Macedonians===\nMacedonians are the sixth-largest Yugoslav and ex-Yugoslav (Balkanic) population in the UAE and in the whole Arab World.\n\n===Montenegrins===\nThe Montenegrins are the seventh-largest Yugoslav and ex-Yugoslav (Balcanic) population in the UAE and in the whole Arab World.\n\n===New Zealanders===\nNew Zealanders in the UAE number around 4,000,<ref>[http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091106/NATIONAL/711059864/1023/rss From F1 to FIFA, the show rolls on] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222010201/http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20091106%2FNATIONAL%2F711059864%2F1023%2Frss |date=22 February 2014 }}</ref> the overwhelming majority of whom are based in Dubai. A number of entrepreneurs from New Zealand are attracted towards the work and business opportunities offered in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unlimited.co.nz/unlimited.nsf/default/eye-of-the-storm|title=Eye of the storm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717134415/http://unlimited.co.nz/unlimited.nsf/default/eye-of-the-storm|archivedate=17 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2007, more than 700 New Zealanders moved to the UAE permanently or for long term.<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10512314\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10512314 |title=Desert jewel a rough diamond |author=Smith, Jacqueline |date=25 May 2008 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=11 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe New Zealand community is involved in numerous cultural events, get-togethers and organisations. In Dubai, expatriate New Zealanders joined Australians to form the Australia New Zealand Association, which aims to provide support to society members and expatriates over the entire country.\n\n===Nicaraguans===\nThe Nicaraguan community in the UAE is rather small. As of 2017 less than 5 expatriates live in the UAE, the majority of them in Dubai Marina.\n\n===Norwegians===\n1,500-2,000 Norwegians live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/norwegians-mark-195th-independence-anniversary-1.69088|title=Norwegians mark 195th independence anniversary|first=Kevin Scott, Staff|last=Reporter|date=18 May 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Peruvians===\nAround 300 [[Peru]]vians live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Poles===\n2,000 Poles live in UAE, the largest Polish population in the Arab World.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/polish-expats-praise-freedom-given-by-uae-1.143306|title=Polish expats praise freedom given by UAE|first=Binsal Abdul Kader, Staff|last=Reporter|date=13 November 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Romanians===\n6,000 Romanians live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.incont.ro/joburi-strainatate/atrasi-de-mirajul-emiratelor-5-000-de-romani-muncesc-in-dubai-pentru-cateva-mii-de-euro-pe-luna.html|title=Atrasi de mirajul Emiratelor. 5.000 de romani muncesc in Dubai pentru cateva mii de euro pe luna|last=incont|publisher=}}</ref> The majority of them are professionals, holding graduate or postgraduate qualifications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/romanians-look-to-boost-ties-with-uae-1.149003|title=Romanians look to boost ties with UAE|first=Binsal Abdul Kader, Staff|last=Reporter|date=13 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Russians===\nA sizable [[Russians]] community lives in the UAE\u2014typically having moved to the country for job opportunities and the year-round sunny weather.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\nAccording to Consul General of The Russian Federation, as many as 10,000 Russian expatriates and overall above 55,000 Russian speakers from CIS (former Soviet Republics) countries live throughout the country, with the majority having made Dubai and Northern Emirates their home.<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/business/russians-feel-at-home-in-uae/|title=Russians feel at home in UAE|work=[[Russia Today]]|date=9 September 2007}}</ref>\nThe UAE is also a popular visiting destination, with above 2,000,000 tourists from Russia & CIS visiting the country each year.<ref name=\"RT\"/>\nA number of business and cultural groups operate within the community, such as [http://www.rbcdubai.org/ Russian Business Council in Dubai and Northern Emirates], which is under the umbrella of the [[Dubai Chamber of Commerce and Industry]]; Russian Cultural Club in the American University of Sharjah; Russian Women Union ''Rossiyanka'', to name a few.\nThe Dubai Russian Private School is a secondary school that uses a curriculum approved by the Russian Ministry of Education and caters to the Russian speaking community needs. After-school activities and extra curricular classes are also available, e.g., dance lessons for adults and children at [https://dubaidance.com/our-history/ \"Dance For You\" studio].\nA number of Russian-language publications operate in the country: [[:ru:\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u042d\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u044b (\u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b)|Russian Emirates magazine]] (dedicated to the luxury lifestyle and fashion), Business Emirates magazine (dedicate to the property, business and investments; the official publication of the Russian Business Council), as well as East Sprigs UAE Travel Guide book for Russian speaking tourists and visitors of the UAE, printed & published by the Russian Emirates Publishing House and actively promoted and circulated. There is a \"Russian Radio \u2013 [http://www.autoradio.ae/ Auto Radio U.A.E]\" broadcasting on 103.2 FM all over the UAE. Dubai has often been described as a playground for Russian VIPs, where large portions of property are bought. Some locals insist that as much as half of the Palm Jumeirah, the first of the city's scheduled three man-made islands, which is already handed over, will eventually be owned by Russian speakers.<ref name=\"RT\"/>\n\n===Samoans===\nA very small number of Samoans are present in the UAE. Most Samoans actively play rugby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/knowledge/news/10986-footie-fundraiser|title=Footie fundraiser|website=Time Out Dubai}}</ref> New Zealand-born Samoan rugby player [[Apollo Perelini]] has been based in the UAE for a couple of years, where he coaches at the Elite Sporting Academy in [[Repton School Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/rugbys-tribute-to-tsunami-victims|title=Rugby's tribute to tsunami victims - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Serbs===\n5,000 Serbs live in UAE.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\"/>\n\n===Slovaks===\nAround 1,000 [[Slovaks]] reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Slovenians===\nBetween 100 and 150 [[Slovenia]]ns live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Spaniards===\nAbout 12,000 Spanish expatriates live in the UAE. A Spanish Business Council has been formed by the expatriate community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/spanish-fans-in-the-uae-expect-team-to-reach-world-cup-quarterfinals-at-least|title=Spanish fans in the UAE expect team to reach World Cup quarterfinals, at least - The National|publisher=}}</ref> The majority of them live in Dubai, followed by Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/biz/inside.asp?xfile=/data/uaebusiness/2013/December/uaebusiness_December270.xml&section=uaebusiness|title=UAE and Spain focus on direct investment, renewable energy|first=Suchitra Steven Samuel|last=(Interview)|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Swedes===\nSwedes in the United Arab Emirates number at over 3,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/gn-focus/sweden/a-meeting-of-minds-1.815780|title=A meeting of minds -GulfNews.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829044340/http://gulfnews.com/gn-focus/sweden/a-meeting-of-minds-1.815780|archivedate=29 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Swiss===\nAround 2,430 [[Switzerland|Swiss]] nationals reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Turks===\nTurks in the United Arab Emirates are Turkish citizens who live in the United Arab Emirates. In 2014, the population was around 10,000 and increasing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/turks-living-in-the-uae-vote-in-presidential-elections|title=Turks living in the UAE vote in presidential elections - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/turkish-community-group-marks-fourth-anniversary-1.636866|title=Turkish community group marks fourth anniversary|first=Ashfaq Ahmed, Chief|last=Reporter|date=5 June 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bilgidubai.info/turkish-community-dubai-english|title=English-Turkish Community Dubai - Dubai|website=www.bilgidubai.info}}</ref> In recent years many Turkish doctors have moved to Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://turkishdoctors.rf.gd|title=Turkish Healthcare Professionals in UAE}}</ref>\n\n===Ukrainians===\nIn 2006 the Ukrainian population was listed at 2,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/heritage-culture/warming-up-1.24650|title=Warming up|first=Shalaka Paradkar, Staff|last=Writer|date=22 June 2006|publisher=}}</ref> More recently, the population grew to 5,000.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Venezuelans===\n2,580 people living in the UAE have Venezuelan roots. Many Venezuelans work in the oil businesses, due to UAE\u2013Venezuela relations ([[OPEC]]).\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Immigration to the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{United Arab Emirates topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Immigration to}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Expatriates In The United Arab Emirates}}\n[[Category:Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\nMost '''[[expatriate]]s in the [[United Arab Emirates]]''' reside in [[Dubai]] and [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name=\"List\">{{cite web |last=Snoj |first=Jure |url=http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality |title=UAE's population - by nationality |publisher=Bqdoha.com |accessdate=1 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711160839/http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality |archivedate=11 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A number of expatriates settled in the country prior to [[History of the United Arab Emirates#Independence|independence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/heritage/former-expat-donates-snapshot-of-uae-history-to-the-emirates |title=Former expat donates snapshot of UAE history to the Emirates|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|publisher=Thenational.ae |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/personal-finance/uae-expats-priced-out-of-their-lives |title=UAE expats priced out of their lives|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The UAE is home to over 200 nationalities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/society/what-makes-uae-a-role-model-of-cohesion-1.1836341|title=What makes UAE a role model of cohesion|work=Gulf News|date=28 May 2016|accessdate=22 April 2017|first=Suchitra Bajpai|last=Chaudhry}}</ref> [[Emiratis]] constitute roughly 20% of the total population, making UAE home to one of the world's highest percentage of immigrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bq-magazine.com/economy/socioeconomics/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality|title=UAE\u00b4s population \u2013 by nationality|first=Jure|last=Snoj|work=BQ Magazine|date=12 April 2015|accessdate=22 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321184658/http://www.bq-magazine.com/economy/socioeconomics/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality|archivedate=21 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Indians in the United Arab Emirates|Indians]] and [[Pakistanis in the United Arab Emirates|Pakistanis]] form the largest expatriate groups in the country, constituting 28% <ref name=\"Pew research\">{{cite news|title=India is a top source and destination for world\u2019s migrants|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2017/03/03/india-is-a-top-source-and-destination-for-worlds-migrants/|accessdate=7 March 2017|work=Pew Research Center|date=3 March 2017}}</ref> and 12% of the total population respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/society/indians-pakistanis-make-up-37-of-dubai-sharjah-ajman-population-1.1562336|title=Indians, Pakistanis make up 37% of Dubai, Sharjah, Ajman population|first=Jumana Khamis, Staff|last=Reporter|date=6 August 2015|publisher=}}</ref> 461,000 [[Westerners]] live in the [[United Arab Emirates]], making up 5,1% of its total population.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20150711160839/http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality</ref><ref>https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/comment/the-other-special-relationship-the-uae-and-the-uk-1.549898</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe United Arab Emirates is the home of immigrants from all over the world; this may be because UAE nationals  prefer to work for the government or military.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/heritage/top-chef-wants-more-emiratis-to-try-a-career-in-the-kitchen |title=Top chef wants more Emiratis to try a career in the kitchen|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=17 November 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/emiratisation-wont-work-if-people-dont-want-to-learn |title=Emiratisation won't work if people don't want to learn|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=18 March 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>  The country's relatively liberal society compared to some of its neighbours has attracted many global expatriates, including people from [[Western world|western nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.yahoo.com/top-5-most-liberal-muslim-countries-1570105.html|title=Yahoo|website=Yahoo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729040734/http://voices.yahoo.com/top-5-most-liberal-muslim-countries-1570105.html|archivedate=29 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Emiratis are outnumbered in their own country by a ratio of nine to one. Under Article 8 of UAE Federal Law no. 17, an expatriate can apply for UAE citizenship after residing in the country for a period not less than 30 years, of which 20 years at least after the said law comes into force, providing that person has never been convicted of a crime and can speak fluent [[Arabic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ilovetheuae.com/2010/07/13/federal-law-no-17-concerning-nationality-and-passports|title=ilovetheuae.com|website=ilovetheuae.com|access-date=14 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226044910/http://ilovetheuae.com/2010/07/13/federal-law-no-17-concerning-nationality-and-passports|archive-date=26 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Arab League populations==\n\n===Algerians===\nAn estimated 10,000 [[Algeria]]ns live in the UAE\u2014one of the smallest Arab communities in the UAE.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n===Bahrainis===\nA small but unknown number of [[Bahrani people]] are present in the UAE.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/source/XXX/359/images/page1.pdf|title=Bahrainis in UAE safe|date=13 March 2008|accessdate=4 April 2015|work=Gulf Daily News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924043506/http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/source/XXX/359/images/page1.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bahrain is also a member of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC); this membership enables Bahraini nationals to enter the UAE without restrictions.\n\n===Comorians===\nMany members of the UAE's 10,000-strong stateless [[Bedoon (ethnicity)|Bedoon]] community have obtained [[Comoro Islands]] passports, providing them a legal status and a pathway towards naturalised UAE citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/heritage/bidoon-celebrate-uae-national-day-as-emiratis |title=UAE bidoon celebrate National Day as Emiratis |work=The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=24 November 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126150126/http://www.thenational.ae/uae/heritage/bidoon-celebrate-uae-national-day-as-emiratis |archivedate=26 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/citizenship-hope-for-uaes-stateless |title=Citizenship hope for UAE's stateless|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> This move came following the Comorian legislature's decision to sell Comorian nationalities to stateless Bedoons in the Gulf countries, including UAE, in return for these Gulf countries' economic investment in Comoros.<ref>{{cite web|last=Araxia |first=Atossa |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/11/10/kuwait-statelesscitizenshipcomoros.html |title=Kuwait offers stateless group citizenship \u2014 from Comoros|work= Al Jazeera America |publisher=America.aljazeera.com |date=10 November 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The number of such Bedoons with Comorian passports in the UAE is estimated to be at least a thousand.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hall |first=Camilla |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8abfc14a-a8aa-11e1-be59-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3WKh9eVbB |title=UAE's stateless acquire foreign passports |publisher=FT.com |date=4 June 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Egyptians===\nThere is a high number of [[Egyptians]] living in the [[UAE]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/community-reports/upbeat-egyptian-expatriates-vote-in-first-free-presidential-elections-1.1021717|title=Upbeat Egyptian expatriates vote in first free presidential elections|first=Samir Salama, Associate|last=Editor|date=12 May 2012|access-date=21 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516234516/http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/community-reports/upbeat-egyptian-expatriates-vote-in-first-free-presidential-elections-1.1021717|archive-date=16 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> forming the largest community of non-citizens from the Arab world in the UAE.\n\n===Iraqis===\n{{Main|Iraqis in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nIraqis in the UAE have a population exceeding 100,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzflash.com/mediawatch/05/01/wmw05009.html|title=Buzzflash Headlines|website=www.buzzflash.com|access-date=12 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606160625/http://www.buzzflash.com/mediawatch/05/01/wmw05009.html|archive-date=6 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most Iraqis are recent immigrants who fled instability at home; while Syria, Jordan, Iran and Lebanon were ultimate destinations for most refugees, a large number settled in the United Arab Emirates. In addition, an increasing number of Iraqi students seeking education and career opportunities opted for the country in light of its relatively reputable institutions across the [[Middle East]].\n\n===Jordanians===\n{{main|Jordanians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAs of 2009, the Jordanian population was estimated at 250,000,<ref>{{cite web|last=Husseini |first=Rana |url=http://www.jordantimes.com/?news=14910 |title=Jordan Times |publisher=Jordan Times |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> an increase from 80,000 in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.asp?StoryId=26140|title=Business & Financial - International News, Currencies & Economic Indicators|last=MENAFN|access-date=22 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306002844/http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.asp?StoryId=26140|archive-date=6 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> making them one of the largest Jordanian diaspora communities both worldwide and in the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|Persian Gulf]] region. Jordanian labour is in high value and demand throughout the country. A large number of Jordanians are highly qualified and occupy jobs that require skill and training. Most work in white-collar jobs as professors, managers, bankers, doctors, and engineers. The UAE remains a popular tourist destination for many Jordanians. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n===Kuwaitis===\nA small community of [[Kuwait]]is lives in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/multimedia/framed/spotlight/proud-to-be-kuwaiti-1.1153002 |title=Proud to be Kuwaiti |publisher=GulfNews.com |date=2 March 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531034641/http://gulfnews.com/multimedia/framed/spotlight/proud-to-be-kuwaiti-1.1153002 |archive-date=31 May 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It includes around 1,000 Kuwaiti students studying at eight universities across the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/kuwait-in-shock-over-death-of-sharjah-student-beaten-by-friends |title=Kuwait in shock over death of Sharjah student beaten by 'friends' |work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=27 February 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-251959007.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152913/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-251959007.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2015|title=Kuwaiti students in UAE to observe annual gathering.|date=19 March 2011|newspaper=Kuwait News Agency (Kuna)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2224776&Language=en |title=Kuwaiti students in UAE hold annual event - Education - 03/03/2012 |publisher=KUNA |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>  Kuwait is also a member of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC); this membership enables Kuwaiti nationals to live and work in the UAE without restrictions.\n\n===Lebanese===\n{{Main|Lebanese people in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAn estimated 80,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/01/lebanese-uae-fears-deportation.html|title=Lebanese Living in UAE Fear Deportation|date=21 January 2013|access-date=6 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016142536/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/01/lebanese-uae-fears-deportation.html|archive-date=16 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lebanese live in the UAE, mostly in Dubai, Abu Dhabi, and Sharjah. The UAE remains a popular touring destination for many Lebanese. The majority of [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] expatriates who work in the UAE are [[educated]], with some being fluent in both French and English languages. Many Lebanese are involved in business and the [[News media|media]] as plastic surgeons, businessmen, artists, presenters, hairdressers, and news anchors.\n\nOver 15,000 Lebanese companies operate in the [[Jebel Ali Free Zone]] alone, an economic hub located in [[Jebel Ali]], a city in Dubai. Notable Lebanese nationals who have lived in UAE include the late [[Antoine Choueiri]], the owner of the Middle East's largest media broker (Choueiri Group), which controls Arabian Media Services International, MEMS, Arabian Outdoor, Times International, Audio Visual Media, C Media, Press Media, Digital Media Services, Interadio, Promofair, AMC and SECOMM; and [[Elias Bou Saab]], the founder of the [[American University in Dubai]] (AUD).\n\n===Libyans===\nAn estimated 2,000 Libyans live in the UAE, forming one of the smaller non-citizen Arab communities. Many Libyans who have lived in exile in UAE for decades returned to Libya after the fall of the former Libyan regime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/libyans-in-uae-are-already-booking-their-tickets-home|title=Libyans in UAE are already booking their tickets home - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Mauritanians===\nAround 5,000 Mauritanians are residing and working in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/31/3106505_mauritania-africa-uea-terminates-contracts-of-mauritanians.html |title=The Global Intelligence Files - MAURITANIA/AFRICA-UEA terminates contracts of Mauritanians employed in police corps |publisher=Wikileaks.org |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=McDougall|first1=James|last2=Scheele|first2=Judith|title=Saharan Frontiers: Space and Mobility in Northwest Africa|date=2012|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253001245|page=178|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=OWONbhuKBlQC&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Moroccans===\nAn estimated 100,000 Moroccans live in the UAE. They form one of the biggest communities from North Africa of citizens from the Arab world in the UAE. Morocco and the UAE are known to be close allies.\n\n===Omanis===\nOmanis consist of expatriates and residents in the United Arab Emirates who hail from Oman. Being a bordering country and sharing cultural links, thousands of Omanis live in the U.A.E. They are predominantly Arabs and belong to the Muslim [[Ibadi]] sect.\n\nOmanis make a large percentage of the UAE's officer corps and also dominate the police forces.<ref>[http://www.jepeterson.net/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/Future_of_Federalism_in_UAE.pdf J.E. Peterson. The Future of Federalism in the United Arab Emirates], pp. 18</ref>\nMany are originally students pursuing higher education in various institutions across the country. In 2003, their number was estimated at over 9,000.<ref name=\"V\"/> According to the ''Times of Oman'', the United Arab Emirates is the most popular destination for Omani students who choose to study abroad; its close location and sharing of the language and culture makes them more comfortable at places like Dubai, Abu Dhabi, [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]] and the border town of [[Al Ain]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofoman.com/innercat.asp?detail=39494|title=More Omanis opting to study overseas|first=Aftab H.|last=Kola|work=Times of Oman|date=4 October 2010|accessdate=29 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617012859/http://www.timesofoman.com/innercat.asp?detail=39494|archivedate=17 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBoth countries have signed a memorandum of understanding aimed at providing benefits to Omani nationals and citizens in the UAE as well as treating Omani labour and work force at par with the country's nationals.<ref name=\"MOU\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oeronline.com/php/2006_july/inthe_news.php|title=Omani workers to get same status as UAE nationals|date=July 2006|work=Oman Economic Review|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522183909/http://www.oeronline.com/php/2006_july/inthe_news.php|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Being a member of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)]] (like the UAE) enables Omani nationals to move and work freely within the country and enjoy contrasting residential benefits as compared to expatriates in the UAE from non-GCC states.\n\nIn 2003, Omanis in the UAE were allowed to vote for council members in the elections of the [[Consultative Assembly of Oman|Omani Majlis al-Shura]]. It was the first-ever overseas [[suffrage]] in Oman's history.<ref name=\"V\">{{cite news |last=Bibbo |first=Barbara |date=28 September 2003 |title=Omanis in UAE allowed to vote in Shura council polls |url=http://www.mafhoum.com/press6/162S25.htm |newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Palestinians===\nAn estimated 100,000<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/report-uae-to-deport-hundreds-of-palestinians-by-month-s-end-1.8448|title=Report: UAE to Deport Hundreds of Palestinians by Month's End|first=Haaretz|last=Service|date=4 September 2009|publisher=|via=Haaretz|newspaper=Haaretz}}</ref> Palestinians live in the UAE and form one of the largest community of non-citizens from the Arab world in the UAE.\n\n===Qataris===\nSome [[Qatar]]i citizens are based in the UAE. Qatar was a member of the GCC and thus citizens of both countries were free to live and work in each other's countries without restrictions. The [[2017\u201318 Qatar diplomatic crisis]] began when several countries abruptly cut off diplomatic relations with Qatar in June 2017. These countries included Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt. The severing of relations included withdrawing ambassadors and imposing trade and travel bans.<ref>{{cite news |last=Al Ramahi |first=Nawal |title=Qataris in the UAE express cautious optimism over resolving dispute |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/qatar/qataris-in-the-uae-express-cautious-optimism-over-resolving-dispute-1.1305191 |newspaper=Gulf News |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ahmed Shaaban |url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/kt-article-display-1.asp?xfile=data/community/2013/June/community_June43.xml&section=community |title=Qataris in UAE hail Hamad's move to hand power to son |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author='+readFromCookie(\"jsonUserName\")+' |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/crime/qatari-cell-members-arrested-in-uae-1.1357928 |title=Qatari cell members arrested in UAE |publisher=GulfNews.com |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Also, Qatari citizens who have family members from the UAE will not be affected.<ref>https://www.thenational.ae/world/saudi-arabia-and-the-uae-exempt-qatari-spouses-caught-in-gcc-crisis-1.42885</ref>\n\n===Saudis===\nA total of 4,895 Saudis were living in the UAE in 2007;<ref>[http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=6&section=0&article=111912&d=17&m=7&y=2008&pix=business.jpg&category=Business Nearly 5,000 Saudis are living in UAE - Arab News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616060042/http://archive.arabnews.com/?page=6&section=0&article=111912&d=17&m=7&y=2008&pix=business.jpg&category=Business |date=16 June 2012 }}</ref> this number grew when a further 700 entered at the start of 2008.\n\nThey are mostly found working in the sectors of commerce and industry as well as medicine, law, insurance and shipping. Both the UAE and Saudi Arabia are Arab states and part of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]; according to agreements, the citizens of each GCC member can live and work in any of the six countries without a visa and other restrictions. The Saudis own a total of 1,357 houses and 1,450 pieces of land in various [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]] in the UAE.\n\n===Somalis=== \nMore 50,000 Somalis live in the United Arab Emirates.Many of these are people who settled in the UAE before its creation.There is up to 35,000 of people who are Citizens of Western Nations. They came as in the hopes to invest in the UAE.Since many Somali passport holders face many restrictions in the UAE, which makes it easier for Western Passport holders of Somali origin . There's a lot of Gold Stores, where people who left Western nations choose to invest in the UAE, while is closer to Somalia. The Somali Business Council based in Dubai regulates 175 Somali companies.<ref name=\"Cdsdhfc\">{{cite news|title=Dubai's Somali diaspora hope for change|url=http://english.cntv.cn/program/newsupdate/20120911/105653.shtml|accessdate=4 February 2015|agency=CCTV|date=11 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701165012/http://english.cntv.cn/program/newsupdate/20120911/105653.shtml|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Somali-owned businesses line the streets of [[Deira, Dubai|Deira]], the Dubai city centre,<ref name=\"Sciodb\">{{cite news|title=Somalis cash in on Dubai boom|url=http://newsvote.bbc.co.uk/mpapps/pagetools/print/news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4535642.stm|accessdate=29 January 2015|agency=BBC}}</ref> with only [[Iran]]ians exporting more products from the city at large.<ref>{{cite news|title=Forget piracy, Somalia's whole 'global' economy is booming - to Kenya's benefit|url=http://www.theeastafrican.co.ke/news/-/2558/914994/-/view/printVersion/-/yvxnho/-/index.html|accessdate=29 January 2015|agency=TEA}}</ref> [[Internet caf\u00e9]]s, [[hotel]]s, [[Coffeehouse|coffee shop]]s, [[restaurant]]s and [[International trade|import-export businesses]] are all testimony to the Somalis' entrepreneurial spirit. Star African Air is also one of three Somali-owned [[airline]]s based in Dubai.<ref name=\"Sciodb\"/>\n\n===Sudanese===\n79,000 Sudanese live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/> Most of them are based mainly in Dubai, with smaller populations in other emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle09.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2010/April/theuae_April278.xml&section=theuae|title=Sudanese expats cast votes in UAE|first=Amira|last=Agarib|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Syrians===\n{{Main|Syrians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nA large number of Syrians live in the UAE. Many of whom have been in the country since its prosperity, even before 1971. Syrians, similarly to the Lebanese, are educated and highly respected. Many Syrians have opened restaurants, opened businesses, and many of them work in both the public and private sectors. Most Syrians reside in Abu Dhabi, Dubai, and Sharjah.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/syrians-in-dubai-look-to-rebuild-homeland |title=Syrians in Dubai look to rebuild homeland|work= The National |publisher=Thenational.ae |date=5 June 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Their population is over 242,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/government/uae-home-to-242000-syrians|title=UAE home to 242,000 Syrians|last=AP|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Tunisians===\nA small but unknown number of Tunisians live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates/1395278208262.html |title=Nahyan bin Mubarak attends Tunisian Embassy's reception |work=WAM |publisher=Wam.ae |date=20 March 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610135815/https://www.wam.ae/en/news/emirates/1395278208262.html |archivedate=10 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abudhabinews.net/index.php/sid/231255149|title=Nahyan bin Mubarak attends Tunisian Embassys reception|access-date=6 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306135223/http://www.abudhabinews.net/index.php/sid/231255149|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tn.webradar.me/portal/2599846|title=WebRadar - Log in|website=tn.webradar.me}}</ref> There is a Tunisian Business Council based in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbcauh.ae/en/info/Members_Benefits|title=Members Benefits|website=tbcauh.ae}}</ref> There is also a web radio operated by the Tunisian community, known as 3ASLEMA Dubai.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.3aslemadubai.com/ |title= 3ASLEMA Dubai |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525213813/http://www.3aslemadubai.com/ |archivedate=25 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Yemenis===\nOver 98,000 Yemeni expatriates lives in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/news/463272|title=Etihad Airways introduces maiden flight to Sanaa|date=2 September 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==African populations==\n===Angolans===\nAround 900 [[Angola]]ns reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Chadians===\n200 [[Chad]]ian nationals reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Eritreans===\nThere were 3,000 to 4,000 Eritreans in the UAE as of 2010. 60% of them were women working as baby-sitters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/darticlen.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2010/June/theuae_June112.xml&section=theuae|title=Eritreans in UAE celebrate independence day|first=Afkar|last=Abdullah|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Ethiopians===\nAn estimated 100,000 Ethiopian nationals live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.albawaba.com/business/uae-and-ethiopia-love-story-foreign-direct-investment-503605|title=The UAE and Ethiopia: a love story of foreign direct investment|date=2 July 2013|publisher=}}</ref> A large number of them are domestic workers, housemaids or involved in labour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/ethiopia-wants-dh1-200-minimum-wage-for-its-citizens-in-the-uae|title=Ethiopia wants Dh1,200 minimum wage for its citizens in the UAE - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/employers-of-ethiopian-maids-in-uae-urged-to-inform-embassy|title=Employers of Ethiopian maids in UAE urged to inform embassy - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Ghanaians===\nA community of over 300 [[Ghana]]ian expatriates live in the country. They have two main associations, the Ghana Community in Dubai and the Ghana Social Club in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=232388|title=Ghanaians in UAE Celebrate Ghana at 55|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref> Ghana has a consulate-general in Dubai serving the community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/artikel.php?ID=236432|title=Vice President  Interacts With Ghanaians In Dubai|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/artikel.php?ID=204383|title=Independence Day Celebration:  Ghanaians in Dubai|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/diaspora.news.php?country=AE|title=News About Ghanaian Community in United Arab Emirates|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/diaspora/artikel.php?ID=313817|title=Ghanaians in Abu Dhabi Elect New Leaders|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref>\n\n===Kenyans===\nKenyans in the United Arab Emirates had an estimated population numbering 50,000 in 2019. Of these, many work in Dubai in the hospitality and construction industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hseassignmentabroad.in/blog|title=Abroad Experience in Kuwait|author=Hybridrain|date=December 2019 |website=hseassignmentabroad.in}}</ref>\n\n===Nigerians===\nAround 2,000 to 5,000 Nigerians live in UAE. Notable Nigerians living in the [[UAE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaeinteract.com/docs/Nigerian_President_receives_outgoing_UAE_envoy/62002.htm|title=UAE Interact, United Arab Emirates information, news, photographs, maps and webcams|last=UAEINTERACT|website=www.uaeinteract.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201310180816.html|title=Nigeria: Why People Visit Dubai|first=Shehu|last=Abubakar|date=18 October 2013|publisher=|via=AllAfrica}}</ref>\n\n===Senegalese===\nThe population of [[Senegal]]ese people in the UAE is around 700 to 800.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===South Africans===\n{{main|South Africans in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===South Sudanese===\nA South Sudanese community is present in the UAE. They are mainly Christians. They were treated as part of the Sudanese community; however, after [[South Sudan]] achieved independence from [[Sudan]] in 2011, South Sudanese expatriates living in the UAE were required to apply for new [[South Sudanese passport]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/south-sudanese-in-uae-fear-diplomatic-limbo|title=South Sudanese in UAE fear diplomatic limbo - The National|publisher=}}</ref> The UAE airline [[flydubai]] operates several flights a week from Dubai to [[Juba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flydubai.com/en/news/article/flydubai-makes-maiden-flight-to-juba/|title=flydubai makes maiden flight to Juba<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Ugandans===\nA small number of Ugandans live in Dubai. There is a Ugandans in Dubai Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/dh20-000-to-send-a-body-home-from-uae-for-burial|title=Dh20,000 to send a body home from UAE for burial - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/676843|title=Ugandan robs bank in Dubai<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141022160604/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/676843|archivedate=22 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Zimbabweans===\nA number of Zimbabweans live in Dubai, although their population is unknown. They are mainly employed in the tourism and hospitality sectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b-metro.co.zw/dubai-mystery-revealed/|title=Dubai mystery revealed|work=B-Metro|first=Nhlalwenhle |last=Ncube|date=2 March 2015|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Central Asian populations==\n===Kazakhs===\nMost Kazakhs are business people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/kazakh-community-celebrates-independence-day-1.149859|title=Kazakh community celebrates Independence Day|first=Binsal Abdul Kader, Staff|last=Reporter|date=20 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref> The Kazakhstan Society in UAE is an association of Kazakh expatriates based in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vk.com/club5112953|title=\u2654=====KAZAKHSTAN=====\u2654 \u2654=======SOCIETY======\u2654 \u2654=========in========\u2654 \u2654========UAE========\u2654|website=vk.com}}</ref> As of 2015, the population was 5,000 to 6,000.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Kyrgyz===\nUp to 4,000 Kyrgyz expatriates were residing and working in the UAE as of 2012. There is a Kyrgyz Club in Dubai and the community celebrates events such as the Independence Day of Kyrgyzstan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/dubai-s-kyrgyz-community-come-together-for-independence-day-1.1069496|title=Dubai's Kyrgyz community come together for Independence Day|first=Jumana Khamis, Staff|last=Reporter|date=3 September 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyrgyzclub.org/en/Global/64|title=About us|publisher=Kyrgyz Club}}</ref>\n\n===Tajiks===\nEthnic Tajiks living in the UAE hail from [[Tajikistan]] and Afghanistan. They celebrate cultural events including [[Nowruz]].<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/dubai-expats-celebrate-persian-new-year-nowruz-1.1306593|title=Dubai expats celebrate Persian New Year Nowruz|first=Faisal|last=Masudi|date=20 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Uzbeks===\nA small number of Uzbeks live and work in the UAE. They celebrate cultural events such as [[Nowruz]].<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/a-bit-like-attending-college-departing-expat-looks-back-on-his-uae-experience|title=A bit like attending college: departing expat looks back on his UAE experience - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uznews.net/en/society/23666-shoot-me-why-is-dubai-so-desirable|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141020133402/http://www.uznews.net/en/society/23666-shoot-me-why-is-dubai-so-desirable|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-10-20|title=\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440-1 / Centre1.com - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|website=\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440-1 / Centre1.com - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438}}</ref> Their number has grown to about 14,000 in 2016 from 4000 in 2014.\n\n==East Asian populations==\n===Chinese===\n{{see also|Chinese people in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Japanese===\nAlmost 4,000 Japanese live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/region/middle_e/uae/index.html|title=Japan-United Arab Emirates Relations|website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan}}</ref> Over 2,000 of them reside in Dubai, making the city home to the largest Japanese community in the whole of the Arab world.<ref name=\"AME\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ameinfo.com/112883.html|title=JAFZA home to Hitachi Construction Machinery's new regional centre|date=7 March 2007|work=[[AMEinfo.com]]|accessdate=21 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828111024/http://www.ameinfo.com/112883.html|archivedate=28 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Japan]] also maintains a sizeable trade presence in the UAE through representative offices of multinational corporations and organisations; as of 2007, there were an estimated 105 Japanese companies operating in the [[Jebel Ali Free Zone]] alone.<ref name=\"AME\"/>\n\nAccording to registrations based with local embassies and consulates, the community has been growing at an average of 20 percent per year, much larger than the population during the 1980s when only a few hundred Japanese expatriates lived in the country.<ref name=\"Judo\">{{cite news |last=Constantine |first=Zoi |date=11 October 2007 |title='I planted a judo seed in the desert' |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/i-planted-a-judo-seed-in-the-desert-1.206249 |newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=21 November 2010}}</ref> The Japanese have introduced [[judo]] in the country. Most immigrants are principally skilled workers employed in white-collar business and industry sectors. Dubai has one Japanese association and there is also a [[Dubai Japanese School]], which is based on Japanese curriculum. The [[Japanese School in Abu Dhabi]] also serves Japanese expatriates.\n\n===Koreans===\nApproximately 3,100 Koreans live in the United Arab Emirates.<ref name=\"MOFAT\">{{Citation|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade |location=South Korea |year=2009 |accessdate=21 May 2009 |url=http://www.mofat.go.kr/consul/overseascitizen/compatriotcondition/index6.jsp?TabMenu=TabMenu6 |title={{asiantitle|\uc7ac\uc678\ub3d9\ud3ec\ud604\ud669||Current Status of Overseas Compatriots|a}} |ref=none |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023213104/http://www.mofat.go.kr/consul/overseascitizen/compatriotcondition/index6.jsp?TabMenu=TabMenu6 |archivedate=23 October 2010 }}</ref> The United Arab Emirates received a small contingent of Korean migrant workers in the late 1970s and early 1980s, but it was never a major destination.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Seok|first=Hyunho|chapter=Korean migrant workers to the Middle East|title=Migration to the Arab World: Experience of Returning Migrants|editor-last=Gunatilleke|editor-first=Godfrey|pages=56\u201358|publisher=United Nations University Press|year=1991|isbn=978-92-808-0745-5}}</ref> However, due to rapid growth since 2005, the country has come to have the Arab world's largest Korean population.<ref name=\"MOFAT\"/> {{as of|2008}}, roughly 2,500 South Koreans live in [[Dubai]] alone, largely businessmen working at the 90 Korean companies in the country.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?section=theuae&xfile=data/theuae/2008/february/theuae_february897.xml|date=26 February 2008|accessdate=22 May 2009|title=South Korea to open consulate in Dubai|periodical=Khaleej Times}}</ref> There were also many flight attendants working for [[Emirates Airlines]]; the number of Koreans working for Emirates Airlines increased from 15 in 1998 to 620 as of 2007, mostly based out of Dubai. Dubai has the UAE's largest community of South Koreans.<ref>{{citation|title=Korean Female Crew Capture Middle East|periodical=Chosun Ilbo|date=4 May 2007|accessdate=4 May 2007|url=http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200705/200705040012.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070510014534/http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200705/200705040012.html|archivedate=10 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, a consulate was not opened in Dubai until March 2008.<ref>{{citation|url=http://are-dubai.mofat.go.kr/eng/af/are-dubai/mission/about/index.jsp|title=About us|publisher=The Consulate General of the Republic of Korea in Dubai|accessdate=22 May 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405235607/http://are-dubai.mofat.go.kr/eng/af/are-dubai/mission/about/index.jsp|archivedate=5 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRoughly 1,300 North Korean workers live in the UAE, primarily in Dubai and [[Abu Dhabi]]. They earn between US$300 and $500 per month, but must make so-called \"loyalty payments\" of $150 to $250 to the North Korean government. This has sparked discontent among those workers\u2014and in response, the North Korean government has sent security agents to patrol North Korean work camps and look for people making critical comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/12/25/2009122500238.html|title=N.Korean Workers Brave Hard Times in UAE|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Won Ho Chung]] is a famous Arabic language comedian of Korean origin who is based in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wonhochung.com/|title=Wonho Chung|website=Wonho Chung}}</ref> In 2010, Chung was appointed goodwill ambassador for the Korea Tourism Organization in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/content/cms_view_994589.jsp|title=The First Ethnic Korean Comedian of the Middle East|website=english.visitkorea.or.kr}}</ref>\n\n===Mongolians===\nAbout 6,100 of [[Mongols|Mongolians]] working in [[Dubai]] and [[Abu Dhabi]].\n\n===Taiwanese===\nAround 400 [[Taiwan]]ese people reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n==South Asian populations==\n\n===Bangladeshis===\nOver 500,000 Bangladeshis live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdnews24.com/economy/2016/10/10/uae-to-consider-taking-bangladesh-workers-in-future|title=UAE to consider taking Bangladesh workers in future - bdnews24.com|website=bdnews24.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/displayarticle.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2010/February/theuae_February665.xml&section=theuae&col=|title=Bangladeshis Observe Martyrs' Day|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref> Expatriates from [[Bangladesh]] in the United Arab Emirates form one of the largest communities along with others hailing from the [[Indian subcontinent]]. They are spread out over the various [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]] of the country, with many based in Dubai and [[Abu Dhabi]]. A sizeable number of the South Asian labour force in the UAE is from Bangladesh. In the fiscal year 2005-2006, remittances from Bangladeshis were marked up to US$512.6M.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200609/04/eng20060904_299331.html|title=People's Daily Online  -- Expatriate Bangladeshis in UAE remit more money home|last=english@peopledaily.com.cn|website=english.peopledaily.com.cn}}</ref>\n\nA number of Bangladeshi-curriculum schools operate in the UAE, including the [[Shaikh Khalifa Bin Zayed Bangladesh Islamia School]] in Abu Dhabi.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n===Bhutanese===\nMost Bhutanese nationals in the UAE are labour force and service industry workers. Employ Bhutan Overseas is a Bhutanese government-authorized employment agency that sends Bhutanese workers to the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.employbhutanoverseas.com/|title=Home|work=Employ Bhutan Overseas|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Indians===\n{{main|Indians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Nepalese===\nNepalese in the United Arab Emirates are a large community numbering around 125,258; of these, 75,000 are in [[Dubai]], some 30,000 in [[Abu Dhabi]] remaining are spread out over the northern [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]]. As per IOM Report of 2012-14, most of [[Nepalese people|Nepalese]] migrant workers in [[UAE]] number up to 97,874.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://nepal.iom.int/jupgrade/index.php/en/press-room/18-topic-details/115-art-latest-news-28|title=Total hill and Madheshi migrant workers in UAE}}</ref>\nOut of the population, half are labour migrants in the construction sector, while others work in hospitality and security services (as security guards). Nepalese security guards are popular in the UAE for their trustworthiness.<ref>{{citation|last=Abdul Kader|first=Binsal|title=Number of Nepalese in UAE steady|periodical=Gulf News|date=17 May 2010|accessdate=17 July 2010|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/number-of-nepalese-in-uae-steady-1.627869}}</ref> There are also some skilled professionals.\n\nAs part of curbing illegal migration, the UAE made new amendments to visit visa regulations in 2008. According to experts, the changes were likely to affect Nepalese the most, along with Indians and Pakistanis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/new-uae-visa-rules-likely-to-affect-indians-pakistanis-and-nepalis_10075731.html|title=New UAE visa rules likely to affect Indians, Pakistanis and Nepalis|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistanis===\n{{main|Pakistanis in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Sri Lankans===\nSri Lankans in the United Arab Emirates have grown to a population of over 300,000;<ref>{{cite news |last=Abdul Kade |first=Binsal |title=Sri Lankan expats to get free IT and English language training |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/sri-lankan-expats-to-get-free-it-and-english-language-training-1.975908|newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AG\">{{cite news |title=Sri Lankans in UAE asked to register themselves |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/sri-lankans-in-uae-asked-to-register-themselves-1.28877 |newspaper=Gulf News |date=24 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711135608/http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/sri-lankans-in-uae-asked-to-register-themselves-1.28877 |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> they mostly form the country's large foreign labour force. In 2009, community members were urged to register themselves. A lack of community data has often resulted in difficulties in reaching out to the community at the time of major announcements, rules and regulation.<ref name=\"AG\"/> Most expatriates from Sri Lanka, along with other immigrants from the [[Indian subcontinent]], tend to be found in [[Dubai]], although sizeable communities are existent in [[Abu Dhabi]], [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]], [[Al-Ain]] and [[Ras al-Khaimah]].\n\nThere is a huge demand for Sri Lankan Quantity Surveyors, Commercial Managers and Contract Administrators in ever expanding UAE construction industry. They are usually highly paid due to the high demand for their quality of professionalism. Not only them, there are lots of Sri Lankans well off in UAE banking and hotel/tourism industries.\n\n==Southeast Asian populations==\n===Burmese===\nAround 10,000 reside in the UAE.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/myanmar-violence-traps-rohingya-bangladesh-border-170826101215439.html|title=Myanmar troops open fire on civilians fleeing attacks|work=Al Jazeera|date=27 August 2017|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cambodians===\nAround 7,600 [[Khmer people]] reside and work in [[Dubai]], [[Sharjah]], and [[Abu Dhabi]].\n\n===Filipinos===\n{{main|Filipinos in the United Arab Emirates}}\nAn estimated 700,000 expatriates from the [[Philippines]] live or work in the UAE. Particularly in [[Dubai]], [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Al-Ain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-filipinos-rejoice-as-cebu-pacific-arrives-with-cheap-deals-2013-01-21-1.491817|title=Dubai Filipinos rejoice as Cebu Pacific arrives with cheap deals|first=Bindu Suresh|last=Rai|date=21 January 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Indonesians===\n{{main|Indonesians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Laotians===\nAround 62,500 [[Lao people|Laotians]] living and working in the United Arab Emirates.\n\n===Malaysians===\nThere were 6,000 Malaysians living and working in the United Arab Emirates as of 2010. Most are found in [[Dubai]] and can be seen working with foreign and local companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2010/1/25/nation/5536408&sec=nation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128011812/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2010%2F1%2F25%2Fnation%2F5536408&sec=nation|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 January 2010|title=Looking to the Middle East|work=The Star Online|date=25 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In addition, a small number of Malaysian pilots work for the Abu Dhabi-based [[Etihad Airways]]. {{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n===Singaporeans===\nThere is a small community of Singaporeans in the UAE numbering around 2,100, the largest Singaporean community in the Middle East.<ref name=\"Singaporeans\"/> The community includes Singaporean Malays, [[Chinese Singaporean]]s and [[Indian Singaporeans]]. Dubai has three Singaporean expatriate clubs: the Singapore Business Council (SBC), Singapore Malay-Muslim Group (SMG) and the Singapore Women's Group (SWG).<ref name=\"Singaporeans\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/singapore-embassy-in-uae-hosts-national-day-celebrations-1.1231843|title=Singapore Embassy in UAE hosts National Day celebrations|first=Staff|last=Report|date=16 September 2013|publisher=}}</ref> Many Singaporeans visit the UAE for tourism or transit through its airports.\n\n===Thais===\nThais in the United Arab Emirates are based predominantly in [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Dubai]]. Smaller populations also live in the northern [[Emirates of the United Arab Emirates|emirates]]. A significant number of Thais work in the construction sector. In 2006, there were some 3,500 Thai workers in Dubai alone. This figure jumped to 6,500 in 2007 and recent numbers are predicted to be as high as 8,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/opinions/columnists/the-missing-pillar-in-thai-gulf-ties-1.103442|title=The missing pillar in Thai-Gulf ties|first=Abdullah Al Madani, Special to Gulf|last=News|date=4 May 2008|access-date=31 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718084949/http://gulfnews.com/opinions/columnists/the-missing-pillar-in-thai-gulf-ties-1.103442|archive-date=18 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The UAE and Thailand have signed a memorandum of understanding aimed at protecting the rights of Thai workers living and working in the UAE.\n\n=== Vietnamese ===\nMore than 5,000 Vietnamese nationals and people of Vietnamese descent live in the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/government/169253/na-chairwoman-s-uae-trip-to-improve-vietnam-s-stature.html|title=NA Chairwoman's UAE trip to improve Vietnam's stature - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other populations==\n===Afghans===\nAbout 150,000 [[Afghans]] live in the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/afghans-take-hope-from-uae-s-achievements-1.1112640|title=Afghans take hope from UAE's achievements|first=Shafaat Shahbandari, Staff|last=Reporter|date=30 November 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nExpatriate Afghan businessmen, traders, and entrepreneurs formed an Afghan Business Council of Dubai in 2005. The organisation strives to develop economic, cultural, and social relations between Afghanistan and the UAE, and to promote the interests of the Dubai Afghan business community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcdxb.com/|title=Afghan Business Council|website=www.abcdxb.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Afghan community in the UAE forms the second largest diaspora of Afghans after the [[United States]].\n\n===Albanians===\nAround 50 to 3000 [[Albania]]ns reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Americans===\n{{Main|Americans in the United Arab Emirates}}\nAmericans in the United Arab Emirates form one of the largest Western expatriate communities in the [[UAE]]. Over 50,000 United States nationals reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/> The bulk of these live in Dubai while sizable populations are also found in Abu Dhabi. According to statistics produced in 1999, there were 7,500 United States citizens in Abu Dhabi and as many as 9,000 United States citizens in Dubai.<ref>[http://www.overseasdigest.com/amcit_nu2.htm Private American Citizens Residing Abroad] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326040310/http://www.overseasdigest.com/amcit_nu2.htm |date=26 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Argentines===\nArgentines in the United Arab Emirates are 2,000 and form the third largest community of Argentines in the Middle East (after Lebanon and Israel) and are mainly expatriates (bankers, pilots, stewards and technicians  {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} working with the two main airlines in the country) and professional footballers playing in the [[UAE Football League]]. Even the legendary Argentine player [[Diego Maradona]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/maradona-named-as-coach-at-al-wasl.aspx?pageID=238&nID=7144&NewsCatID=364|title=Maradona named as coach at Al-Wasl - MIDEAST|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News - LEADING NEWS SOURCE FOR TURKEY AND THE REGION}}</ref> was an expat for a while in UAE.\n\n===Azerbaijanis===\nAzerbaijanis in United Arab Emirates number around 12,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diaspora.az|title=Diaspora.az|website=Diaspora.az}}</ref> This figure however, only includes Azerbaijani nationals and not ethnic Azerbaijanis from Iran, otherwise the figure would be much higher. The Azerbaijanis mostly live in Dubai, Abu Dhabi and Sharjah.\n\n===Armenians===\nArmenians in United Arab Emirates number around 3,000.<ref>{{in lang|hy}} [http://encyclopedia.am/pages.php?bId=1&hId=71&sWord=Array \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0565\u0580\u0568 \u0531\u0544\u0537-\u0578\u0582\u0574]. Retrieved 7 July 2012.</ref>\n\n===Australians===\n{{Main|Australians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAustralians in the United Arab Emirates consist of 7,000 expatriates, half of whom live in the capital of Abu Dhabi (3,500) and the other half of whom live in  Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southern-cross-group.org/archives/Statistics/Numbers_of_Australians_Overseas_in_2001_by_Region_Feb_2002.pdf|title=Statistics - Numbers of Australians Overseas in 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720101723/http://www.southern-cross-group.org/archives/Statistics/Numbers_of_Australians_Overseas_in_2001_by_Region_Feb_2002.pdf|archivedate=20 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAustralians have been attracted by the lifestyle Dubai offers, including the wealth of outdoor activities for their families.<ref>[http://gulfnews.com/in-focus/australia/living-it-up-in-dubai-1.28037 Gulfnews: InFocus Australia - Living it up in Dubai] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020200022/http://gulfnews.com/in-focus/australia/living-it-up-in-dubai-1.28037 |date=20 October 2012 }}</ref> However, their population fell in 2009 due to the downturn in the [[economy of Dubai]], as retrenched Australian expatriates with underwater real-estate loans fled the country to avoid [[debtor's prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/debt-laden-jobless-aussies-flee-dubai/news-story/76649c215e51f9e8d2417e142586a13a|title=Debt-laden jobless Aussies flee Dubai|date=9 May 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Dubai, Australian and New Zealander expatriates joined together to set up the Australia New Zealand Association, which aims to provide mutual support for their communities in the entire UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/australian-expatriates-celebrate-national-day-1.46995|title=Australian expatriates celebrate national day|first=Kevin Scott, Staff|last=Reporter|date=26 January 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian International School in [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]] is an established international school, catering to much of the Australian community. The school's education system and syllabus is [[Queensland]]-curriculum based.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ais.ae/|title=Australian International School|website=www.ais.ae}}</ref>\n\n===Austrians===\nThe UAE is home to 1,800 Austrians, and 36 Austrian companies operate directly in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/politics/uae-urges-austria-to-change-stance-on-euro-visa-free-travel|title=UAE urges Austria to change stance on euro visa-free travel - The National|access-date=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821060223/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/politics/uae-urges-austria-to-change-stance-on-euro-visa-free-travel|archive-date=21 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \nJumeirah Park in Dubai, as of 2019, is the preferred neighborhood for Austrians living in Dubai.\n\n===Belarusians===\nAround 2,500 [[Belarus]]ians reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Belgians===\n3,000 Belgians reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Bosnians===\nA community of Bosnian expatriates lives in the UAE, numbering from 1,000 to 2,000.<ref name=\"List\"/> In 2014, the Bosnian community of Dubai provided humanitarian aid to affectees of floods in Bosnia and also in Serbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/serbian-and-bosnian-communities-rally-aid-for-flood-victims-1.1336117|title=Serbian and Bosnian communities rally aid for flood victims|first=Janice Ponce de Leon, Staff|last=Reporter|date=21 May 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Brazilians===\nBrazilians in the United Arab Emirates are the third largest community of Brazilians in the Middle East (after Israel and Lebanon) and are mainly expatriates and professional footballers. In 2002, up to 235 Brazilians were reported  living in the country ([[Abu Dhabi]] and Dubai).<ref>[http://www.acontece.com/?act=25&actB=6 Estimates of Brazilians living abroad by region] (''Portuguese'')</ref> These figures increased ten-fold, with data disclosed by the embassy of Brazil in Abu Dhabi putting the number as high as 2,000 by 2010.<ref name=\"AN\">{{cite news|url=http://www2.anba.com.br/noticia_especiais.kmf?cod=10525305|title=Brazilian immigrants in the Arab world|work=Brazil-Arab News Agency|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204190550/http://www2.anba.com.br/noticia_especiais.kmf?cod=10525305|archive-date=4 December 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most immigrants are pilots, stewards and technicians working with the two main airlines in the country, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] and [[Etihad Airways|Etihad]]. The Emirates airline alone has over 100 Brazilian pilots and 600 [[Flight attendant|stewards]].<ref name=\"AN\"/> Brazil also has a large business presence in the UAE, with representative offices for several [https://www.makinabook.com/ construction companies], exporters and banks.\nFootballers from Brazil top the list of foreigners playing in the [[UAE Football League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.emirates247.com/sports/football/13-brazilians-in-uae-football-clubs-2010-09-15-1.291242|title=13 Brazilians in UAE football clubs|work=[[Emirates Business 24/7]]|date=15 September 2010}}</ref> The UAE remains a popular touring destination for many Brazilians and airlines provide links between both countries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwood |first=Gemma |date=23 March 2008 |title=Brazilians to flock to Dubai |url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/brazilians-flock-dubai-52059.html |work=[[Arabian Business]]}}</ref>\n\n===British===\nBritish presence in the country dates back to the 19th century, when the region was a protectorate. In 2012, there were an estimated 240,000 Britons living in the country, representing the largest [[Western world|western community]] in the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/news-comment/the-other-special-relationship-the-uae-and-the-uk|title=The other special relationship: the UAE and the UK - The National|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to 2008, there were 120,000 expatriates holding British passports in the UAE. However, after the [[Late-2000s recession in Europe|2008 UK recession]] another 120,000 British nationals emigrated to the UAE to find work, doubling their numbers within a period of just four years. Most Britons took their entire families with them.{{fact|date=September 2019}} The main localities where British citizens are based include Dubai, [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Sharjah (emirate)|Sharjah]]. A number of Britons working in the UAE are high-salary white-collar job professionals. Probationary work permits are valid for up to three months for Britons. In the 2010 UK general elections, following a drop in sterling, UAE-based British expats were seen taking advantage by sending increased funds back home to the [[UK]], with the number of [[United Arab Emirates dirham|dirham]] trades flowing back to the UK rising by over 40 percent in two days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/588002-uk-expats-take-advantage-of-weak-sterling|title=UK expats take advantage of weak sterling|publisher=|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515123824/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/588002-uk-expats-take-advantage-of-weak-sterling|archive-date=15 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Bulgarians===\nAround 7,000 [[Bulgaria]]ns live in the UAE, the largest population of Bulgarian people in the Arab World.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulgaria-news.bg/category/world/tourism/article/post1110.html|title=\u0429\u0415 \u041f\u0420\u0418\u0412\u041b\u0418\u0427\u0410\u041c\u0415 \u0422\u0423\u0420\u0418\u0421\u0422\u0418 \u041e\u0422 \u041e\u0410\u0415 \u0427\u0420\u0415\u0417 \u0414\u0418\u0420\u0415\u041a\u0422\u041d\u0418 \u041f\u041e\u041b\u0415\u0422\u0418|first=Toxic Media|last=Ltd.|website=www.bulgaria-news.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nazmibaycin.com|title=www.nazmibaycin.com|first=\u0413\u0438\u043c\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0437\u044a\u043c \u0441\u0435 \u0432\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0438 \u0432|last=Editor|date=15 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref> They mostly live in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plovdivmedia.com/6345.html|title=- www.PlovdivMedia.com|website=www.plovdivmedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloomstart.eu/bg/index.php?action=addon_news_article&id=56 |title=\u0412 \u0442\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u044f\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430  |accessdate=6 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417113810/http://www.bloomstart.eu/bg/index.php?action=addon_news_article&id=56 |archivedate=17 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Canadians===\n{{see also|Canadians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nAround 40,000 Canadians live in the United Arab Emirates as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/visa/canada-may-limit-services-for-dual-citizens-1.1277888|title=Canada may limit services for dual citizens|first=Mick O\u2019Reilly Senior Associate|last=Editor|date=15 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/business/story.html?id=71a7f906-61d3-4be2-b4f3-7eae5c8df15f&p=1 Dubai Mighty Camels playing our game - Canada.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007015148/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/business/story.html?id=71a7f906-61d3-4be2-b4f3-7eae5c8df15f&p=1 |date=7 October 2015 }}</ref> There is a Canadian Club in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubforcanadians-dubai.com/|title=ClubForCanadiansDubai \u2013 Just another WordPress site|website=www.clubforcanadians-dubai.com}}</ref>\n\n===Caribbeans===\nThe Caribbean community in UAE numbers around 2,000 as of 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Celebrating-Ja-in-Dubai_17270367|title=Celebrating Ja in Dubai|first=Jamaica Observer|last=Limited|website=Jamaica Observer}}</ref> which is an increase since 2006 when it barely numbered 100. The majority of them are [[Jamaica]]ns, and a few dozen Jamaican pilots are presently working for the Emirates airline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/heritage-culture/cool-and-caribbean-1.24564|title=Cool and Caribbean!|first=Shalaka|last=Paradkar|date=4 May 2006|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nationwideradiojm.com/jamaicans-languishing-in-dubai-prison/|title=Jamaicans Languishing in Dubai Prison - Nationwide 90FM - Jamaica|website=nationwideradiojm.com}}</ref>\n\n===Chileans===\nAround 270 [[Chile]]ans live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Colombians===\n{{see also|Colombian people in the United Arab Emirates}}\nOver 14,000 Colombians live in the [[United Arab Emirates]], primarily in [[Dubai]]. Is one of the biggest growing communities in the country, and is the second Latin American community after Brazilians. They work in the tourism sector in Dubai, as footballers.\n\n===Croatians===\nOver 500 Croatians are currently living in the UAE, primarily in Dubai. The community is growing. Migration occurred in two waves, with the first wave taking place 15 years ago and the latest and larger wave comprising recent migrants. Croatians can be found working as cooks, stewards, waiters and in white-collar positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatiaweek.com/croatian-community-growing-in-dubai/|title=Croatian Community Growing In Dubai|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Cubans===\nA small Cuban community is present in Dubai. The population has increased over the years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubaminrex.cu/en/cubans-living-dubai-meet-cuban-ambassador|title=Cubans living in Dubai meet with Cuban Ambassador - CubaMINREX<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402172803/http://www.cubaminrex.cu/en/cubans-living-dubai-meet-cuban-ambassador|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/cubans-in-uae-see-no-changes-with-power-transfer-1.248243|title=Cubans in UAE see no changes with power transfer|first=Emmanuelle Landais, Staff|last=Reporter|date=31 July 2006|publisher=}}</ref> Cuban [[cigar]]s are popular in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/the-life/cigar-smokers-hold-fierce-to-tradition-in-the-uae|title=Cigar smokers hold fierce to tradition in the UAE - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/features/cigar-sales-in-the-uae-light-up-1.1030625|title=Cigar sales in the UAE light up|first=Mick O'Reilly, Senior Associate|last=Editor|date=1 June 2012|publisher=}}</ref> Cuban food and salsa clubs are available in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ritmo-de-havana.com/about-us/|title=About - Ritmo de Havana|access-date=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009185028/http://www.ritmo-de-havana.com/about-us/|archive-date=9 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Cypriots===\nAs many as 1,000 [[Cyprus|Cypriots]] live in the UAE. They are mainly involved in the construction and trading industry. Others work as pilots and aeronautical engineers with local airlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/tourism/emiratis-visa-free-travel-to-europe-applauded-by-cyprus|title=Emiratis' visa-free travel to Europe applauded by Cyprus - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Czechs===\nAround 1,500 [[Czechs]] reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Danes===\nAs of 2010, their number was around 2,000, up from just 400 since 2005.<ref>[http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100422/NATIONAL/704219884/1010/rss Danes to reopen embassy in Abu Dhabi: The National (UAE)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223070044/http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20100422%2FNATIONAL%2F704219884%2F1010%2Frss |date=23 February 2014 }}</ref> The [[Danes|Danish]] community of Dubai has founded a cultural organisation known as ''Danes in Dubai'', which aims at fostering relations between Denmark and the UAE.<ref>[http://www.danesindubai.com/script/site/page.asp?artid=25&cat_id=27 Danes in Dubai - Official homepage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708223621/http://www.danesindubai.com/script/site/page.asp?artid=25&cat_id=27 |date=8 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Dominicans===\nAround 2,000 to 3,000 [[Dominican Republic|Dominicans]] reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Dutch===\nCurrently there is a growing population of Dutch nationals. As of 2011 members of the community number at 4,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/society/dutch-consulate-opens-newoffice-in-dubai-marina-1.918111|title=Dutch consulate opens newoffice in Dubai Marina|first=Janice Ponce de Leon, Staff|last=Reporter|date=25 October 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Fijians===\nA small Fijian community numbering in the hundreds exists in the UAE, based in Dubai, Abu Dhabi, Al Ain and other places.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/lifestyle/house-home/were-the-only-fijians-in-rak|title='We're the only Fijians in RAK' - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mailife.com.fj/president-visits-fijian-community-in-the-emirates/|title=President visits Fijian community in the Emirates - Mai Life Magazine|website=www.mailife.com.fj|date=21 May 2014}}</ref> They include both native Fijians and [[Indians in Fiji|Indo-Fijians]]. New job opportunities have prompted some Fijians to migrate to the UAE. Most Fijians in the UAE can be found working in retail, tourism and hospitality, as nurses,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Connell|first1=John|title=The Global Health Care Chain: From the Pacific to the World|date=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135912826|pages=111, 112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lkuSAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 }}</ref> pilots,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/fiji-interested-in-airline-partnership-with-uae|title=Fiji interested in airline partnership with UAE - The National|publisher=}}</ref> seafarers teachers, hotel workers, sportspeople and in other jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijilive.com/news/2013/02/new-uae-job-opportunities-for-fijians/52044.Fijilive|title=New UAE job opportunities for Fijians<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028060602/http://fijilive.com/news/2013/02/new-uae-job-opportunities-for-fijians/52044.Fijilive|archivedate=28 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/10/14/fiji-embassy-uae-hosts-first-fiji-day-celebrations/|title=FIJI EMBASSY UAE HOSTS FIRST FIJI DAY CELEBRATIONS - THE JET - Fiji's First Community Newspaper|last=admin|access-date=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106123809/http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/10/14/fiji-embassy-uae-hosts-first-fiji-day-celebrations/|archive-date=6 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/08/06/an-interview-with-dr-robin-nair-fijis-envoy-in-the-middle-east/|title=An Interview with Dr Robin Nair \u2013 Fiji's Envoy in the Middle East - THE JET - Fiji's First Community Newspaper|last=admin|access-date=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323102456/http://www.thejetnewspaper.com/2014/08/06/an-interview-with-dr-robin-nair-fijis-envoy-in-the-middle-east/|archive-date=23 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=224111|title=Fiji Times Online : Page Not Found|website=www.fijitimes.com|access-date=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020220816/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=224111|archive-date=20 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Fijian community in Abu Dhabi convenes celebrations for Fiji Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/10/celebration-in-abu-dhabi/|title=Celebration In Abu Dhabi - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Finns===\nFinns in the United Arab Emirates form a community of 1,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finland.ae/public/default.aspx?nodeid=42992&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI|title=Embassy - Embassy of Finland, Abu Dhabi : Embassy|website=www.finland.ae |language=fi}}</ref>\n\n===French===\nOver 10,000 [[France|French]] people live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mofa.gov.ae/mofa_english/portal/b04da0f7-4a48-4358-9999-68fa599464a2.aspx|title=His Highness Sheikh Mohammed Bin Rashid receives French PM<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617130822/http://mofa.gov.ae/mofa_english/portal/b04da0f7-4a48-4358-9999-68fa599464a2.aspx|archivedate=17 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/french-website-helps-uae-residents-find-la-vie-en-rose-1.96004|title=French website helps UAE residents find la vie en rose|first=Kevin Scott, Staff|last=Reporter|date=2 April 2008|publisher=}}</ref> The French maintain numerous community organisations, schools, restaurants, and academies throughout the country. According to various statistics, the French population of UAE has been growing at a rate of 5% a year.<ref name=\"A\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.justlanded.com/just-landed-news/guide-de-dubai-en-francais-expatries/|title=Dubai Guide in French / Guide de Duba\u00ef fran\u00e7ais|publisher=}}</ref> France also has an industrial presence with close to 300 French enterprises and businesses. Roughly half of these are in Dubai.<ref name=\"A\"/>\n\n===Germans===\nGermans in the United Arab Emirates number 10,000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/community/features/3686-german-expats-in-dubai|title=German expats in Dubai|website=Time Out Dubai}}</ref> found across major cities of the country.\n\nThe UAE has three German schools:\n\n* [[Deutsche Schule Abu Dhabi]]\n* [[Deutsche Schule Sharjah]]\n* [[Deutsche Internationale Schule Dubai]]\n\n===Greeks===\nOver 5,000 Greeks live in the UAE, mostly in [[Dubai]].<ref name=\"List\"/><ref name=\"MFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gr/www.mfa.gr/en-US/Policy/Geographic+Regions/Mediterranean+-+Middle+East/Bilateral+Relations/United+Arab+Emirates/|title=Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Greece) - United Arab Emirates|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"EG\"/> They are predominantly professionals in white-collar industry, serving in various positions such as executives and businessmen.<ref name=\"MFA\"/> Many of them have been living in the country for more than 20 years, while every year an increasing number of newcomers are setting up in the UAE.<ref name=\"EG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emiratesgreeks.com/news.php?op=details&id=71|title=Emirates Greeks - Embassy of Greece in the UAE honours economic and commercial partners|website=www.emiratesgreeks.com|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710191018/http://www.emiratesgreeks.com/news.php?op=details&id=71|archive-date=10 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition, more than 120 Greek companies of different sectors currently operate in the country.<ref name=\"EG\"/>\n\nThe Greek community is organised through social circles. There are two (informal) Greek schools, whose teachers are posted and managed by the [[Minister of Education (Greece)|Greek Ministry of Education]].\n\nThe [[Greek Orthodox Church]] of the UAE is under the jurisdiction of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Antioch Patriarchate]]; the current bishop is the Metropolitan of Bagdad and Kuwait Constantine. There is a Greek Orthodox Church of St Nikolaos in [[Abu Dhabi]].  Prior to its construction, there existed no Greek church in the UAE and the community had to use other churches for their services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyfrappe.com/Home/tabid/36/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/58/Default.aspx|title=Construction of Greek Orthodox Church to begin in UAE: Daily Frappe|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119153123/http://www.dailyfrappe.com/Home/tabid/36/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/58/Default.aspx|archivedate=19 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Hungarians===\nAccording to a Hungarian aviation official, \"there is a sizeable Hungarian community already working in the UAE\" and many Hungarians travel to Dubai for tourism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.routes-news.com/tourism-and-destinations/4-tourism-destinations/1774-a-route-in-focus-budapest-dubai|title=Routes News - A route in focus: Budapest\u2013Dubai<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221103329/http://www.routes-news.com/tourism-and-destinations/4-tourism-destinations/1774-a-route-in-focus-budapest-dubai|archivedate=21 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=February 2016}}\n\n===Iranians===\n{{Main|Iranians in the United Arab Emirates}}\nIranians in the UAE number 400,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/region/iran/iranian-expats-in-the-uae-see-polls-as-a-pointless-exercise-1.988403 |title=Iranian expats in the UAE see polls as a pointless exercise |accessdate=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303195423/http://gulfnews.com/news/region/iran/iranian-expats-in-the-uae-see-polls-as-a-pointless-exercise-1.988403 |archivedate=3 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> to half a million.\n\n===Irish===\nMore than 8,000 Irish expatriates live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/desert-dreaming-29384974.html|title=Desert Dreaming - Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/irish-youth-flock-to-uae-in-search-of-better-job-opportunities-2013-03-02-1.497046|title=Irish youth flock to UAE in search of better job opportunities|first=Majorie van|last=Leijen|date=2 March 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/economy/irish-minister-jimmy-deenihan-makes-uae-first-stop-on-post-appointment-tour|title=Irish minister Jimmy Deenihan makes UAE first stop on post-appointment tour - The National|publisher=}}</ref> There is an Abu Dhabi Irish Society and a Dubai Irish Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/world/other-world/why-irish-eyes-are-smiling-in-the-uae-1.1304746|title=Why Irish eyes are smiling in the UAE|first=Marianna Wright Special to Gulf|last=News|date=16 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Israelis===\nThe United Arab Emirates does not recognise Israel due to the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict|Palestinian conflict]], and therefore Israeli passport-holders cannot legally enter the UAE. Restrictions were tightened against the entry of Israeli citizens following the [[assassination of Mahmoud Al-Mabhouh]] in Dubai, which was blamed on Israeli intelligence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/israelis-no-longer-allowed-in-dubai-after-hamas-hit-1.263926|title=Israelis No Longer Allowed in Dubai After Hamas Hit|first=News|last=Agencies|date=1 March 2010|publisher=|via=Haaretz|newspaper=Haaretz}}</ref> However, there are [[History of the Jews in the United Arab Emirates|Jewish expatriates in the UAE]], and Israelis with [[dual citizenship]] who live, visit, and work in the UAE as citizens of other countries.<ref name=\"Israelis\"/> Some Israeli companies conduct business in the UAE indirectly through third parties.<ref name=\"Israelis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Israelis-doing-business-in-Dubai-will-wait-out-storm|title=Israelis doing business in Dubai will wait out storm|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Italians===\n{{main|Italians in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\n===Latvians===\nAbout 300 Latvians live in the UAE. To serve the community, Latvia opened an embassy in Abu Dhabi in September 2014, its first diplomatic mission in the [[Persian Gulf]] region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/uae-latvian-community-will-benefit-from-embassy-opening|title=UAE Latvian community will benefit from embassy opening - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Mexicans===\nApproximately 3,000 Mexican citizens live and work in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/first-mexican-embassy-in-uae-inaugurated|title=First Mexican Embassy in UAE inaugurated - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Moldovans===\nA relatively large population of Moldovans live in the UAE, especially in Sharjah. Abu Dhabi and Dubai have a joint population of around 22,000 Moldovans.\n\n===Macedonians===\nMacedonians are the sixth-largest Yugoslav and ex-Yugoslav (Balkanic) population in the UAE and in the whole Arab World.\n\n===Montenegrins===\nThe Montenegrins are the seventh-largest Yugoslav and ex-Yugoslav (Balcanic) population in the UAE and in the whole Arab World.\n\n===New Zealanders===\nNew Zealanders in the UAE number around 4,000,<ref>[http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091106/NATIONAL/711059864/1023/rss From F1 to FIFA, the show rolls on] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222010201/http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20091106%2FNATIONAL%2F711059864%2F1023%2Frss |date=22 February 2014 }}</ref> the overwhelming majority of whom are based in Dubai. A number of entrepreneurs from New Zealand are attracted towards the work and business opportunities offered in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unlimited.co.nz/unlimited.nsf/default/eye-of-the-storm|title=Eye of the storm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717134415/http://unlimited.co.nz/unlimited.nsf/default/eye-of-the-storm|archivedate=17 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2007, more than 700 New Zealanders moved to the UAE permanently or for long term.<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10512314\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10512314 |title=Desert jewel a rough diamond |author=Smith, Jacqueline |date=25 May 2008 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=11 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe New Zealand community is involved in numerous cultural events, get-togethers and organisations. In Dubai, expatriate New Zealanders joined Australians to form the Australia New Zealand Association, which aims to provide support to society members and expatriates over the entire country.\n\n===Nicaraguans===\nThe Nicaraguan community in the UAE is rather small. As of 2017 less than 5 expatriates live in the UAE, the majority of them in Dubai Marina.\n\n===Norwegians===\n1,500-2,000 Norwegians live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/norwegians-mark-195th-independence-anniversary-1.69088|title=Norwegians mark 195th independence anniversary|first=Kevin Scott, Staff|last=Reporter|date=18 May 2009|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Peruvians===\nAround 300 [[Peru]]vians live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Poles===\n2,000 Poles live in UAE, the largest Polish population in the Arab World.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/polish-expats-praise-freedom-given-by-uae-1.143306|title=Polish expats praise freedom given by UAE|first=Binsal Abdul Kader, Staff|last=Reporter|date=13 November 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Romanians===\n6,000 Romanians live in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.incont.ro/joburi-strainatate/atrasi-de-mirajul-emiratelor-5-000-de-romani-muncesc-in-dubai-pentru-cateva-mii-de-euro-pe-luna.html|title=Atrasi de mirajul Emiratelor. 5.000 de romani muncesc in Dubai pentru cateva mii de euro pe luna|last=incont|publisher=}}</ref> The majority of them are professionals, holding graduate or postgraduate qualifications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/romanians-look-to-boost-ties-with-uae-1.149003|title=Romanians look to boost ties with UAE|first=Binsal Abdul Kader, Staff|last=Reporter|date=13 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Russians===\nA sizable [[Russians]] community lives in the UAE\u2014typically having moved to the country for job opportunities and the year-round sunny weather.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\nAccording to Consul General of The Russian Federation, as many as 10,000 Russian expatriates and overall above 55,000 Russian speakers from CIS (former Soviet Republics) countries live throughout the country, with the majority having made Dubai and Northern Emirates their home.<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/business/russians-feel-at-home-in-uae/|title=Russians feel at home in UAE|work=[[Russia Today]]|date=9 September 2007}}</ref>\nThe UAE is also a popular visiting destination, with above 2,000,000 tourists from Russia & CIS visiting the country each year.<ref name=\"RT\"/>\nA number of business and cultural groups operate within the community, such as [http://www.rbcdubai.org/ Russian Business Council in Dubai and Northern Emirates], which is under the umbrella of the [[Dubai Chamber of Commerce and Industry]]; Russian Cultural Club in the American University of Sharjah; Russian Women Union ''Rossiyanka'', to name a few.\nThe Dubai Russian Private School is a secondary school that uses a curriculum approved by the Russian Ministry of Education and caters to the Russian speaking community needs. After-school activities and extra curricular classes are also available, e.g., dance lessons for adults and children at [https://dubaidance.com/our-history/ \"Dance For You\" studio].\nA number of Russian-language publications operate in the country: [[:ru:\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u042d\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0442\u044b (\u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b)|Russian Emirates magazine]] (dedicated to the luxury lifestyle and fashion), Business Emirates magazine (dedicate to the property, business and investments; the official publication of the Russian Business Council), as well as East Sprigs UAE Travel Guide book for Russian speaking tourists and visitors of the UAE, printed & published by the Russian Emirates Publishing House and actively promoted and circulated. There is a \"Russian Radio \u2013 [http://www.autoradio.ae/ Auto Radio U.A.E]\" broadcasting on 103.2 FM all over the UAE. Dubai has often been described as a playground for Russian VIPs, where large portions of property are bought. Some locals insist that as much as half of the Palm Jumeirah, the first of the city's scheduled three man-made islands, which is already handed over, will eventually be owned by Russian speakers.<ref name=\"RT\"/>\n\n===Samoans===\nA very small number of Samoans are present in the UAE. Most Samoans actively play rugby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/knowledge/news/10986-footie-fundraiser|title=Footie fundraiser|website=Time Out Dubai}}</ref> New Zealand-born Samoan rugby player [[Apollo Perelini]] has been based in the UAE for a couple of years, where he coaches at the Elite Sporting Academy in [[Repton School Dubai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/rugbys-tribute-to-tsunami-victims|title=Rugby's tribute to tsunami victims - The National|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Serbs===\n5,000 Serbs live in UAE.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20150711160839/http://www.bqdoha.com/2015/04/uae-population-by-nationality</ref>\n\n===Slovaks===\nAround 1,000 [[Slovaks]] reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Slovenians===\nBetween 100 and 150 [[Slovenia]]ns live in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Spaniards===\nAbout 12,000 Spanish expatriates live in the UAE. A Spanish Business Council has been formed by the expatriate community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/spanish-fans-in-the-uae-expect-team-to-reach-world-cup-quarterfinals-at-least|title=Spanish fans in the UAE expect team to reach World Cup quarterfinals, at least - The National|publisher=}}</ref> The majority of them live in Dubai, followed by Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/biz/inside.asp?xfile=/data/uaebusiness/2013/December/uaebusiness_December270.xml&section=uaebusiness|title=UAE and Spain focus on direct investment, renewable energy|first=Suchitra Steven Samuel|last=(Interview)|website=www.khaleejtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Swedes===\nSwedes in the United Arab Emirates number at over 3,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/gn-focus/sweden/a-meeting-of-minds-1.815780|title=A meeting of minds -GulfNews.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829044340/http://gulfnews.com/gn-focus/sweden/a-meeting-of-minds-1.815780|archivedate=29 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Swiss===\nAround 2,430 [[Switzerland|Swiss]] nationals reside in the UAE.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Turks===\nTurks in the United Arab Emirates are Turkish citizens who live in the United Arab Emirates. In 2014, the population was around 10,000 and increasing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/turks-living-in-the-uae-vote-in-presidential-elections|title=Turks living in the UAE vote in presidential elections - The National|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/general/turkish-community-group-marks-fourth-anniversary-1.636866|title=Turkish community group marks fourth anniversary|first=Ashfaq Ahmed, Chief|last=Reporter|date=5 June 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bilgidubai.info/turkish-community-dubai-english|title=English-Turkish Community Dubai - Dubai|website=www.bilgidubai.info}}</ref> In recent years many Turkish doctors have moved to Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://turkishdoctors.rf.gd|title=Turkish Healthcare Professionals in UAE}}</ref>\n\n===Ukrainians===\nIn 2006 the Ukrainian population was listed at 2,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/heritage-culture/warming-up-1.24650|title=Warming up|first=Shalaka Paradkar, Staff|last=Writer|date=22 June 2006|publisher=}}</ref> More recently, the population grew to 5,000.<ref name=\"List\"/>\n\n===Venezuelans===\n2,580 people living in the UAE have Venezuelan roots. Many Venezuelans work in the oil businesses, due to UAE\u2013Venezuela relations ([[OPEC]]).\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Immigration to the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{United Arab Emirates topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Immigration to}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Expatriates In The United Arab Emirates}}\n[[Category:Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates| ]]\n", "name_user": "CaradhrasAiguo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Consolidate refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expatriates_in_the_United_Arab_Emirates"}
{"title_page": "D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss Sr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox comics creator\n| name          = D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss\n| image = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people.  See [[WP:NONFREE]].  -->\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1947|01|28}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| area          = Artist\n| alias         = \n| notable works = ''[[The Guide to Getting it On]]''\n| awards        = \n| website       = \n}}\n\n'''D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss Sr.''' (born January 28th, 1947) is a writer, editor, illustrator, and art director, primarily within the commercial comic industry. Gross has worked with a number of comic book companies, including [[Marvel Comics]], [[DC Comics]], [[Chaos! Comics]], [[Image Comics]], [[Innovation Publishing]], and has also begun work under his own company, [[Studio G]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.studiogart.net/|title=Studio G - Art and Illustration of Daerick Gross Sr and DW Gross|website=www.studiogart.net|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>, with his son, D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss.<ref name=\":1\" /> He is the visual editor at inDELible Comics, and is also the art director at [http://acpcomics.com/index.html#FG1-3 ACP Comics] working on promotional art, title logos and art direction.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstcomicsnews.com/comic-book-biography-daerick-gross-sr/|title=Comic book Biography: D\u00c6RICK GR\u00d6SS SR. \u2013 First Comics News|website=www.firstcomicsnews.com|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> He specializes in caricature drawings line art drawings, strong color composition, and graphic arrangement.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/d%C3%A6rick-gr%C3%B6ss-sr-1019a311/|title=Linkedin Profile|last=Gr\u00f6ss Sr.|first=D\u00e6rick|date=|website=Linkedin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2008, he lives in [[Simi Valley, California]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nGr\u00f6ss was born in the Dayton suburb of [[Kettering, Ohio|Kettering]], Ohio on January 27th, 1947, and was a comic book fan in early in his youth.<ref name=\":0\" /> He later attended the [[University Of Ohio|University of Ohio]] from 1965-1967 studying art and theatre.<ref name=\":5\" /> He was a member of the [[Fraternity|fraternity,]] [[Phi Kappa Theta]].<ref name=\":0\" /> After feeling dissatisfied with the art instruction at the university, he finished his education in 1969 at the [http://www.educationhq.org/college-201663.php Central Academy of Commercial Art] in [[Cincinnati]], Ohio.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career ===\nAfter graduating, Gr\u00f6ss began working at [[WCPO-TV]] in [[Cincinnati]], Ohio as a live set designer and creator as well as creating visuals for on camera needs for 3 years.<ref name=\":0\" /> Then Gr\u00f6ss joined the [[The Cincinnati Post|Cincinnati Post]] as a staff artist and cartoonist, eventually becoming the [[Art director|Art Directo]]<nowiki/>r of the post, drawing illustrations and helping with page design.<ref name=\":0\" />\n=== [http://www.internationalhero.co.uk/m/marciell.htm Murci\u00e9laga She-Bat] ===\nAfter responding to a bulletin board memo from CFW Magazines, Gr\u00f6ss started his career within the comic book industry with the creation of the character, [http://www.internationalhero.co.uk/m/marciell.htm Murci\u00e9laga She-Bat], a part of the REIKI team in Robo Warriors. After [[DC Comics|DC]] stopped the production [[Batwoman]] comics, Gr\u00f6ss created this latina-mutant character in 1988 within the pages of a karate themed magazine from CFW, Kung-Fu Warriors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.studiogart.net/shebat/comics.html|title=Murcielaga, She-Bat - Past Appearances in Comics - Studio G|website=www.studiogart.net|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref> Despite selling well, CFW dropped She-Bat, and passed the character to [http://www.heroicmultiverse.com/heroicpub/index.php Heroic Publishing.]\n\nIn the early 1990s, two issues of [http://www.internationalhero.co.uk/m/marciell.htm Murci\u00e9laga She-Bat] were published under Heroic Publishing, and issue #3 was published under [[Revolutionary Comics]] for that single issue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.studiogart.net/shebat/index.html|title=Murcielaga, the She-Bat - America's Foremost Latin Superheroine - Studio G|website=www.studiogart.net|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, a mini series featuring Murci\u00e9laga was released as a bilingual flipbook in both spanish and english. Originally three issues, complications at Gr\u00f6ss' company, Studio G, halted progress of the series.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHeroic Publishing has now republished the original 8 issues of She-Bat and has continued publishing new issues of the series.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Innovation Comics ===\nD\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss hand painted covers for [[Innovation Comics|Innovation Comic]]'s adaptation of the [[Anne Rice]] [[The Vampire Lestat|Vampire Lestat Series]] few a volumes of the comics, then additionally penciled and inked for a total of 12 volumes from 1990-91. The series won [[Comicon|Comicon's]] [[Russ Manning Award|Russ Manning award.]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://comicvine.gamespot.com/anne-rices-the-vampire-lestat/4050-21132/object-appearances/4040-26037/|title=Anne Rice's The Vampire Lestat (Volume)|website=Comic Vine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nGr\u00f6ss also worked on the Innovation's comic adaptation of the [[Forbidden Planet]] in 1992 as the cover artist of issues #1-4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicvine.gamespot.com/forbidden-planet/4050-4896/|title=Forbidden Planet (Volume)|website=Comic Vine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Marvel and DC ===\nGr\u00f6ss worked with [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] at the [[X-Men]] office on [[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]] in issues #84 and #88 penciling Nightcrawler.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicvine.gamespot.com/excalibur-84-dark-adapted-eye-soul-sword-trilogy-p/4000-40076/|title=Excalibur #84 - Dark Adapted Eye (Soul Sword Trilogy Part 2) (Issue)|website=Comic Vine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> With Marvel, he joined the Cybercomics project and penciled rendered some stories, specifically Spider-man. Additionally, he worked as an artist on [[X-Men]]: [[Domino (comics)|Domino]] issue #1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicvine.gamespot.com/x-men-domino-1-tpb/4000-667667/|title=X-Men: Domino #1 - TPB (Issue)|website=Comic Vine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nWith [[DC Comics]], Gr\u00f6ss was an artist for [[Batman comics|Batman:]] Two-Face Strikes Twice on issues #1 and #2 in 1993.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://comicvine.gamespot.com/batman-two-face-strikes-twice/4050-26231/object-appearances/4040-26037/|title=Batman: Two-Face Strikes Twice (Volume)|website=Comic Vine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Additional work ===\nWith [[Carnal Comics]], an adult comic book company, Gr\u00f6ss worked on several different series as an artist throughout the 90's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicvine.gamespot.com/porn-star-fantasies-6-surfer-safari-roman-rendezvo/4000-267403/|title=Porn Star Fantasies #6 - Surfer Safari; Roman Rendezvous II (Issue)|website=Comic Vine|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nOne of Gr\u00f6ss\u2019 most well-known works is ''[[The Guide to Getting it On|The Guide To Getting It On]]'' published by [https://openlibrary.org/publishers/Goofy_Foot_Press Goofy Foot Press] as an illustrator with the psychoanalyst and author, [[Paul Joannides (psychoanalyst)|Paul Joannides]]. This book was originally published in 1996, but is currently on its ninth edition. It is an educational sexual manual, outlining various health issues and recommendations associated with sexually active adults. This guide is required reading in over 50 college sex education courses and continues to be printed and taught at schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guide2getting.com/about/|title=About|website=Guide To Getting It On|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nGr\u00f6ss also did some penciling and inking work featured in [[Gay Comix|Gay Comics]] issue #24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.comicbookdb.com/issue.php?ID=97836|title=Gay Comix (Gay Comics) (1980) #24 - Comic Book DB|website=www.comicbookdb.com|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Gr\u00f6ss has illustrated several trading card decks, including the Marvel trading card game, [[OverPower|Overpower]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trollandtoad.com/final-fantasy-more-ccgs/overpower-ccg-sealed-product/marvel-overpower-base-set-booster-box-36-packs-marvel-/150923|title=Marvel Overpower Base Set Booster Box [36 Packs] (Marvel)|last=Toad|first=Troll and|website=TrollAndToad|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> and with [[Fantasy Flight Games]], he created a set of [[Game of Thrones]] playing cards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cardguide.fandom.com/wiki/File:BurningBridges-QoD.jpg|title=BurningBridges-QoD.jpg|website=CardGuide Wiki|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\n== Publishing company ==\nD\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss Sr. founded the company, D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss Studios, creating freelance commercial art and illustration services in 1989. The artist renamed the studio in the early 1990s to [http://www.studiogart.net/ Studio G]. His son, D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss, merged into the company in 1996. Due to a fire in 2001, much of Gr\u00f6ss' work through the company was destroyed prior to that date. It is now an independent publisher of small comics throughout 2000s. The company is now in its third generation of illustrators with Gr\u00f6ss' granddaughter entering the business as well.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThrough Studio G, Gr\u00f6ss has released an assortment of T-Shirt designs featuring his assorted works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thegspotstudio.threadless.com/|title=The G-Spot Studio {{!}} Featuring custom t-shirts, prints, and more|last=Threadless|website=thegspotstudio.threadless.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>  D\u00e6rick Gr\u00f6ss Sr. started a small series of online political cartoons in 2017 featuring the president of the United States, [[Donald Trump]], called ''Trumpy''. The work is a political commentary and [[satire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstcomicsnews.com/category/column/trumpy/|title=Trumpy \u2013 First Comics News|website=www.firstcomicsnews.com|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 1991 ''[[Russ Manning Most Promising Newcomer Award]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hahnlibrary.net/comics/awards/manning.php|title=Comic Book Awards Almanac|last=|first=|date=|website=Hahn Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Contributions ===\n\n==== [[Innovation Comics]] ====\n\n* ''Anne Rice's [[The Vampire Lestat]]'' issues #1-12 (1990-91)\n* ''Anne Rice's [[Interview with the Vampire|Interview With the Vampire]]'' issue #2 (1991)\n* ''Anne Rice's Queen of the Damned'' issue #2 (1991)\n* ''The Vampire Companion'' issues #1-2 (1991)\n* ''Forbidden Planet'' issues #1-4 (1992)\n* Forbidden Planet: The Saga of the Krell issue #1 (1993)\n* ''[[Hero Alliance]]'' issue #17 (1991)\n* ''The Colour of Magic'' issues #1-4 (1991)\n* ''The Shadow of the Torturer'' issues #2-3 (1991)\n* [[Bozo the Clown|Bozo:]] The World's Most Famous Clown vol.1 (1992)\n\n==== [http://www.heroicmultiverse.com/heroicpub/index.php Heroic Publishing] ====\n\n* ''Murci\u00e9laga: She-Bat'' issues #1-5 #8-16 (1993-2017)\n* ''Reiki Warriors Special'' issue #1 (2013)\n* ''Tigress'' issue #3 (1992)\n* ''Lady Arcane'' issues #1-2 (1992)\n* ''League of Champions'' issue #9 (1990)\n* ''Champions Classics'' issue #4 (1992)\n* ''The Adventures of Chrissie Claus'' issue #3 (1991)\n* ''[[Sparkplug 